<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="version">
<PB N="1">
<HEAD>I. THE NORTHERN PROSE VERSION|OF|The Rule of St. Benet.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(Lansdowne MS. 378, British Museum.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="prolog">
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="1b">Asculta, o fili! </P>
<P>Son, Herkyn &thorn;e commandementis of &thorn;e mastir, &amp; lay to|&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>; similarly p. 12, l. 32, p. 13, ll. 9, 36, etc.</NOTE> eere of thy herte, &amp; gladly take And spedily fulfil|&thorn;e warnyng of &thorn;e meke fadir, &thorn;at &thorn;u mai turne a-gayne to|hym by &thorn;e labur of obedience, fra whame &thorn;u had gane by|&thorn;e slewth of inobedience.  Tharfore my worde be now|directe to the, &thorn;at forsakis thy awne lustis &amp; takis &thorn;e ryght|strang &amp; doghty armur of obedience to seryf our lorde|Iesu criste, &thorn;e verrey kyng.  First &thorn;at &thorn;u aske of hym|wid besy prayer alle gude thing &thorn;at &thorn;u begyns to do to be|perfytely endid; &thorn;at he, &thorn;at hase vochyd safe to cownte|vs in &thorn;e nummer of hys sons, be not greuyd ony tyme be|our euyl dedis.  Sa, for soth, it is to obey hym at al tyme|for hys aune gudis &thorn;at ere in vs, &thorn;at he, as a wrath fader,|not alanly diseret vs os not hys sons, Bot also os a dredful|lord, wrathid thoro our<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. o<SUP>r</SUP>.</NOTE> euyl dedys, betake vs to perpetual|payne os ful wykkyd seruandis, whylk wald not folow|hym to blis.</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="1">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="2a">primum capitulum.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>primum</I>; one of the downstrokes required to|make <I>-mum</I> is missing.&mdash;After <I>capitulum</I>, and in several places on|the seven first pages, the sign -:- is used instead of a plain stop.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Exurgamus ergo.</P>
<P>In &thorn;is first sentence bidis us sain benet &thorn;at we be|wakande, and bidis we sal rise, &thorn;at es of ure sinne, als|it es writen, and &thorn;at yure ehin be opin, and yure herte[s],<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>yures herte</I>; cf. p. 2, l. 2.</NOTE>|til godis brih[t]nes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>brihnes</I>.</NOTE> Godis uoice &thorn;at &yogh;e here and under-stande<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS.|<I>under. c. / stande.</I>  At the end of several lines on the nine first|leaves (but never afterwards) some strokes, sometimes apparently|forming real letters or words, are added simply in order to give to|the lines their full length.</NOTE>
<PB N="2">|it, als it sais: "Hodie si uocem eius&mdash;Yef ye &thorn;e uoice of|god herd o day, yure hertis ware noht hard; it munde|ma &thorn;am neis;" Als haly writ says: "Qui habet aures<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>aur/res</I>.</NOTE>|audiendi, audiat&mdash;&THORN;at erin hauis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between <I>erin</I> and <I>hauis</I> there is a blank|large enough for about five letters; it seems to have been left|thus by the scribe.</NOTE> herkins wat &thorn;e haly spirt|sais in haly writ."  wat sais he? "Cumis to me, I sal yu|lere &thorn;e dute of god, his wille &thorn;at &yogh;e may do.  Rennes fast|do wilis ye haue liht, &thorn;at &thorn;e mirkenes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>mirken/nes</I>.</NOTE> o ded our-take &thorn;e|noht."  &THORN;e haly spirt bidis us &thorn;at we trou his reed, &thorn;at|we may cum to &thorn;e lif and se &thorn;e dais of godis sune|in ioye wid-uten ende.  "yef &thorn;u will haue &thorn;at ioy,|gete &thorn;i tunge, &thorn;u speke na sca&thorn;e, and tine lippis fra|iuel.  Turne &thorn;e fra iuil &amp; do &thorn;e gode, &thorn;at ti lif folihe|&thorn;aim. wen &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;us do, &thorn;an sal<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sa</I>.</NOTE> min ezin be on &yogh;ow.|Til &yogh;ure praier sa[l] I here, sal &yogh;e noht be for-getin.  Or|&thorn;at &yogh;e calle to me, I sal saie: I es here."  My suete sistirs,| I saie to <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="2b">yu: es na sueter uoice &thorn;an of iesu; sua sais|sain benet.  God al-mihti kenne us &thorn;e rihte gate til|endeles ioy.  Amen.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="2">
<HEAD>Secundum capitulum.</HEAD>
<P>Succinctis ergo fide.</P>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence mustirs sain benet us hu we sal lede|ure lif, and sais &thorn;at we sal belt us wid chastiment,|riht trouz &thorn;at ye haue wid gode dede, &thorn;at tu belte &thorn;ine|lendis sua, and &thorn;at tine fete be shod in riht gate, Als &thorn;e|gospel tellis, in his tretes &thorn;at &thorn;u ga, til his rengne &thorn;at|&thorn;u may cume, &thorn;are hise frendis sal euir be, &thorn;at here hauis|wele wroht.  Yef &thorn;u wil to &thorn;at rengne cume, do &thorn;e dedis|of godis sune; &thorn;u sal [be] &thorn;idir<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sal &thorn;idit</I>.</NOTE> broht. we aske &thorn;e, lauerd,|&thorn;urz &thorn;e muz of &thorn;e profete, Wha in &thorn;i tabernakil sal wne.|"An wha sal wne wid &thorn;e in &thorn;e muntain &thorn;at es sua briht?"|Lauerd, &thorn;an we haue askid &thorn;e, &thorn;e ancewer of &thorn;e sal we here:|&thorn;e riht &thorn;idir at cume &thorn;ai sal haue, entre &thorn;at ere wid-uten|sinne; &THORN;at rihtuis es of dede and rihtuis of speche in his|hert of alle &thorn;ing; &thorn;at wid tunge lezis noht, bot sothfastnes|in his &thorn;oht; &THORN;at euil dos til nan, ne reproues na man of|&thorn;aire mis-dede.  He dos all to noht &thorn;e sinne &thorn;at wnis in
<PB N="3">|his &thorn;oht and quites him <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3a">at te nede.  Lauerd, we prai<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>prai&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE>|&thorn;e &thorn;at we may serue sua, in &thorn;i tabernakil &thorn;at we may wne.|Amen.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="3">
<HEAD>Tercium capitulum.</HEAD>
<P>Ergo preparanda.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Latin catch-words <I>Ergo preparanda</I>|are placed in the right margin; they properly belong to l. 27.</NOTE></P>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence sais sain benet til &thorn;a &thorn;at luuis god &amp;|dutes hym: yef &thorn;u findis ani god in &thorn;e, til god sal &thorn;e|louing be, a[n]d<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ad</I>.  The same slip was made in p. 6, l. 12, and p. 9, l. 29,|in which latter place, however, <I>ad</I> was immediately crossed out, and|<I>and</I> was added.</NOTE> grace til him giue, of whame we haue al|&thorn;e gude; als &thorn;e prophete sais: "Non nobis domine&mdash;Lord,|of us es it noht, bot til &thorn;i name ioy es broht"; Als sain|paul sais: "Lauerd, of me haue I noht, bot &thorn;u sende it|me."  In o&thorn;ir stede sais he: "In god sal man be glad and|loue him in dede."  And heris wat ure lauerd sais in &thorn;e|gospel: "Qui audit&mdash;Wha sam heris my word and dos it|in werke, Til &thorn;e wyis man sembils<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>se m bils</I>.</NOTE> he, &thorn;at fundes his hus|opon &thorn;e stan fra &thorn;e water and te flod; for &thorn;i ne failed it|noht, for it [was] wrht<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>it wrht</I>.</NOTE> o-pon &thorn;e harde stane." &THORN;us kennis ure|lauerd us his werkis, at folu his cumandementis.  For &thorn;i|he giuis us respit, &thorn;at we sal mende ure sinne and si&thorn;in to|&thorn;e ioy be sent; Als &thorn;e postil sais &yogh;ur godes word: "An|nescitis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>nescitits</I>.</NOTE>&mdash;&THORN;e sufferans may &thorn;u noht wite of god her witerlike,|&thorn;at he to &thorn;e hauis don?"  Als ure lauerd sais: <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3b">"Of |&thorn;e sinfull will I noht &thorn;e dede, bot &thorn;at tay turne and liue."|wen we aske &thorn;e, lauerd, wha in &thorn;i tabernakill sall wone,|and we here &thorn;i cumandement, and dos te werkis &thorn;at fallis|&thorn;ar-to, &thorn;an sall we be ayris in &thorn;i ioye.  lord, for &thorn;i mercy|&thorn;u gif us grace &thorn;are at be.  Amen.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="4">
<HEAD>Capitulum IIII.</HEAD>
<P>Monachorum.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Monachorum</I> properly belongs to p. 4, l. 14.</NOTE></P>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence bidis us sain benet &thorn;at we make ure|hertis redy, and ure bodis als-sua, in mekenes, yef we|will wone wid god.  &THORN;an ure force es gane us fra, we pray|ure lauerd be ure help for his mikill miht.  Yef we &thorn;e|painis of helle will fle, and cum till ioy &thorn;at ay sall be,|&THORN;anne full-fille we his wille.  Loke &thorn;at &yogh;e renne sui&thorn;e, yef
<PB N="4">|&yogh;e will to &thorn;e lange liue.  &thorn;are may help &thorn;e here to.  &THORN;us|sais sain benet: Mi scole wil i stablis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>wilistablis</I>.</NOTE> to godis seruise.|Greue &thorn;ing will i noht stablis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sta = blis</I>.</NOTE> na noht &thorn;at wrange es, bot|a stresce will I make in mendnis of &yogh;oure sinne, And for to|yeme charite, &thorn;at &thorn;er nan iuil lares by-gynne, Bot &thorn;at haly|kirke &yogh;ow lokis.  Loke &thorn;u folow &thorn;i domnum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>domnum</I>?|the d is defective, and resembles an o; no contraction mark is distinguishable.</NOTE> in haly religiun;|&thorn;an sall &thorn;i charge be liht; &thorn;an sal &thorn;i hert liht be,|in godis trouht yef &thorn;u<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between <I>yef</I> and <I>&thorn;u</I> there are a couple of|indistinct strokes slanting like the two first of a w.  Possibly the|scribe was about to write <I>we</I> instead of <I>&thorn;u</I>.</NOTE> it se.  In mikill suetnes may &thorn;u| renne, wen &thorn;u can knau god and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="4a">his cumandement.  &THORN;an|sall tu euir mare wone wid him in &thorn;at suete felazscap.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>felazhap</I>|(thus h for sc).</NOTE>|&THORN;at here liuis in clene scrift and in paine, &thorn;ai sall haue|part wid him.  Lauerd, &thorn;u grante it us sua, til &thorn;i ioy &thorn;at|we ga.  Amen.</P>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<P>Quartum vero genus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The catch-words properly belong to l. 28.</NOTE></P>
<P>Foure maner of Munkis es in religiun, sais sain benet.|&THORN;e first maner &thorn;an er &thorn;a in cuuent es gadird for to|liue in godis pais, vndir reul of dicipline, and a abbot ouir|&thorn;am.  &THORN;e to&thorn;ir maner &thorn;an ere ermitis and reclusis, godis|wille bi &thorn;am ane at do.  &THORN;e ermitis and &thorn;e reclusis &thorn;at|liuis sua, kenning bi-hus &thorn;am haue for to fezte wid &thorn;are|miht a-gain &thorn;e deuil and a-gain &thorn;ar sinne.  &THORN;anane by-houis|&thorn;am fezte &thorn;am ane, at god es tar best help.  &THORN;e|&thorn;ridde er &thorn;a &thorn;at in na reul will ga, na hauis na kenning.|Als es o &thorn;aim at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;aim</I>, i above the line.&mdash;<I>at</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE> saie als &thorn;e gold &thorn;u may se, &thorn;at semis|gode and es noht: wen it es forht broht, &thorn;an es it als &thorn;e|lede.  Bi-fore &thorn;e werld er &thorn;ai semande, and fals-like liues,|and tines &thorn;aire mede, And leris o-gain god of &thorn;ar abit.|&thorn;ai er unwise; &thorn;ai desaiue &thorn;am-self and o&thorn;ir ba&thorn;e.  &THORN;e|ferde maner er wel werre, &thorn;at nou&thorn;er will wone, bot gange| fra stede til stede wil &thorn;ai, noure wone lange.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="4b">&thorn;air aue|wille will &thorn;ai do.  Glutunie luue &thorn;ai. better es to be stille|&thorn;an for to speke of &thorn;air lif.  Sain benet sais: now wil I|blinne to speke of &thorn;aim, for it ne helpis noht, &amp; speke of
<PB N="5">|&thorn;a &thorn;at liuis in godis ordir.  &thorn;at we wid &thorn;aim may ga, god|gif it us.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>Abbas qui preesse.</P>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence mustirs sain benet wat man az<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ar</I>, for <I>az</I> or <I>ah</I>.</NOTE> at be|abot.  &THORN;e abot ah fo[r]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fo</I>; cf. p. 6, l. 18.</NOTE> to wite what his name|singnefiis and whi he beris &thorn;e curun.  He [ah] at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>He at</I>.</NOTE> mustir|gode dedis and wel rede and singe in haly kirke, Gode|a-saumpil til o&thorn;ir at giue for to liue riht.  &THORN;e name of &thorn;e|abot bitakins fadir of maine.  For he sal be in haly kirke|in godis stede for to lere his munkis wisdom and charite.|He ah na &thorn;ing at cumande bot &thorn;at he may haue warant at|god.  Rihtuis ah he at be, and of charite, Als haly writ|sais, wis of speche, Of gode cunsaile at &thorn;e nede; sua az|abot at be.  He sal lere his cuuent &thorn;e riht gate, in godis|troht &thorn;at &thorn;ai be.  Euer sal be in his &thorn;oht &thorn;at his munkis|be wel lered, &thorn;at &thorn;ai dute god.  &THORN;e abot sal be blamid|if &thorn;e cuuent mis-ga.  &THORN;a &thorn;at ere of ille dedis, he <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="5a">az at |chasti &thorn;am.  &thorn;an sall he be quit at &thorn;e iugement, And saie|wid &thorn;e prophete: "Lauerd, I ne hid noht in me &thorn;e rehtuisnes|of &thorn;e.  I bad &thorn;ai sulde it gete.  Summe hauid me|in despit, wen I lered &thorn;aim, And did &thorn;aire azen wille."|&THORN;anne sais saine benet of &thorn;aim &thorn;at ere unbuxum ogain god,|&thorn;at &thorn;ai sall to paine ga. lauerd de-fende us &thorn;ar-fra.  Amen.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>Ergo cum aliquis suscipit.</P>
<P>Sain benet spekis yet of &thorn;a &thorn;at sall be abotis: Gode|a-saumpil sal he giue, Of twine maner at lere<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>lers</I>.</NOTE> his|discipilis in religiun in halynes at serue god: ba&thorn;e in word|and dede, ba&thorn;e to &thorn;e simplis and till &thorn;e harde of hart.|His dedis az at be suilke als he cumandis til o&thorn;ir.  He|bidis &thorn;ai sall nan euil do.  Yef he kennis gode till o&thorn;ir,|and him-self dos noht sua, God refusis him; Als haly writ|sais: "Quare tu enarras &amp;c.;&mdash;Whi telles tu mi rih[t]uisnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>rihuisnes</I>.</NOTE>|wid &thorn;i muz, and dos it noht?  Dicipline &thorn;u hatid, and keste|mine wordis obac; &thorn;are for-gat tu &thorn;e.  In &thorn;i bro&thorn;ir ehe &thorn;u|ses a stra, And noht a balke in &thorn;in azen."  &THORN;abot az at|loue nane mare <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="5b">&thorn;an o&thorn;[i]r<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS.|<I>o&thorn;r</I>; cf. p. 7, l. 26.</NOTE> for his heze kinredin, bot he be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I> omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE>
<PB N="6">|buxum and religius bot ilkain o&thorn;ir bro&thorn;ir.  For nede he|may do an bi-fore an[o]&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>an&thorn;er</I>.</NOTE> for reuerance, yef he ne will|noht ilkain in his ordir, als he takis.  Ba&thorn;e yung and alde|sall halde reul; til a god haue we tan.  Alle sal be louid|eftir an in haly religiun, bot if &thorn;ai bettir do; For &thorn;ai|az at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>at</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ai</I>.</NOTE> be louid euin-like in charite, ilkain als tay ere.|Scrif[t]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Scrif</I>.</NOTE> sal he do on &thorn;aim, &thorn;are sinnis for to les.|Lauerd, &thorn;u giue us sua at do, &thorn;at we may cume to &thorn;i|regne.  Amen.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>In doctrina sua namque.</P>
<P>Sain benet sais &thorn;at abot az at lere his cuuent, als sain|pol bidis: Blame &thorn;at mis-do, a[n]d<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ad</I>.</NOTE> do &thorn;am liue riht;|chasti &thorn;aim fra iuil wne, als &thorn;e fadir dos his sune.  &THORN;a &thorn;at|ere fraward and recles, Lede &thorn;aim &thorn;e straiter.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>straiter</I>?  The fifth character, at the end of a line,|is blurred; possibly <I>strat/ter</I> (cf. p. 2, ll. 3, 7, footnotes).</NOTE>  &THORN;a &thorn;at er|buxum<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>buzum</I>.</NOTE> and meke, &thorn;ai sall haue cumfort.  Yef ani faute|be funden in &thorn;aim, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ai</I>.</NOTE> it be sone mendid.  He sall|vmbe-&thorn;inke hym of &thorn;e prest of sylo, &thorn;e ire of god com to,|fo[r]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fo</I>.</NOTE> he ne chastid noht hise childir, bot lete &thorn;aim in &thorn;aire|wille.  &THORN;e gode sall he chasty wid word and amonesce|&thorn;aim.  &THORN;at er prude and kene, &thorn;ai sall be chastid wid| wand.  For it is writen <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="6a">&thorn;at man sall chasti &thorn;aim:|"Percute filium &amp;c.;&mdash;Smite &thorn;i sune wid &thorn;i wand, and|make him meke, and deliuir his saul fra paine."  Lauerd,|&thorn;u deliuer us fra paine.  Amen.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>Meminisse.</P>
<P>Ay, sais sain benet, &thorn;abot az at &thorn;inke &thorn;at, wat his|name es.  &THORN;e mare he hauis in pouste, &thorn;e mare|hauis he at yelde.  Abot az at be wis; greueus &thorn;ing es|hym bi-taht: &THORN;e sauls for to gete, And mony &thorn;ing for to|wite.  Wid summe sal tu faire speke, and summe gete wid|chastiment &amp; haue &thorn;am under wand, and lere &thorn;aim ilkain|eftir &thorn;ar maner wid resun.  &THORN;an &thorn;ar &thorn;e noht be calanged|of &thorn;e cuuent &thorn;at es undir &thorn;e, &thorn;at es giuin [&thorn;e] at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>giuin at</I>;|cf. p. 7, l. 2, and p. 41, l. 15.</NOTE> yeme.  &THORN;ur&yogh;|&thorn;e dute &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue &thorn;e ioy of god, may &thorn;ai ler at serue
<PB N="7">|him to will.  For nan er&thorn;elike<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>er &thorn;e like</I>.</NOTE> pouste az he at for-gete &thorn;e|sauls &thorn;at es bitaht him at yeme.  &THORN;e tresur of god er &thorn;ai.|Resun sal he yelde to god of &thorn;aim.  Yef &thorn;u be of litil|uresun, be of riht trouz, and here what haly boke sais:|"Primum querite regnum dei&mdash;First sal tu seke godis|rengne and his rihtuisnes, &thorn;an sall &thorn;ing multeplii &thorn;e."|He &thorn;at made &thorn;is salme sais: <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="6b">"wha sua liuis riht, &thorn;ai |sal haue na ned.  Nichil de-esse&mdash;Na &thorn;ing sal faile &thorn;aim|&thorn;at wil luue god."  &THORN;abot az at under-stande of &thorn;e sauls he|hauis at yeme, &thorn;at he sall yelde resun of &thorn;aim.  Loke &thorn;e|numbir of his cuuent: Als well az he to yeme &thorn;aim als his|azen saul, yef he wil be sauf.  &THORN;an he for o&thorn;ir sal ancewer|swa, full riht az he at ga, And mende him in dede.  &THORN;e|mare he mendis his cuuent, Till mare ioy sall he be sent,|til god at take his mede.  Lauerd, giue us sua at liue, &thorn;at|we may yelde &thorn;e resun for us-self at &thorn;e day of dome.|Amen.  Qui uiuis &amp; regnas.</P>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<P>De adsc[i]endis ad consilium sororibus.&mdash;Quociens|aliqua.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>adscendis</I>.&mdash;<I>Quociens aliqua</I> fills|up the blank at the end of Chapter II, thus apparently preceding|the heading of the next chapter.</NOTE></P>
<P>Sain benet mustirs in &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>, MS. <I>his</I>; cf. the|beginnings of most chapters.</NOTE> sentence Hu &thorn;abes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;abes</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;abas</I> with an e over the|second a.</NOTE> sal take|hir cunsale.  Scho sall calle &thorn;e cuuent to-gidir and|muster &thorn;aim &thorn;e nede, and loke whilke sais best resun, and|proue &thorn;air wit sua.  &THORN;an ilkain hauis said &thorn;air auis, &THORN;at|es best, halde &thorn;ar-to.  Sua bidis haly writ, &thorn;at alle be|cald til cunsaile, yung and alde, in hali religiun; For|ofte sendis god resun til &thorn;e yunge &thorn;at a-no&thorn;[i]r<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>a no&thorn;r</I>.</NOTE> ne can noht.|&THORN;at all consentis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="7a">to sal nan gain-saie, bot halde it in |obedience.  Als te decipill es at his maister cumandement,|Als sal &thorn;abes consent til &thorn;aire cunsale &thorn;at resun es.|Alle sal folihe &thorn;e maister of &thorn;e reule, ba&thorn;e yung and alde.|&THORN;at nan folu &thorn;air ahen wille, ne nan bere &thorn;aim sua heze,|&thorn;at tay striue ogain &thorn;air abes.  Yef any sal take discipline,|gruching sal sho make nane, bot halde &thorn;e cumandement.
<PB N="8">|&THORN;e dedis of &thorn;abbesse sal be in &thorn;e dute of god, for|sho [sal] be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sho be</I>.</NOTE> set til resun of all hir iugemens and of al hir|dedis bi-for god, &thorn;at es rihtuis of iugement.  &THORN;ar es priue|cunsale be at do, &thorn;e alde sal sho calle &thorn;ar-to; Als haly|writ bidis: "Omnia<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Omnis</I>.</NOTE> fac cum consilio&mdash;Alle &thorn;ing do wid|cunsale, and eftir &thorn;e dede sal &thorn;e noht mis-like."  Lauerd,|we pray &thorn;e &thorn;at we may suilke cunsal take, &thorn;at we may do|&thorn;i wille.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="4">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<P>Que<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Quo.</NOTE> sunt in-strumenta bonorum operum.&mdash;In|primis dominum.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In|primis dominum</I>, cf. the footnote on <I>Quociens aliqua</I>, p. 7, l. 18.</NOTE></P>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence spekis sain benet, and mustirs til his|cuuent what &thorn;aire god dedis ah at be.  First sal ye|luue god wid al yure herte and wid al yure saul and wid|al yure uertu, And ti prome als ti-self; sua ah ye at do.| Man <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="7b">ah ye noht at sla; na to licherie ga; Na til|&thorn;ifte; Na cuuatus;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Na cuuatus</I> twice.</NOTE> Ne bere fals witnes, bot onur alle|men; &amp; do til na man bot als tu walde man did to &thorn;e;|And leue &thorn;in ahen wille, and foliz godis wil; and halde|&thorn;e in<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;ein</I>.</NOTE> chastite, and iuil langingis do away; luue fasting; &thorn;e|pouir help bi-for &thorn;e ga; &thorn;at ere nakid cla&thorn;e; wisit &thorn;at er|seke; &thorn;e dede winde and til eryd bringe; Sahtil &thorn;at ere|wraze; And uncu&thorn;e be wid &thorn;e dedis of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;e|dedis of</I> twice.</NOTE> &thorn;e werld; luue|god ouir alle &thorn;ing.  when &thorn;u es in ire, heuin &thorn;e noht;|&thorn;ar-of cumis ille ending.  Halde na feluni in &thorn;i harte;|Ne giue na fals pes; Charite felle &thorn;u noht; Iuil for iuil|sal tu noht do, Ne wrang to na man; Til god uengance|fallis it.  Yef ani do yu wrang, ye sal take it in pacience,|Als hali boke cumandis.  Ye sal luue yure enemis &amp;|striue noht ogain &thorn;am, ne banne &thorn;am noht, bot blisce &thorn;am|and suffir iugement.  Ye ne sal noht be prude in herte;|Ne ete our-mikil; Ne drinc ouir-mikil; Mesurlike slepe;|Ne be noht slau, Ne gruchande; In god al yure trouz, and| ful of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="8a">charite; And yef ye finde ani gode in yu, till|god sal &thorn;e louing be, and grace til him giue.  ye sal dute
<PB N="9">|domis-day And te fir of helle; And haue god trouz til &thorn;e|lif &thorn;at lastes ay; And ilke day &thorn;at ye &thorn;inke o-pon &thorn;e ded;|And haue bi-fore yu &thorn;at god in alle stedis may se; wicke|&thorn;ohtis do oway &thorn;at to yu cume, and bide &thorn;aim ga forz, and|quite yu wid scrift; And gete yure mu&thorn;es fra unait|wordis; haly lescun bli&thorn;elike here; And clene uresun for|to lere; wid teris and wid sizing knau yure sinne, sua|sal ye amende yu o-gain god; leue &thorn;e wille of yure fles,|sua sal ye yure sinnes les.  &thorn;at yure abes cumandis yu,|sal ye do, and be not &thorn;ar-o-gain, Als ure lauerd bad his|deciplis; his cumandement do noht oway; luues chastite|and kaste pride oway; loke ye do sua.  &thorn;e alde men sal ye|onur, &thorn;e yunge luue in god; And pray for yure enmis;|and for-giue &thorn;aim &thorn;aire fautes &thorn;at mis-do ogain yu.  yef|ye be wrad &thorn;an &thorn;e sune rises,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sunerises</I>.</NOTE> make pes are it ga to|rest.  &thorn;at ye ne falle in na mis-hope, bot in godis trouz to|liue.  &thorn;is is &thorn;entendement of haly kirke for to wirke|godis wille; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="8b">&thorn;an sal it come be-for us at &thorn;e day of |dome; he giuis us ure mede.  God giue us &thorn;at ilke mede|&thorn;at he hizte til hise freendis, &thorn;at nan eye may se, ne erin|here, ne herte forz telle, what god hauis graid til &thorn;a &thorn;at|luues him.  [L]uues haly kirke and yure cloister; &thorn;anne<NOTE PLACE="foot">22 ff. On this page several rubrics were|never entered in the blanks left for them.  On the preceding pages|the usual red strokes in the black letters are entirely wanting.</NOTE>|may ye do godis wille.  [L]auerd, giue us sua &thorn;ir cumandemens|at do, &thorn;at we may cum to &thorn;i ioy!  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD>V.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence spekis sain benet of obedience, what|it is at saie.  [&THORN;]at es te<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>este</I>.</NOTE> firste mekenes: wid-uten|duelling til &thorn;at man bidis yu do.  [M]eke bi-houis yu|be for &thorn;e luue of god, for he mekid him for yu.  [M]eke|yu to godis seruise in hali kirke and do yure miht &thorn;ar-to,|&thorn;at ye may fle &thorn;e fir of helle and cum til heuin-rike; &thorn;are|es faire at be.  [&THORN;]at yure abes cumandes yu at do, &thorn;at ye|do it suiftlike; als god cumandis: "Ob auditu &amp;c.;&mdash;[&THORN;]urz|&thorn;e wordis ye here o me, &thorn;an ah ye at be meke";|als yure maistiresse leris yu, als it sais: "Qui uos audit&mdash;
<PB N="10">|wha sam heris yu, &thorn;an heris me."  for &thorn;i sal ye understande|&thorn;aim: &thorn;at of mekenes wil lere, &thorn;ai sal here &thorn;e|cumandemens, and do als man bidis &thorn;am.  ye sal leue| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="9a">yure ahen propir will, and do o&thorn;ir mens.  &thorn;oz ye be in|labur, and yure maistires cumande yu at do a-no&thorn;ir &thorn;ing,|ye sal laie it dune, &amp; do &thorn;at scho bidis; &thorn;an er ye buxum|under reule.  ilkain sal take discipline at o&thorn;ir, als hir|mastiresse &thorn;oz scho ware, in &thorn;e dute of god.  ye sal wne|yu til strate gate, for &thorn;e luue of god; Als ure lauerd sais:|"Angustia &amp;c.;&mdash;Straite gatis toke I me for to giue yu a-saumpil|at liue."  ye ne sal noht liue in yure ahen wille,|bot giue yu til mekenes.  ye sal do o&thorn;er mens wille, yef|ye wil cum to god.  &THORN;a &thorn;at wil liue in cuuent, &thorn;ai sal|haue maistiresse ouir &thorn;am for to yeme &thorn;aim, &thorn;at tay foliz|&thorn;e wordis of god, als he sais: "Non veni &amp;c.;&mdash;I ne|come not in-til er&thorn;e for to do mi wille, bot my fadirs &thorn;at|me sent."  &thorn;at es godis wille, &thorn;at ye foliz yure ordir, and|luue til yure prome, and do with-uten gruching &thorn;at yu es|cumandid.  &thorn;e mekenes &thorn;urz god ye can, als he sais|him-self: "Qui uos audit&mdash;&thorn;at heris in yu,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yu</I>, MS. <I>me</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;ai here|me."  For &thorn;i bi-houis &thorn;e decipils do &thorn;e mekenes, als &thorn;ai|haue tane to; &thorn;at es godis wille.  &thorn;oz &thorn;u gruche, &thorn;e|cumandement sal be haldin.  And yef &thorn;u gruches &amp; dos| &thorn;at ilke &thorn;ing, god es noht paid &thorn;ar-of; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="9b">for he ses ty|herte, &amp; for ty hauis &thorn;ou no mede of &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at tu dos|gruchande; for &thorn;i sal tu quite &thorn;e wid scrift; ye, it bi-cimis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi-cimis</I>, see Notes.</NOTE>|yu.  lauerd gif us sua meke at be, &thorn;at we may halde ure|ordir, and syne cume til &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at lastes ay.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="6">
<HEAD>VI.</HEAD>
<P>Sain benet spekis in &thorn;is sentence of silence, how &yogh;e|sal it halde.  he bidis &thorn;at &yogh;e do als &thorn;e prophete|sais: "kepe &yogh;our tunge, it sp[e]ke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>spke</I>.</NOTE> no sca&thorn;e, &amp; &yogh;our lippis|fra iuil, &amp; kepe &yogh;ow fro dedly synne."  for &thorn;i sal &yogh;e seldin|speke, for &yogh;e sal speke nan unat, ne vse yow noht &thorn;ar-to.|&amp; in o&thorn;ir stede es writen: "Mors &amp; uita &amp;c.;&mdash;In &thorn;e|pointe of &thorn;e tunge es lif &amp; ded."  loke whe&thorn;er &yogh;e wil take|to.  &thorn;e maistires aw at speke for to lere hyr dicipils|wisdom.  &thorn;e decipils sal here &thorn;ar lesson &amp; understand it.
</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="7">
<PB N="11">
<HEAD>VII.</HEAD>
<P>yet</P>
<P>Of mekenes spekis sain benet in &thorn;is sentence, &amp; sais|with hali scripture:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scripture</I>, i above the line.</NOTE> "Omnis qui se exaltat &amp;c.;&mdash;|&thorn;a&thorn;at heyes &thorn;am, &thorn;ai sal be mekid; &amp; &thorn;ai &thorn;at mekes|&thorn;am sal be heyed."  vre lord saide &thorn;at it es pride in &thorn;aim|&thorn;at hyes &thorn;aim.  Til mekenes he bides yu se, &amp; say als &thorn;e|prophete saide, when he spac til ure lauerd with mu&thorn;e:|"Domine, non est &amp;c.;&mdash;lauerd, my hart es not heyid in|me, ne min eyen.  Mikil o me ne held I noht to praise|me-self.  yef I leuid at se to mekenes &amp; heyid me, My|lauerd munde do <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="10a">to my saul als &thorn;e barne &thorn;at is done |fra his modir milke ouir-arlike."  Mikyl walde he fle|pride, &thorn;e prophete, als hali writ sais.  Yef ye wyl be|hezid, lokes &thorn;at ye be meke, And make yure stize to he|heuin wid yure gode dedis, &thorn;at iacob saz slapande: he saz|gode wid his angels cume dune and vp in &thorn;e stede &thorn;are he|lay.  yef ye wil se to mekenes, &thorn;are sal ye be hezed,|and gang vp wid &thorn;at stize.  &thorn;at bitakins, &thorn;an &thorn;ai com|dune, ye sal be lazed, yef ye be prude; and tan &thorn;ai yede|vp, &thorn;at ye sal be hezed, yef ye to mekenes can se.  &THORN;e|stize betakins vre lif here.  &thorn;e stize hauis tua tres, bitakins|&thorn;e body and te saul, ay&thorn;ar at helpe o&thorn;ir.  &thorn;e stelis bytuixe|bitakins oure gude dedis, &thorn;at sal bere vs vp to god.|&thorn;e tres betakins mekenes to goddis seruise and vnder|discipline.  Lauerd, we prai &thorn;e for &thorn;i misericorde &thorn;at we|mai sua yeme &thorn;is reul o mekenes, In &thorn;e felazscap of &thorn;in|angels &thorn;at we may be.  amen.  Qui viuis &amp; regnas deus|per omnia secula.</P>
<P>Sain Benet sais &thorn;at te dedis of mekenes ere ful suete;|sua kennis he us; And sais &thorn;at ye sal haue firste|&thorn;e dute of god, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">The first <I>&thorn;at</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;a</I><SUP>t</SUP>.</NOTE> ye liue sua, &thorn;at ye be noght for-getil|and fle evil dedis, And tat ye recorde wel &thorn;e cumantemens|of god.  Loke &thorn;at ye fle sinne, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="10b">yef ye wile cume to &thorn;e |ioy of heuin fra &thorn;e pines of helle; &thorn;at yure wyl be euir at|gete yu fra sca&thorn;e; &thorn;at ye gete yu fra iuil &thorn;ohtes, yure|tunges fra iuil speche, yure eyen, yure hend, yure fete fra|vnait gate, fra iuil wylle; And scere o-way al &thorn;e langing|of yure fleis.  God ses al yure &thorn;oght and al yure dedis.
<PB N="12">|&thorn;e angel &thorn;at here yemis yu dos hym at wit all yure|dedis; sua sais te prophete.  Alle yure &thorn;ohtes may he|se; And whyder &thorn;ai wyl lede yu,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yu</I>, MS. <I>ye</I> (or <I>&thorn;e</I>).</NOTE> resun sal ye yelde|of &thorn;am.  for &thorn;i ah ye at gete yu fra iuil &thorn;ohtes, &thorn;at ye|may cume to &thorn;e ioy of heuin.  god gyf it us!  amen.</P>
<P>Of propir wyl spekis sain benet; and ye sall do it als|god bidis in haly writ and sais: "Et a voluntatibus&mdash;Turne|yu fra yure wille and gete yu fra iuil;|&thorn;an may ye liue in pais."  Of yure ahen wylle sall ye|blinne, al &thorn;at wil do yu sinne; Als it is wrytyn: "Sunt|vie que&mdash;&thorn;e rihte gate, it es til &thorn;e lyf &thorn;at lastes ay."  &thorn;a|gates sal ye fle &thorn;at wicke men gas to hell by.  for &thorn;i ar|&thorn;ai rotyn &thorn;at folyzed wicke wylle; hauid tay na bettir|mede.  sua sal yure antente be, &thorn;at god may se al yure|wylle; Als te prophete sais.  He sais: "all his langing| es by-fore god."  for &thorn;i <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="11a">es gude &thorn;at ye doe o-way yure|wicke dedis &amp; &thorn;ohtes; &thorn;e dede is set to chasti &thorn;aim.|for witte ye wele &thorn;at god may se ba&thorn;e iuil and gude; es|noght hyd be-fore hym.  God lokis ut of heuin in-tyl|er&thorn;e tyll hise at visit &thorn;aim, and lokes yef man askys hym|ohte.  For &thorn;i lokys &thorn;at ye do wel, &thorn;at yure angel may|do yure nedis to god of al &thorn;at ye haue nede.  And getes|yu wel, yure fautes be noght musterd by-fore god. Lauerd,|&thorn;u do vs sua at liue, &thorn;at we may deliuir vs of al vre|fautes, And si&thorn;in to ioy cume.  Amen.</P>
<P>&THORN;e to&thorn;ir maner o mekenes is, sais sain benet, For to|hate yure ahen propir wyl, And fulfil noght yure|langing, bot do godis wylle, and his desire fulfille; Als|him-selfe sais: "Non veni &amp;c.;&mdash;I ne cume noght for to do|my wille, bot my fadirs &thorn;at me sent."  And in odyr stede|sais he: "Voluntas habet &amp;c.;&mdash;Wille he hauide paine at|do, at haue &thorn;e curune &thorn;at lastes ay, als it was hys wille."|Lauerd, we pray &thorn;e &thorn;at we may sua halde &thorn;is mekenes,|&thorn;at we may do &thorn;i wille.  amen.</P>
<P>Of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde maner o mekenes spekys sain benet to &thorn;a|in his reul wyl be, And bidis &thorn;at ye sal be meke|vnder yure abbes and do godis seruise; Als ta-postil saide|of godis sune, &thorn;at he was meke riht tyl &thorn;e ded.  God| giue vs &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="11b">we may sua be.  amen.
</P>
<P>
<PB N="13">Of &thorn;e fer&thorn;e maner o mekenes spekys sain benet, hu ye|sal meke yu of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at yu &thorn;inc es igainis yu, &thorn;at|fallis to yure ordir.  yef man dos yu ani wrang, ye sal take|it in pacience, and noht fle &thorn;ar-fore, ne leue yure gode|dede; Als haly boke sais: "Qui perseuerauerit &amp;c.;&mdash;Wha|sua wel wirkis til endyng, &thorn;ai sal be sauf of alle &thorn;ing";|Als &thorn;e prophete sais: "Confortetur &amp;c.;&mdash;ye sal haue cumfort|in yure hertis of god."  For &thorn;i sal ye be of pacience,|for &thorn;e luue of god, of &thorn;ing &thorn;at es o-ganis yure fleis; Als te|prophete sais to god: "Lauerd, we ere ilke day, for &thorn;e|luue of &thorn;e, in &thorn;e dute of dede als te shep &thorn;at ere driuin to|ded, for we folih &thorn;e; bli&thorn;elike we suffir it, for we sal haue|mede of &thorn;e"; Als haly writ sais: "Probasti nos &amp;c.;&mdash;Lauerd,|&thorn;u prouis vs here als te siluir &thorn;at es brind; &thorn;u did|vs in &thorn;e lay and noy opon vre bak."  for we sulde lere|vnder maistires hu we sulde liue; Als te letter sais:|"Inposuisti &amp;c.;&mdash;Ouir vs hauis &thorn;u don men," &thorn;i wylle at|fulfille.  &THORN;a &thorn;at ere vnbuxum, &thorn;ai sal be done to paine.  Of|&thorn;aim spekis sain paul, and sais &thorn;at tay ere fals.  &THORN;ai caste|&thorn;air mantil and rennis a-mise.  &thorn;at bytakins, &thorn;ai sal liue|here bot <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="12a">a while.  Alle be blisced &thorn;at weris taim.  God |giue vs sua meke at be, and sua his wille at do, &thorn;at we his|ioy cum to.  amen.</P>
<P>Of &thorn;e fifte maner o mekenes spekis sain benet for to|lere hys sistirs hu &thorn;ai salle scriue &thorn;aim to &thorn;air abbes,|ba&thorn;e nunne and sistir.  Loke &thorn;at ye be buxum and scriue|yu of alle &thorn;e sinnis &thorn;at ye haue don; Als haly writ bidis|yu: "Reuela domino &amp;c.;&mdash;Mustir til god al &thorn;i gate, &amp; he|sal make it in pes."  And in odir stede sais he: "Confitemini|&amp;c.;&mdash;Knaus to god al yure sinne, for he es of mercy|and gude at al nede."  yet sais &thorn;e prophete: "Delictum|meum &amp;c.;&mdash;Lauerd, I mustird &thorn;e myne dedis, I ne hid|tam noht and alle my herte."  &thorn;an ye do &thorn;us, &thorn;an sale yure|sinnes be for-gyvin.  Lauerd giue vs grace sua for to muster|vre dedis, &thorn;at we may til his ioy cum.  amen.</P>
<P>Sain Benet spekis of &thorn;e sexte de-grece of mekenes Til|his sistirs, and sais &thorn;at ilkain sal halde &thorn;aim-selfe|lest of alle odir.  And al &thorn;ingis &thorn;at man bidis yu do, &thorn;at|ye do it mekely, &thorn;at resunnabil es. &thorn;u sal &thorn;inke in &thorn;i herte|&thorn;at tu es vndinge to gode dede; Als &thorn;e prophete saide:
<PB N="14">|"Ad nichilum &amp;c.;&mdash;Til na &thorn;ing es I made <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="12b">bot for to|doe godis wylle.  ic<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ic</I>, MS. <I>it</I>; similarly 9 and 10.</NOTE> is like tyl a mere &thorn;at beris &thorn;at man|lais on hir bak."  In what dede sam ye be, loke &thorn;at yure|&thorn;oht and &yogh;ure herte [be] to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>herte to</I>; cf. p. 38,|l. 7.</NOTE> god almihten.  Lauerd, we praie|&thorn;e, what sam we do, &thorn;at we to &thorn;e be broht.  amen.</P>
<P>Sain benet spekis yet til his sistirs of &thorn;e seuind|degrece o mekenes, and bidis &thorn;at ye sal meke yu|ilka in-til o&thorn;ir, ba&thorn;e mare &amp; lesse, And saie als te prophete|saide: "Ego sum &amp;c.;  Ic es wrmis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wrmis</I>, see Glossary.</NOTE> and na man,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>naman</I>.</NOTE>|And ut-castyng o men.  First was ic hezed, and si&thorn;in|lazed &thorn;ur scrifte, and ouir-cumin."  sua sal ye do, &amp; tanne|mai ye sai with &thorn;e prophete: "Bonum michi &amp;c.;&mdash;Lauerd,|god it es to me &thorn;at &thorn;u mekyd me to lere &thorn;ine cumandemens."|God giue vs sua his cumandemens at lere, &thorn;at we|may cume til his mekenes.  Amen.</P>
<P>Of &thorn;e ahtend maner o mekenes spekis sain benet til|his cuuent, and bidis &thorn;at ye sal do als te reul sais,|And als it cumandis, And meke vnder &thorn;are maistres in alle|&thorn;aire dedis.  Lauerd, ye giue vs at halde &thorn;is mekenes til|&thorn;ending.  amen.</P>
<P>Sain benet spekis til his cuuent of &thorn;e nihend degrece| o mekenes, And biddis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="13a">&thorn;at ye ne sal noght vse|yu tyl mekil speche.  for hali writ spekis &thorn;are-of, and|sais &thorn;at naman may mikil speke, bot yef &thorn;are be sinne|i-mang, Na naman wil prayse &thorn;aim &thorn;at es of mikil speche;|Ofte speke &thorn;ai wrang.  Lauerd, &thorn;u giue vs sua vre silence|to yeme, &thorn;at we may serue &thorn;e to-queme, in yu&thorn;e and in|elde.  amen.</P>
<P>Of &thorn;e tende maner o mekenes spekis sain benet|til his cuuent, And bidis &thorn;at ye ne sal noght be|ouir-lazand; and &thorn;inkes what &thorn;e prophete sais: "Stultus|in risu &amp;c.;&mdash;&thorn;e fool turnes hys &thorn;oght in-til lazter, and helpis|noht."  Lauerd, we pray &thorn;e &thorn;is resun be halden with vs,|and send vs &thorn;i wit.  AMeN.</P>
<P>Sain benet spekis yet til his cuuent Of &thorn;e ellofte maner|of mekenes, And biddis &thorn;at ye sal mekely speke|when ye speke, &amp; wid-vten lazter, and o fa wordis &amp;|stabil, and speke wiselike.  &thorn;an &thorn;u sal speke to &thorn;i felahe,
<PB N="15">|crie noght o-pon hir, bot faire aske &thorn;in erand, als haly|boke sais: "Sapiens verbis &amp;c.;&mdash;&thorn;e wyse man musters|hym wid fa wordis &amp; welle sitande."  Lauerd, we pray|&thorn;e Of &thorn;is maner &thorn;at we may be.  Amen.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="13b">Saint benet spekis in &thorn;is sentence Of &thorn;e telfete maner |o mekenes, And bidis &thorn;at ye sal meke yure herte|til alle men, ba&thorn;e to mare &amp; les.  In what labur sam ye|be, &thorn;oz ye be in &thorn;e kirke, Ou&thorn;ir in &thorn;e garde, Ou&thorn;ir in gate,|Ou&thorn;ir in felde, ou&thorn;ir what labur sam ye do, &thorn;at ye haue yure|heuidis enclind to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>heuid is enclin do</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;er&thorn;e, And &thorn;eneke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e/ncke</I>, originally <I>&thorn;encke</I>?</NOTE> on yure synnys for to|mende &thorn;aim, And tat ye be als rad als ye saz &thorn;e iugiment|of god, And &thorn;inke what &thorn;e puplicane saide, when he laide|hym by-hinde &thorn;e dore, Als te gospel telles: "Domine,|non sum dignus &amp;c.;&mdash;Lauerd, I ne is noght digne at lifte|mine ezin til heuin for mine sinnes."  loke what &thorn;e prophete|sais til oure lauerd in haly writ: "Incuruatus sum|&amp;c.;&mdash;Ic is lazed and mekid til alle &thorn;at mine ezin se."|When ye haue fulfild &thorn;is al, &thorn;ire mekenes, &thorn;an sal ye cume|til perfite charite, til &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at god hauis graid til mannis|sunis.  Lauerd, graunt it vs, &thorn;at we may sua &thorn;ir mekenes|halde, &thorn;at we to &thorn;i ioy may cume.  amen.  Qui viuis &amp;c.;</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD>VIII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;e tyme of wintir, &thorn;at es fra &thorn;e Kalandis of|nouembir til &thorn;e paskys, als it is forlokyd wyd|resun, &thorn;anne sal ye ryse at &thorn;e aztend time <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="14a">of &thorn;e nyght, |&thorn;at it be litil ouir mid-nyght; &thorn;an es tyme at rise, als it is|set, til godis seruise; And si&thorn;in, &thorn;e space eftir matins, til|sauters and til haly lescuns at here.  &THORN;at es hele of &thorn;a &thorn;at|ere in<NOTE PLACE="foot">The first <I>in</I> is above the line.</NOTE> sekenes, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>t</SUP>/<I>&thorn;at.</I></NOTE> es at say in sinne.  And fra &thorn;e paskis til|&thorn;e Kalandis of nouembir sal &thorn;e tyme be sua set, &thorn;at tare|be lytil entirual, &thorn;at ta &thorn;at sal ga til laburs, &thorn;at tay may|haue &thorn;e morning in &thorn;e begining of &thorn;e lyth to &thorn;air labur.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="9">
<HEAD>IX.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;e tyme of wintir, &thorn;an sal &thorn;e first vers be at|matins: "Deus, in adiutorium"; And in &thorn;e to&thorn;er|tyme &thorn;ris &thorn;is vers: "Domine, labia mea aperies"; at &thorn;e
<PB N="16">|&thorn;ridde tyme aiont wid &thorn;e "gloria patri"; and si&thorn;in efter|&thorn;e nihend-fer&thorn;e salme wid &thorn;e antefen ou&thorn;ir wid-vten; and|sy&thorn;in efter &thorn;e ymne; And tare-eftyr sexe salmis wid &thorn;e|antefens.  Wen &thorn;ai ere said and te verset, &thorn;abbasse saie &thorn;e|benecun; &thorn;an sal alle site, And nym &thorn;re lescuns, red o-pon|&thorn;e lettrun, &amp; by-tuixe &thorn;e lescuns &thorn;re respuns; and eftir &thorn;e|&thorn;ridde respun &thorn;e vers wid &thorn;e "gloria patri," standande|alle for &thorn;e onur of the haly trinite.  &thorn;e boke of &thorn;e halizes|sal be red, ba&thorn;e of &thorn;e newe lay &amp; of &thorn;alde testament, and|te exposiciuns of &thorn;aim Of oure fore-fadirs &thorn;at ware in|stabil trouz.  Eftir &thorn;e &thorn;re lescuns wid &thorn;e respuns, O&thorn;ir|sexe salmis sungen wid alleluia.  And eftir salbe redde|&thorn;e lescun of &thorn;a-postils wid gude deuocion, and te vers,| and si&thorn;in &thorn;e letanie "Kyrieleison."  And sua <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="14b">finise|matins.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="10">
<HEAD>X.</HEAD>
<P>Fra &thorn;e paskis til &thorn;e kalandis of nouembir sal be|halden a quantite of &thorn;e salmis, als is said bi-fore;|for &thorn;e nihtis er scorte als mikil, &thorn;at te &thorn;re lescunis be noght|red, bot an for &thorn;a &thorn;re of &thorn;alde testament, wid a scort respun;|Bot al &thorn;e to&thorn;ir finist, als it sais by-fore, &thorn;at na|nyht be lesse saide &thorn;an tuelue salmis, vt-takyn &thorn;e &thorn;ridde|and te nihende-fer&thorn;e salme.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="11">
<HEAD>XI.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;e sunendais es for to ryse arliker, And halde|yure mesur o waking; &thorn;at es &thorn;at ye syng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ye syng</I> twice.</NOTE> &thorn;e sexe|salmes and te vers, als is ordainde by-fore, sitande alle wid|ordir, and foure lescuns red wid respuns, als es ordainde,|and eftir &thorn;e "gloria patri"; &thorn;an sal alle stande for &thorn;e|reuerence; And efter o&thorn;ir sexe salmis wid &thorn;e antefens, als|by-fore, wid &thorn;e werset; And efter o&thorn;ir foure lescuns wid|&thorn;e respuns, wid &thorn;at ilke ordir by-fore; And tare-eftir &thorn;re|cantikils of &thorn;e prophetis, als te abes stablis, and songen|wid "alleluia"; si&thorn;in &thorn;e verset, and te abes te benicun;|And si&thorn;in foure lescuns red of &thorn;e new lay wid &thorn;at ilke|ordir by-fore.  Efter &thorn;e fer&thorn;e Respun, &thorn;abbes sal by-gynne|&thorn;is ymne: "Te deum laudamus."  When it is finist, &thorn;anne| sal &thorn;abbes by-ginne a lescun of &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="15a">gospel wid honur and
<PB N="17">|wyd &thorn;e dute of god; &thorn;an sal alle stande.  when it is red,|&thorn;e o&thorn;ir sal say amen; And tabbesse by-ginne: "Te decet|laus"; And giue &thorn;e benicun, and biginne matins.  &THORN;is|ordir sal be haldin euin-like opon &thorn;e sundais als wel in|sumir als in winter, bot if it sua be, &thorn;at ye rise ouir-late;|&thorn;an may ye make lesse lescun; bot loke &thorn;at it be-time yu|noht.  Loke &thorn;at it be endid wid al &thorn;at fallis &thorn;ar-to.  And|yef it fallis yu ani time, On waim &thorn;e for-getilnes es on-long|sal man take amendis for &thorn;at faute in &thorn;e kirke.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="12">
<HEAD>XII.</HEAD>
<P>At matins on &thorn;e feste-dais, First sal ye saie sexe|salmis wid-vten antefens, And si&thorn;in &thorn;e fyftyd|salme wid "alleluia."  wen &thorn;ai ar said, &thorn;e hundred seuintende|and &thorn;e sextid &thorn;e secunde, si&thorn;in &thorn;e benichune, and|a leschun red of &thorn;a apocalips wid gude deuocion, &amp; te|respun, and te ymne ambrosine, and te uerset, and te|antefen of &thorn;e gospel, &amp; te letanie, and sent forz.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>forz</I>; z has a peculiar shape, reminding of the sign for <I>and</I>.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="14">
<HEAD>XIV.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;e haly dais al sal be als we haue bi-fore saide id|on &thorn;e sundais, Bot &thorn;at te salmis and te antefens|and te lescuns be saide als <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="15b">fallis to &thorn;e day.  Bot te vse |bi-fore be haldin.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="15">
<HEAD>XV.</HEAD>
<P>Fra &thorn;e paskis til &thorn;e witsundai salle "alleluia" be|saide wid-vten entirual als wel at te salmis als at|te respuns.  And fra &thorn;e witsunday til &thorn;e lentyn sal it ilke|niht be saide wid &thorn;e sexe last salmis of te nocturne.  Ilke|sunday wid-uten lentin sal &thorn;e cantikils be said wid "alleluia,"|Matins, Prime, Vndrin, Midday, Noon; Al be saide|wid "alleluia"; Bot te respuns noht Bot fra &thorn;e paskis til|&thorn;e witsunday.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="16">
<HEAD>XVI.</HEAD>
<P>Als te prophete sais: "Sepcies in die laudem dixi|tibi&mdash;Seuin si&thorn;e o-po day saie I louing to &thorn;e."|Whilke haly seuin sy&thorn;e er &thorn;a &thorn;at sal be ful-fild wid vs o|&thorn;is maner, yef we folih &thorn;e vris of god: Of Matins, Of|prime, of Vndrin, Of Midday, Of noon, Of euensang, Of
<PB N="18">|cumplin.  Of &thorn;es times sais he: "seuin sy&thorn;e o-po day saie|I louing to &thorn;e."  Til &thorn;a &thorn;at rysis o night and wakis Sais|vre lauerd: "My frende, o niht ras I for yu and wakid."|For &thorn;i sal ye giue louing til hym, in &thorn;e iugiment of hys| rihtvisnes,<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="16a"> at matins, at prime, at vndern, At midday,|at noon, at euensang, at cumplin; And<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>, MS. <I>At</I>.</NOTE> o nith ryse for|to loue hym.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="17">
<HEAD>XVII.</HEAD>
<P>Now haue we deuisid &thorn;e ordir of &thorn;e salmis on &thorn;e|niht, at matins.  Loke we now tyl &thorn;e vris &thorn;at|folihis.  At prime &thorn;re salmis ilkain by &thorn;am ane.  &THORN;e ymne|of &thorn;is ilke vre sal be saide efter &thorn;is verse: "Deus in adiutorium|meum," Are ye beginne te salme.  when &thorn;e &thorn;re|salmis ere saide, a lescun sal be red, and si&thorn;in &thorn;e vers,|And "Kyryeleison," and finist &thorn;e hure.  Vndern, Midday,|Noon wid &thorn;at ilke ordir be sungen, &thorn;at is, wid vers, wid|ymnis &thorn;at fallis to &thorn;aim, &thorn;re salmis, and lescuns, and vers,|and "Kyryeleison"; And sua finise &thorn;e vres.  &THORN;e salmis sal|be sung wid antefens, yef &thorn;e cuuent be mikil; And yef &thorn;ai|be fa, saie it plane forde.  Bot euensang sal be saide wid|foure salmes And te Antefens, And efter &thorn;e salmis A|lescun, &amp; si&thorn;in &thorn;e respun, and si&thorn;in &thorn;e ymne and te|verset, &thorn;e cantikyl of &thorn;e gospel, and te letanie, And sy&thorn;in|&thorn;e "Pater noster."  O &thorn;is maner sal &thorn;e vris be sent forde.| Cumplin <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="16b">sal be saide wid &thorn;re salmis wid-vten antefens,|&amp; si&thorn;in &thorn;e ymne &thorn;at fallis &thorn;ar-to, A lescun, and te verset,|&amp; si&thorn;in "Kyryeleison," and te benicun, and sent forde &thorn;e|vris til god.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="18">
<HEAD>XVIII.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet cumandis &thorn;at tis &thorn;ing be haldin, &thorn;at yure|"Pater noster" be saide hezelike at matins and at|euinsang, for &thorn;e sclandir &thorn;at hauis ben of religiun &thorn;at|cu&thorn;e not noht<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>not noht</I>, evidently wrong, possibly|for <I>not all</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;aire "pater noster."  Ilkain ah at<NOTE PLACE="foot">ah at, MS. ahat to; cf. p. 22, l. 11 and footnote.</NOTE> quite|&thorn;am of &thorn;is vice.  Alle ah at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ah at</I>, MS. <I>ahat to</I>; cf. p. 22, l. 11 and footnote.</NOTE> cune &thorn;air "Pater noster"|&thorn;at in religiun wil be als god cumandis. for ye sal vmbe&thorn;inke|yu what resun fallis to &thorn;is vers, when ye it saie:|"Et dimitte nobis debita nostra, sicut &amp; nos dimittimus
<PB N="19">|debitoribus nostris."  &THORN;an prai we &thorn;us: "Lauerd, &thorn;u forgiue|vs ure sinnis, als we for-giue &thorn;aim &thorn;aire fautes &thorn;at|hauis mis-don a-gain vs."  When ye here &thorn;is vers at|matins, ye sal for-giue alle men &thorn;aire trespas for &thorn;e loue|o gode.  And als-sua at euinsang sal &yogh;e for-giue. for &thorn;i|wil sain benet &thorn;at it be saide hezlike, for alle wrezis sal|be for-giuin.  Lauerd giue vs sua at liue, &amp; sua at forgiue,|&thorn;at we may ga &thorn;e riht gate til heuin.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="19">
<HEAD>XIX.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="17a">In &thorn;is sentence tellis sain benet hu ye sal do yure office, |when ye cume in-to &thorn;e kyrke.  Ye sal true &thorn;at god|may se in alle stedis ba&thorn;e vyl &amp; gude.  Ye az at say yure|seruise als ye stode by-fore god, wyd als gude deuocyon,|And think wat te prophete saide: "Seruite domino &amp;c.;&mdash;Ye|sal serue god wyd ahe, &amp; here hym wyd dowte."|And in o&thorn;ir stede sais he: "Psallite&mdash;ye sal singe god|wyslike"; Als haly write sais: "In conspectu &amp;c.;&mdash;Lauerd,|I sing to &thorn;e in &thorn;e siht of &thorn;in angels to loue &thorn;e."  loke|ye do yure seruise als ye stode by-fore god almihti.  And|lokis, when ye sing, &thorn;at yure herte acorde wid yure voice;|&thorn;an sing ye riht.  Lauerd, &thorn;u giue vs sua vre seruise at|do, to &thorn;e felazscap of angels &thorn;at we may cum.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="20">
<HEAD>XX.</HEAD>
<P>Sain benet spekis in &thorn;is sentence til hys cuuent, and|kennys &thorn;am how &thorn;ai sal make &thorn;air prayer to god &amp;|wid what reuerence.  When ye wyl aske any thing at a|ryche man in ertht, ye aske ful mekelike yure erande.|wyd mekil mare deuociun ahte ye &thorn;anne at pray to god,|of whaim &thorn;at al &thorn;e gude cumis. yure antente sal be &thorn;at ye|ne sal noght be herde for yure many wordis; bot scort|vrisun, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="17b">and wyd deuocion, and wyd terys of herte; for &thorn;i |sal yure vrisun be breue &amp; clene, Bot yef it sua bi-tide,|&thorn;at any falle in mis-trouz; &thorn;an sal scho pray gerne to god.|Bot te cuuent vrisun sal be breue, &thorn;at ere in stedfast trouz.|Lauerd, we prai &thorn;e &thorn;at we may suilke vrisun make, &thorn;at it|be to &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;i</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE> wil.  AmeN.
</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="21">
<PB N="20">
<HEAD>XXI.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence spekys sain Benet of &thorn;a &thorn;at sal be in|officis, and bidis, yef &thorn;e cuuent be mikil, &thorn;at tay|sal be chossin &thorn;at sal &thorn;e officis yeme, And by-kenne it|taim &thorn;at best can serue god &amp; te cuuent; als tabbesse|cumandis taim sal &thorn;ai do.  &THORN;abbes ah at set nan &thorn;ar-to|bot &thorn;at scho is sikir offe, &thorn;oz &thorn;ai be noht &thorn;e ordenest, bot|&thorn;at tay be of clene lif and leel.  Yef any waxe prude in|hir office, man sal byd hyr amend hyr Ane tyme, and a-no&thorn;ir|tyme, And &thorn;e &thorn;irdde tyme.  Yef &thorn;ai wil noht a-mende|sua, man sal do &thorn;am ut of &thorn;air bayly, And do a-no&thorn;ir|in hir stede, &thorn;at man ses es dingne.  Sain benet|cumandis, yef priuresse be prudde, &thorn;at man sal do sua|wid hir.  Lauerd, &thorn;u giue vs sua vre office at do and| resun at yelde, &thorn;at we may cume til ioy <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="18a">&thorn;at lastes ay.|Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="22">
<HEAD>XXII.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet spekys here, and kennis yu hu ye sal|slape ilkain in bedde by &thorn;am ane, al wid ordir, als|tabbesse lokys taym.  Yef yt sua may be, alle sal lie in|a hus, &thorn;at ilkain wite of o&thorn;ir.  Yef &thorn;e hus be ouyr-litel,|summe sal lie in a-no&thorn;ir huse, ten ou&thorn;ir tuenty.  Bot te|eldest be wyd &thorn;am for to yeme &thorn;aim. &amp; &thorn;at ye haue|liht al &thorn;e nyht brinnande.  Ye sal lie clad and beltyd.|Knyvys sal ye haue nane by yure bed, nou&thorn;ir gret ne|smal.  When &thorn;e bel ringis, &thorn;at ye be redy, and ilkain|help o&thorn;ir, and ga in-to &thorn;e kyrke til godys seruise.  &THORN;e|nouice beddis sal be &thorn;at nane &thorn;aire may nehe o&thorn;ir; Bytuix|&thorn;alde &thorn;ai sal lie.  Man sal wakin &thorn;aim faire til godis|seruise.  Lauerd giue vs sua for to lie and sua for to rise,|&thorn;at we may haue &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at lastes ay.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="23">
<HEAD>XXIII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence leris sain Benet hys cuuent hu &thorn;aire|fautes sal be amendid.  Yef any be of grete herte|and wyl noht be buxum, ou&thorn;ir prud, ou&thorn;ir ani greuching| make aigain haly religiun, ou&thorn;ir &thorn;e cumandement <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="18b">hauis|in despit, &thorn;a &thorn;at ere of suilke dedis, Priuelike man sal|amoneste &thorn;am, &thorn;at tay amende &thorn;aim. yef &thorn;ay wyl noht
<PB N="21">|amende sua, &thorn;ai sal be broht by-fore &thorn;e cuuent and tare|amende hir faute.  Yef sho wyl not yet amende, sho sal|be cursyd. yef sho be a fole &amp; ful of iuil, and mas na|force of &thorn;e cursing, sho sal be berid ful wel, and do hir<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hir</I>, MS. <I>it</I>; cf. p. 25, l. 16.</NOTE>|a-mende it sua.  Lauerde schilde vs fra &thorn;at cursing; and|yef ani &thorn;ar-inne be, god for his grace bringe &thorn;am vte.|AmeN.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="24">
<HEAD>XXIV.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence mustirs sain Benet Hu man sal do|wid &thorn;aim &thorn;at es in sentence, &amp; bidis &thorn;at man sal|do &thorn;aim efter &thorn;aire faute es.  Yef &thorn;e faute be litil, &thorn;ai sal|make &thorn;e cuuent at wite and a-ioingne hir &thorn;ar-eftir.  Wylys|sho is in sentence, sho ne sal noht be in cuuent, til it be|amendid, In kirke ne salme beginne ne antefin, lescun|nan rede. sho sal [ete] when<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sal when</I>.</NOTE> alle hauis etin.  Yef &thorn;ai ete|at midday, sho salle ete at noon; yef &thorn;ai ete at noon, sho|sal ete at euin, als te ordir sais, til sho haue amendid hir|faute.  Lauerd giue vs sua vre scrifte at do, &thorn;at we may|hys rengne cum to.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="25">
<HEAD>XXV.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet spekys in &thorn;is sentence til &thorn;a &thorn;at ere fallen|in greuer faute, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="19a">Hu &thorn;ai sal amende.  &THORN;ai ne |sal noht cum in &thorn;e kirke, na in fraitur, Bot yef &thorn;abbesse|cumande hir.  Nan sal comun wid hir, Bot an &thorn;at es set|til hir.  Wid greting sal sho do, and wyd reu&thorn;e of herte,|&thorn;e penance &thorn;at es laid on hir; sua salle hir fautes be|mendid. for sain paul sais &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;at dos wicke dedis, &thorn;at|tay giue &thorn;am-selfe til &thorn;e deuil. for &thorn;i ah &thorn;ai at be chastid,|&thorn;at te saule ga noht til helle.  And ta &thorn;at ere in cursing,|&thorn;ai ah at dreze &thorn;aire penance wid reu&thorn;e of herte and be|sari of &thorn;air dede, &thorn;at te deuil haue na pouste ouir &thorn;aim.|sho sal ete al-ane suilke als tabes cumandis hir; nan sal|blisse hir mete.  Lauerd for his grace, he silde vs fra|suilke paine.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="26">
<HEAD>XXVI.</HEAD>
<P>Sain benet sais in &thorn;is sentence: yef any sistir ou&thorn;ir|bro&thorn;ir of &thorn;ordir be sua hardi at comun wid hir,|wid-vten cumandement of &thorn;abbes, wid speche, ou&thorn;ir ani
<PB N="22">|erand sendis til hir, suil[ke]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>suil</I>, for <I>suilke</I>, or <I>suilk</I>, or possibly <I>suik</I>; cf. p. 31,|l. 32.</NOTE> sentence sal sho haue.  Lauerd|for his grace, he gete vs fra &thorn;at sen[ten]ce<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sence</I>.</NOTE> and fra alle o&thorn;ir.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="27">
<HEAD>XXVII.</HEAD>
<P>In al maner, sais sain benet, sal &thorn;abbesse ta yeme of| &thorn;a &thorn;at mis-dose; for &thorn;e hale hauis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="19b">na mister o|miri, Bot te seke hauis mister.  For &thorn;i sal sho do als te|wyse miri dos, &thorn;at wyl hele &thorn;e seke.  Priuelike sal sho|sende an ordane nunne til hir &thorn;at es in sentence at comforth|hir, and for to turne hir wylle til amendement and|til mekenes, and for to moneste hir &thorn;at sho haue reu&thorn;e in|herte of hir misdedis and riht trouz; Als sain paul &thorn;apostil|sais: "Mikil charite mustirs he."  al ah at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ahat</I>.</NOTE> prai for|hym.  On alle maner sal &thorn;abbes entirmete hir Al maner|of sentence at muster til hir sep, &thorn;at nan be tint. for wyte|sho wel sho hauis vnder-tan &thorn;e saules at gede, And noht|at striue o-gain &thorn;aim.  Bot sho sal haue dute of &thorn;at vre|lauerd saide wyd &thorn;e prophete til &thorn;e hirdis of haly kirke:|"Quod crassum videbatis &amp;c.;&mdash;&THORN;at fat ere, sal ye ta; &thorn;at|ere febyl let ga."  &THORN;is is at vnder-stande, &thorn;at so ne sal|noht entirmete hir sua mikil of &thorn;a &thorn;at ere strang and hale|als of &thorn;a &thorn;at ere febyl and seke.  O &thorn;is maner sal &thorn;abbesse|folize &thorn;e saumpyl of Iesu, &thorn;e gude herde, &thorn;at lefte in &thorn;e|munte ane wane of a hundrez sep, and yede at seke &thorn;is|ane &thorn;at was want.  When he hauid funden it, sa fain he|was; he toke it on his haly schuldirs and broht it til| &thorn;o&thorn;ir.  &THORN;is is at vnderstande <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="20a">&thorn;at he lefte in heuin &thorn;e|felascap of angels and com in-til er&thorn;e at laite &thorn;e man &thorn;at|was tint; sua mekyl pyte hauid he of hym, &thorn;at he &thorn;urz his|haly grace by-com man &amp; bar manes kinde til &thorn;e felazscap|of angels til paradis, where-in Adam fel for hys synne.|Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue vs grace sua at wirke, &thorn;at we til|&thorn;at felazscap may cume.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="28">
<HEAD>XXVIII.</HEAD>
<P>Sain benet sais: yef any be tane ofte in faute, and|sho be cursid, and wyl noht yet amende, wyd|smerte beting sal sho be chastyd.  Yef sho wyl noht o
<PB N="23">|&thorn;is maner a-mende, bot wid pride defende hir dede, &thorn;an|sal &thorn;abbes do als te sleze miri: wen sho hauis laid hir|plaisters and hir vinemens wid faire wordis and te medicinis|of haly writ, and cursid hyr, &amp; berid, And may noht|helpe do hir best, &thorn;abbes &amp; al &thorn;e cuuent sal pray for hir|to god, &thorn;at he make hyr hale.  Yef sho may noht be hale|of &thorn;at maner, sho sal be done oute of &thorn;air felahscap;|Als te apostil sais: "Auferte malum &amp;c.;&mdash;Do a-way &thorn;e|wycke fra yu."  And in o&thorn;ir stede sais he: "Infidelis &amp;c.;&mdash;yef|so be vnleel, do hyr A-way." for a wicke shep|may spille al &thorn;e flok.  Lauerd, yef it be &thorn;i wille, &thorn;u|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="20b">gete vs fra &thorn;is sentence. </P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="29">
<HEAD>XXIX.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence sais sain Benet &thorn;at wha sam es &thorn;urz|&thorn;aire dedis don out of &thorn;e kirke and wil cum i-gain,|At te begining sal sho haite a-mendement of hir faute warfore|sho was don ut; &thorn;anne sal so be recaiuid, And don|at te laste ende for to loke hir mekenes.  Yef sho gas ut|a-no&thorn;ir tyme, &thorn;ris shal sho be recaiuid sua; bot si&thorn;in wite|sho wel es tare<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>es tare</I>, MS. <I>eftare</I>.</NOTE> na cuming a-gain.  Lauerd for his grace|defend vs fra &thorn;is vice.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="30">
<HEAD>XXX.</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;is sais sain benet, &thorn;at ta &thorn;at ere of elde and vnderstandis,|&thorn;ai sal haue &thorn;aire mesur; &amp; for &thorn;i &thorn;e barnis|&thorn;at ere yunge, &thorn;at vnderstandis noht what paine fallis til|cursing, when &thorn;ai misdo, wid fasting ou&thorn;ir wid smerte|beriing sal &thorn;ai be chastid; &thorn;ar-&thorn;urz sal &thorn;ai be helid.|Lauerd, for yure pite ye gete vs fra sinne, ba&thorn;e yunge &amp;|alde.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="31">
<HEAD>XXXI.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence sais sain benet &thorn;at te celeresse sal be|chosin of &thorn;e cuuent, &thorn;at sho be meke, and sobur,|and noht of mekil mete, ne prude, ne noius, ne wrangdoande,|ne latte, ne wastande, Bot god dutande; Of al|&thorn;is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="21a">sal ye ta yeme.  Wid-vten &thorn;e cumandement of &thorn;abbes |sal sho na &thorn;ing do.  &THORN;at sho cumandis hir sal sho do,
<PB N="24">|bot sho sal [noht] noy<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sal noy</I>.</NOTE> hir sistirs.  Par auenture yef ani|man askis hir ohte &thorn;at es a-gain resun, sho sal noht for &thorn;i|haue &thorn;am in despit, ne mis-ancewer &thorn;am, Bot mekelike saie|naie of &thorn;aire ful asking.  Ouir al thing sal sho gete hir|saul &amp; &thorn;incke what ta apostil sais: "Qui bene &amp;c.;&mdash;wha|sua seruis wel, mede by-fore god sal he haue."  Of &thorn;e seke,|and of &thorn;e barnis, And of gestys, and of &thorn;e pouir sal sho|take yeme eftir hir miht.  For wite ye wel &thorn;at sho sal|yelde resun o domes-day of alle hir dedis.  &THORN;e vassels &thorn;at|fallis til hir mester sal sho yeme als onestelike als te|vassels &thorn;at ere halized obute &thorn;auter. for-getil ah sho noht|to be, Ne ouir-mikil haue, Ne ouir-mikil waste of &thorn;at|fallis to &thorn;e huse, Bot alle &thorn;ingis do wid mesur, als tabbes|cumandis hir.  Ouir &thorn;at sho be buxum.  And when sho|hauis noht at giue, &thorn;at sho anscewer &thorn;aim faire, als hali|writ bidis: "Sermo bonus &amp;c.;&mdash;Gode speche es better|&thorn;an grete gifte"; And do &thorn;at tabbes cumandis hir; and|tat sho defendis, do it noht.  Sho sal grai&thorn;e &thorn;e cuuent|mete wid-vten greuching<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>greuehing</I>.</NOTE> and wid-vten duelling, &thorn;at tay| be noht sclaundird; And &thorn;incke what vre <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="21b">lauerd sais|in &thorn;e gospel of &thorn;aim &thorn;at sclandirs ani of his barnis: "him|ware wel bettir," he sais, "&thorn;at a milnestane ware a-bute|his hals in &thorn;e deppest of &thorn;e se."  Yef &thorn;e cuuent be|mikil, &thorn;e celeresse sal haue a felaze at helpe hir, &thorn;at sho|wid gode wil may do hir labur &thorn;at es bitaht hir, &thorn;at sho|may do in time &thorn;at sho ah for to do, &thorn;at nan be wre[t]hid<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>wrehid</I>.</NOTE>|ne noid in godis hus.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue hir sua|hir office at do, &thorn;at so may haue &thorn;anc o god and of &thorn;e|cuuent.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="32">
<HEAD>XXXII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at tabbesse sal|ta yeme of alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at fallis til &thorn;e hus, and of|vstilement and o&thorn;ir &thorn;ingis sal sho<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sho</I>, MS. <I>mo</I>.</NOTE> puruaie o lif and ded|&thorn;at so be sikir, and cumande til ilkain &thorn;at sho ses ned at|do.  Sho sal haue &thorn;am enbreuid, alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at fallis til|&thorn;e hus, for to wite what sho recauis and what sho giuis,|when sho sal remue &thorn;at ere in officis. yef ani haue ille
<PB N="25">|wroht wid &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at was bitaht &thorn;aim at yeme, sho sal be|apreuid;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>aperuid</I>.</NOTE> yef sho wil noht mend, &thorn;e iugiment sal sho|suffir.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue vs wel at yeme &thorn;is|sentence And alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ir.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="33">
<HEAD>XXXIII.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="22a">Of propirte spekis sain Benet, and sais &thorn;at of alle |o&thorn;ir vices sal man fle &thorn;is, &thorn;at nan be sua hardy,|&thorn;at tay o-way do ne giue na &thorn;ing wid-vten leue of &thorn;abbesse,|ne &thorn;at nane haue &thorn;ing in propirte, boke ne tabils,|ne nan o&thorn;ir &thorn;ing; for nan may haue &thorn;air ahen body at hys|wylle ne at tair pouste.  &thorn;ai sal haue alle &thorn;ingis at tabbes|&thorn;at tay haue nede of.  &thorn;ai sal haue na thing bot &thorn;at tabbesse|deliuirs taim.  &THORN;at ane hauis sal be comun til alle;|Als haly boke cumandis: nan sal calle &thorn;at tay haue &thorn;air|azen.  Yef it be an &thorn;at delitis tam in &thorn;is vice, And wil not|do it, Man sal saie til hir an time, and a-no&thorn;ir time, and|te &thorn;ridde.  Yef so wil noht amende sua, Man sal do hir|amende on o&thorn;ir maner.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i pite defende vs fra|&thorn;is vice.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="34">
<HEAD>XXXIV.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at tabbes sal|do als ta-postils did at te begining of cristiante: &thorn;ai|departid &thorn;air &thorn;ing til &thorn;a &thorn;at hauid nede.  "&thorn;ai departid,"|als hali writ sais, "til ilkain, als tay hauid ned." sua salle|&thorn;abbes do.  sho salle noht loke what man he es and of|what kinredin, Bot te sekenes of ilkain, and do &thorn;am efter|&thorn;at tay haue ned.  til god sal sho yelde grace, and noht be|sari of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="22b">hir gifte &thorn;at so hauis giuin til &thorn;a &thorn;at hauis mare |nede &thorn;an sho.  Tyl &thorn;e nedful sal sho meke hir for in|ire sekenes, And noht bere hir heze for &thorn;e helpe &thorn;at god|hauis lent hir; And o this maner sal al liue in pais.  Ouir|al &thorn;ing sal &thorn;ai loke &thorn;e wicke &thorn;at ere imangis &thorn;aim; and yef|&thorn;are be ani funden, wid smerte beriing sal &thorn;ai be amendid.|Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue vs miht at fle al iuils.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="35">
<HEAD>XXXV.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence bidis sain Benet &thorn;at ye sal serue sua,|&thorn;at nan be quit of &thorn;e seruise of &thorn;e kichin, Bot yef|&thorn;ai be acumbird wid sekenes ou&thorn;ir wid odir laburs; for
<PB N="26">|man sal haue grete mede for &thorn;at seruise.  Til &thorn;a &thorn;at ere|febil sal ye finde helpe and cumforth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cumforth</I>, r above the line, t apparently expuncted.</NOTE> &thorn;at tay ne serue noht|wid ouir-mikil noye.  Al sal haue comfort eftir &thorn;at &thorn;e|cuuent is mikil, and efter &thorn;ai ere in ese to serue.  Yef &thorn;e|cuuent be mikil, &thorn;e celeresse sal be quit of &thorn;e seruise of &thorn;e|kichin, And ta &thorn;at ere acumbird wid laburs.  &THORN;is o&thorn;ir sal|serue al wid luue.  &THORN;a &thorn;at ere out of &thorn;aire wuke sal opo|&thorn;e setirday ma &thorn;e maunde, and waisse &thorn;e tuailis &thorn;at tay|sal wipe &thorn;aire hend opon and taire fete.  &THORN;a &thorn;at ga ut of|&thorn;e wuke, and te to&thorn;ir &thorn;at cumis in, sal waisse &thorn;e o&thorn;ir fete| at te <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="23a">maunde.  &thorn;e vassels &thorn;at tay serue wid, sal &thorn;ai ta|yeme to, &amp; yelde &thorn;ame til &thorn;e celeresse clene and hale; and|sho sal loke what sho yeldis &amp; what sho recaiuis.  &THORN;a &thorn;at|serue o &thorn;e kichin sal miste bi-fore &thorn;e mikil mete bred,|butter, &thorn;at tay may serue wid-vten gruching and wid-vten|noy.  And so &thorn;at gas vt of &thorn;e wuke, and so &thorn;at cumis in,|sal recaiue &thorn;e benichun at morne at matins.  Sho &thorn;at gas ut|sal say &thorn;is vers &thorn;ris by-for &thorn;auter, and al &thorn;e cuuent eftir:|"Benedictus es."  &THORN;an so hase rechaiuid &thorn;e benichun, &thorn;an|sal &thorn;e to&thorn;ir, &thorn;at sal serue eftir hir, cume by-fore &thorn;auter|and saie &thorn;is vers &thorn;ris, and alle &thorn;e cuuent eftir: "Deus, in|adiutorium"; And si&thorn;in rechaiue &thorn;e benichun, &thorn;at god|giue hir grace at serue &thorn;aim to pay.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i grace|giue vs sua at serue, &thorn;at we may [haue] vre<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>may vre</I>; cf. p. 37, l. 4.</NOTE> mede of &thorn;e.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="36">
<HEAD>XXXVI.</HEAD>
<P>Of &thorn;e seke spekis sain benet in &thorn;is sentence, And|cumandis ouir al &thorn;ing &thorn;at man sal ta yeme of|&thorn;aim, &thorn;at tay be serued als it ware god him-selfe.  For he sal|say on domis-day: "I was seke, ye visit; &thorn;at ye did til|an of myne, ye did it me."  Bot tay sal recaiue in &thorn;e onur|of god &thorn;e seruise &thorn;at man dos tam; &thorn;ai ne sal noht &thorn;urz| &thorn;air surfait noy &thorn;aire sistirs &thorn;at seruis tam.  Bot <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="23b">yef it|sua be, &thorn;at taire iuil be sua mikil, man sal suffir &thorn;aim &thorn;e|mare and be of pacience, for of &thorn;aim sal man haue grete|mede of god.  &THORN;abbesse tal ta yeme of &thorn;e seke &thorn;at tay|haue na defaute.  A hus sal &thorn;ai haue bi &thorn;am ane.  And|tat so &thorn;at sal serue &thorn;am dute gode, and do hir miht for to
<PB N="27">|serue &thorn;am wel and wid luue.  &THORN;ai sal haue at ete alle timis|&thorn;at tay haue mister of; bot til &thorn;e hale, &thorn;at mai wel ete,|and til &thorn;e yunge sal man giue latter.  &THORN;e seke &thorn;at ere febil|sal man giue fleis at ete at couir &thorn;am wid-al.  &THORN;abbes sal|do hir antente to &thorn;e seke, &thorn;at tay haue na defaute for &thorn;e|forgetilnes of &thorn;e celeresse and of &thorn;e fermerier; For sho sal|a-mende al at tay misdo.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci gete vs fra|alle iuils of body &amp; sal.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="37">
<HEAD>XXXVII.</HEAD>
<P>Of &thorn;e alde &amp; of &thorn;e barnis spekis sain benet in &thorn;is|sentence, And sais &thorn;at taire elde prais &thorn;at man sal|giue &thorn;am charite, als te reule es set to &thorn;aire mete; bot|mikil pite birs man haue, &thorn;at tay sal ete ar &thorn;e o&thorn;ir.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="38">
<HEAD>XXXVIII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain benet &thorn;at te lescun sal|noht faile at mete.  O &thorn;is maner sal &thorn;is be stabilist,|&thorn;at nan ta &thorn;e boke at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="24a">rede bot sho &thorn;at sal rede al &thorn;e |wuke; sho sal beginne o-po &thorn;e sunday.  sho sal cum by-fore|&thorn;auter o &thorn;e sunday efter &thorn;e messe and say &thorn;ris &thorn;is|verse, and al &thorn;e cuuent eftir: "Domine, labia mea aperies,"|And recaiue &thorn;e benediccion, &thorn;at gete hir fra pride.  &THORN;ai|sal halde silence at te borde, &thorn;at na uoice be herde bot of|hir &thorn;at redis.  &THORN;a &thorn;at serue sal ta yeme til &thorn;am &thorn;at etes,|&thorn;at tay haue na defaute of &thorn;at tay sal haue, wharfore &thorn;ai|make na noise.  Yef <NOTE PLACE="foot">The subject (<I>ani</I>, or the like) is omitted.</NOTE> wil aske ani thing, sho salle make|sinis and noght speke.  Nane sal speke of na demande in|&thorn;e lescun, whar-of noise may rise.  Bot tabbesse, yef sho|wille, sho may breuelike,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Possibly|the verb <I>speke</I> is omitted before or after <I>breuelike</I>.</NOTE> a sentence for to amende.  sho|&thorn;at sal rede sal miste ay litil, be-fore sho rede, &thorn;at sho ne|be not ouir-mikil engreuid.  Ye sal ordain nane for to|rede bot &thorn;at can do &thorn;e ofice, &thorn;at may pai al &thorn;at it heris.|Lauerd, for his grace, he giue vs sua for to rede and singe,|&thorn;at we may pai hym and al &thorn;at vs heris.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="39">
<HEAD>XXXIX.</HEAD>
<P>Of &thorn;e mesur of &thorn;e mete spekis sain benet in &thorn;is|sentence, And sais &thorn;at it es inoh, twane maner of
<PB N="28">|potage al &thorn;e wuke in &thorn;e tweluemonez, what tyme sam<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sain</I>.</NOTE>| ye ete, at midday ou&thorn;ir at none, &thorn;at tay &thorn;at may <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="24b">noght|ete of &thorn;e tane, lat &thorn;aim ete of &thorn;e to&thorn;ir.  &thorn;ir tua mese sal|&thorn;ai ilke day haue.  Yef &thorn;ai haue whar-of, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;rid de</I>.</NOTE> may|&thorn;ai haue of frute ou&thorn;ir of o&thorn;irkin felazscap.  A lafe of|brede mesurde es inoh o day ba&thorn;e at none and at euyn.|Yef &thorn;ai sal supe, &thorn;e celeres sal take &thorn;e &thorn;ridde parti of &thorn;e|lafe &amp; laie it by-fore &thorn;am at te super.  Yef tabbes ses &thorn;ai|haue mikil trauaile, yef scho wil, scho may mende &thorn;am;|Bot gete &thorn;ar be nane owtrage, &thorn;at nane be costiue, ne nane|o&thorn;ir wil, &thorn;urz surfait o mete.  for na &thorn;ing es<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;inges</I>.</NOTE> als mikil|igain cristen men als gluterie; sua sais vre lord: "Videte|&amp;c.;&mdash;Loke yure hertis be noght noyd &thorn;urz gluterie o mete|ne drinke."  Til barnis sal man noht giue sua mikil als til|&thorn;alde for to gete mesur ouir al.  Of &thorn;e beste &thorn;at beris|foure fete sal nane ete bot ta &thorn;at ere seke and febil.|Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue vs sua mesur-like at ete, &thorn;at we|alle wils o bodi &amp; saul mai fle.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="40">
<HEAD>XL.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence spekis sain Benet Of &thorn;e mesur o|drink, and sais &thorn;at ilke man hauis propir gifte o|god in al maner; And for &thorn;i stabelis sain Benet with mikil|doute &thorn;e mesur of o&thorn;ir mens liflade.  Na-for-&thorn;i, for &thorn;e| febilnes <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="25a">of &thorn;a &thorn;at may noht for-bere, hauis he for-lokid|til ilkain a mesur of wyne of &thorn;e day, Ou&thorn;ir suilke als tabbesse|may furde; &thorn;e mesur es callid eminan; &thorn;ai ne mai|noht haue bot mesurlike anis &thorn;ar-of.  &THORN;a &thorn;at may be of|abstinens, mede of god sal &thorn;ai haue.  Yef &thorn;am by-houid|mare ou&thorn;ir for trauaile ou&thorn;ir for hete, In &thorn;e forloking of|&thorn;abbesse sal it be.  Bot sho sal loke &thorn;at &thorn;ai ne be not|ouir-ful ne drunkin.  We rede &thorn;at wyne, ne na drinke &thorn;at|wil make man drunkin, ne feris noht til men of religiun.|for &thorn;i &thorn;at te tyme is sua &thorn;at ye ne mai noht al for-bere, for|&thorn;i consentis sain Benet &thorn;at ye drinke ay litil, bot noht sua|mikil &thorn;at ye be ful; for ouir-mikil drinke dose man ofte|do folie.  Yef it be ani &thorn;at dar noht drinke hir mesur, &thorn;ai|sal grace god and gruche noht.  Ouir alle &thorn;inges loke ye
<PB N="29">|ne be noht gruchande of na &thorn;ing.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i pite gete|vs fra gruching and fra ouir-mikil drinke, sua &thorn;at we mai|haue &thorn;i grace.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="41">
<HEAD>XLI.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence sais sain Benet &thorn;at ye sal ete twise of|&thorn;e day ilke day fra &thorn;e haly paskis til &thorn;e witsunday;|and si&thorn;in til &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="25b">hali rodis dai in semtembir, Al &thorn;e |wukis in &thorn;e summir,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>summir</I>; one of the four downstrokes required to make <I>-mi-</I> is|missing.</NOTE> sal ye faste ilke wuke tua dais, &thorn;e|wedenisdai and te fryday, bot yef ye haue mikil trauaile,|ou&thorn;ir feeste-day, ou&thorn;ir it be mikil hete; &thorn;an relesses sain|Benet yu &thorn;e fasting of &thorn;a tua dais, Als tabbesse forlokis.|sua sal sho ordain and a-tempir al hir &thorn;ingis, &thorn;at &thorn;e saulis|of hir disciplis mai sauf be; And at tay do wid-vtyn|gruching &thorn;at tay sal do.  Fra &thorn;e haly rodes day til &thorn;e|lentyn sal ye fast ilk day, bot if it be for heze feste.  Fra|&thorn;e beginning of lentyn til &thorn;e paskis sal ye ete eftir euensang,|bot it sal be sua, &thorn;at yu ne &thorn;arf na candil, bot al be|don by day alle tyme, ba&thorn;e when ye faste and when ye|ete tuis.  sua sal &thorn;e time be sett.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i grace|giue vs sua at be of discreciun ba&thorn;e of fastyng and of|mete, &thorn;at we mai be sauf.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="42">
<HEAD>XLII.</HEAD>
<P>Of silence eftir cumplin spekis sain Benet in &thorn;is|sentence, and bidis &thorn;at ye sal do yu payne at|halde silence eftir cumplin.  yef &thorn;e cuuent etis tuise, Als|tite as tay rise fra &thorn;e supere, &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai site wid ordir in|&thorn;e cloistir.  when colaciun ringis, &thorn;an salle alle asembil in|&thorn;e chapitir.  an <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="26a">sal rede &thorn;e lescun of &thorn;e halizis, ou&thorn;ir |of haly writ, for to comforth &thorn;aim &thorn;at it heris.  In &thorn;at|tyme sal ye noht rede &thorn;e boke of &thorn;e kingis, for nan vnait|sal be herde &thorn;at tyme for &thorn;a &thorn;at ere of febil &thorn;oht; In o&thorn;ir|tyme mai it be red.  yef it be fasting day, &thorn;ai sal haue|gode entirual, And when colaciun ringis, Alle &thorn;at &thorn;e belle|heris ga til to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>, for <I>te</I> (= <I>&thorn;e</I>)? or redundant (= <I>til</I>)?</NOTE> colaciun; And si&thorn;in eftir at cumplin; si&thorn;in|be nan sua hardy to speke. yef ani es tan wid-al, &thorn;at hauis|brokin silence eftir cumplin, smerte correccion salle man|take of hir.  yef gestis cume, and tabbesse cumandis at
<PB N="30">|speke, &thorn;at tare be nane vtrage.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue|vs miht at halde &thorn;is sentence als sain Benet cumandis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="43">
<HEAD>XLIII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence spekis sain Benet of &thorn;a &thorn;at cumis late|til &thorn;air seruise o god and til &thorn;e borde.  Als tite als|te belle es herde, ilkain sal leue &thorn;e werke &thorn;at es in &thorn;aire|hende, and rinne hastelike til &thorn;e ure<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>e</SUP><I>ure</I>.</NOTE> of god, &thorn;at na man|may telle foly to &thorn;am.  For na &thorn;ing sal man leue &thorn;e seruise|o god.  &thorn;a &thorn;at cumis noht at te begining of matins by-fore|&thorn;e "gloria patri" of &thorn;e "Venite," sal noht ga in-til &thorn;aire| stalle, bot sho sal ga til &thorn;e grece by-fore &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="26b">autir, &thorn;at|tabbes mai se and al &thorn;e cuuent; &thorn;are sal sho be til &thorn;abbes|giue hir leue at gange in-til hir stalle.  And for &thorn;i wil sain|Benet &thorn;at ta &thorn;at cume late ga til &thorn;e grece, &thorn;at tay haue|shame of &thorn;air faute and sua salle be amendid.  for suilke|mai it be &thorn;at duellis, &thorn;at &thorn;ai wil slape, Ou&thorn;ir &thorn;inke vnait,|whan &thorn;at &thorn;e deuil mai finde a-chesun in &thorn;am; for &thorn;i shal|sho ga to &thorn;e grece for to amende hir faute, &thorn;at sho amende|hir si&thorn;in forward.  At te huris als-sua, yef sho ne cumis|noht by-fore &thorn;e "gloria patri" of &thorn;e first salme, sho sal|ga to &thorn;e grece and cum noht in hir stalle, are &thorn;abes cumande|hir; Bot sho sal haue nane o&thorn;ir penance for &thorn;at faute.|At te verse by-fore &thorn;e mete sal alle be asembild at te borde;|sho &thorn;at is noht tar-at, for hir neccligence man sal say til|hir ane tyme, and a-no&thorn;ir tyme.  Yef sho wylle noht|a-mende, sho ne sal noht ete wyd &thorn;e cuuent, bot by hir|ane, and &thorn;arne hyr part of &thorn;e drinke, suilke als te o&thorn;ir|haue, til sho haue amendid hir faute.  Als-suilke sal sho|haue &thorn;at es fra &thorn;e vers eftir &thorn;e mete; for &thorn;i es it forlokid,|&thorn;at ta &thorn;at er noht at te vers sal ga til &thorn;e grece bi-fore| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="27a">&thorn;e dese at say hir verse and aske leue at ete; si&thorn;in mai|sho ga at ete in hir ordir.  Nan sal ete ne drink bot at te|tyme &thorn;at o&thorn;ir ete, bot yef it be wyd leue.  Yef &thorn;abbesse|offirs ani &thorn;ing til ani of hir sisturs and sho refuse it, when|sho walde haue it, man salle noght giue it hir, Til sho|haue amendid hir faute.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i grace giue vs sua|at yeme &thorn;is sentence and al &thorn;e o&thorn;ir, &thorn;at we til &thorn;e ioy of|paradise mai cume.  AmeN.
</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="44">
<PB N="31">
<HEAD>XLIV.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence kennis sain Benet vs what amendement|&thorn;ai sal do &thorn;at es in cursing, &thorn;at es don owte of|&thorn;e kirke for greue faute and owte of &thorn;e fraitur.  At ilke|owre, when &thorn;e belle ringis, sal sho lie by-fore &thorn;e kirke dore|til alle &thorn;e cuuent be cumen in, And si&thorn;in rise vp and obied|wid-vten &thorn;e kirke dore to &thorn;e vre be sungen.  When &thorn;e|cuuent cumes forz owte of &thorn;e kirke, sho sal lie dun agayne|by-fore &thorn;e dore til &thorn;ai be passid.  &THORN;us sal sho do ilke|day til &thorn;abbesse bidde hir leue.  When sho sal be asoilid,|sho sal cume in-til &thorn;e chapitir and take hir veine by-fore|&thorn;abbesse and crie hir merci.  When &thorn;abes asoiles hir, sho|sal falle til hir fete, &amp; si&thorn;in by-twixe tua and tua o knees,|and take <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="27b">hir veine.  &THORN;an salle sho site &thorn;ar &thorn;abbes |cumandis hir, bot noht in hir ordir; bot sho ne salle noht|by-ginne in kirke antefin ne Respun, ne rede lescun, Bot|yef &thorn;abbes cumande hir.  Eftir "Benedicamus" at ilke|vre sal sho take hir veine on knes, whare sum sho standes|in &thorn;e quer.  &thorn;is sal sho do ay til &thorn;abbes cumande hir at|leue of &thorn;at penance. sho &thorn;at es done owte of &thorn;e fraitur for|lesse faute, In &thorn;e kirke sal sho amende o &thorn;is maner: At|ilke vre, when &thorn;ai say "Kirieleison," sal sho take hir veine|by-fore &thorn;e auter at te grece, &amp; ligge &thorn;are til &thorn;e "Benedicamus"|be saide. sua sal sho do til &thorn;abbes asoile hir,|And recaiue &thorn;e benecun.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i pite giue vs sua|at mende vre fautis, &thorn;at we may haue &thorn;i benicun.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="45">
<HEAD>XLV.</HEAD>
<P>Sain benet cumandis in &thorn;is sentence &thorn;at ta &thorn;at faile|in &thorn;e kirke at te minning of &thorn;e salmes, Ou&thorn;ir of &thorn;e|Respuns, Ou&thorn;ir Antefens, Ou&thorn;ir lescuns, At te er&thorn;e sal sho|take hir veine by-fore &thorn;am al. yef sho wil noht do it,|Greuer correccion sal man take of hir, for sho walde noht|with mekenes amende hir faute.  &THORN;e barnis sal man chasty|wid wande for suik mis-dede.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="28a">Lauerd, yef it be &thorn;i wil, |giue vs welle at halde &thorn;is sentence.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="46">
<HEAD>XLVI.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet sais: &thorn;a &thorn;at ere in laburs, In kichin ou&thorn;ir|in calgard, in gard ou&thorn;ir wid-vten, in ani labur,|and sho trespasse, Tinis &thorn;ingis ou&thorn;ir brekis, yef sho misdo,
<PB N="32">|o &thorn;is maner sal sho amende: sho sal cum in-til &thorn;e|chapitir bi-fore alle &thorn;e cuuent and take al hir veine, And|knaw hir faute wid hir azen wille.  Yef sho hydes it, and|a-no&thorn;ir sais hir owte, Greuer correccion sal man take of|hir &thorn;an sho hauid mustird it wid hir azen wille.  Yef it|be priue sinne &thorn;at wille a-noy &thorn;e saul, sho sal ga priuelike|til &thorn;abbesse and schriue hir, Ou&thorn;ir til a preste &thorn;at kan|hele hir of hir sinne.  Lauerd for his grace giue vs sua|at schriue vs, and sua at mend vre sinne, &thorn;at we til his|rengne mai ga.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="47">
<HEAD>XLVII.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet cumandis in &thorn;is sentence &thorn;at &thorn;abbes sal|take gude yeme &thorn;at &thorn;e vris of godis seruise be finist|right ba&thorn;e day and niht.  Ou&thorn;ir sho hir-selfe sal finise|&thorn;am, Ou&thorn;ir set a nunn in hir stede &thorn;at wil ententiuelike|do &thorn;e office o god.  &THORN;e salmes and te antefens sal &thorn;ai|biginne eftir hir wid ordir.  Nane sal be don til &thorn;at office| bot &thorn;at may singe and <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="28b">rede welle, &thorn;at alle &thorn;at heris be|edefied &thorn;er-of.  sho &thorn;at &thorn;abbes cumandis &thorn;is office, wid|mekenes sal sho do it, And stabelike wid-vten pride, And|wid &thorn;e dowte of god.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue vs sua|for to singe and rede, &thorn;at we mai do &thorn;i wille.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="48">
<HEAD>XLVIII.</HEAD>
<P>Of &thorn;e trauaile spekis sain Benet in &thorn;is sentence, and|sais &thorn;at vnait sete es il to &thorn;e saule.  For &thorn;i salle|ye trauaile times, And in &thorn;e times at lescuns, als it es|ordaind.  Fra &thorn;e paskis til &thorn;e Mihelmesse, when matins|es done til heze vndirn sal ye wirke, ilke day when time|es, &thorn;at es nede to do.  Fra vndirn to midday at lescuns.|Eftir midday, when &thorn;ai haue etin, sal ye reste in yure|bedde alle wid silence.  Yef any wille &thorn;at tyme loke|lescun, loke &thorn;at sho rede sua, &thorn;at sho ne noy noht &thorn;e o&thorn;ir.|Noon sal be rungen by tyme, And si&thorn;in wirke til euensang.|Yef &thorn;ai haue mikil at do, corn at gadir and o&thorn;ir laburs at|do, &thorn;ai salle noht gruche for &thorn;i; for &thorn;an liue ye right, yef|ye liue wid &thorn;e labur of yure hende, Als haly men did|bi-fore yu, &amp; ta-postils; bot mesurlike sal ye wirke for|&thorn;a &thorn;at ere febil.</P>
<P>
<PB N="33">Fra &thorn;e feeste of &thorn;e Mihthel til &thorn;e lentin, when prime|is sungen til vndern salle <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="29a">ye studie in lescuns. |fra vndern til noon salle ye wirke suilke as ye haue at do.|When noon ringis, ilkain sal lay downe &thorn;at es in &thorn;aire|hende, and ga til &thorn;e kirke; And eftir mete til lescuns|ou&thorn;ir salmes.  In lentin, fra prime til heze vndern sal ye|entende yure lescun, And sy&thorn;in wirke til noon.  At te|bigining of lentyn sal be broght in-til &thorn;e chapitur alle &thorn;e|bokis, and ilkain take &thorn;aris &amp; rede it ouir.  &THORN;abbesse sal|loke a simpil nunne ou&thorn;ir tua for to ga imangis taim atte|timis &thorn;at tay sal saie for to loke &thorn;at nane site vnait, And|for to loke wilke attendis mare til vnait &thorn;an til hir lescun.|&THORN;a &thorn;at ere funden suilke, for &thorn;i &thorn;at tay do iuil til &thorn;amselfe|and til<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>and til</I> twice.</NOTE> o&thorn;ir als-sua, &thorn;ai sal be warnid ane tyme, and|a-no&thorn;ir time.  Yef sho wil noht a-mende, Man sal take|suilke amendis of hir, &thorn;at te o&thorn;ir be warnid &thorn;urz hir.  At|te timis &thorn;at es set efter euensang til lescuns, &thorn;a &thorn;at ere|acumbird wid laburs sal noht studie on &thorn;e sundais, ne on|&thorn;e o&thorn;ir feste-dais, Bot to&thorn;ir alle at lescuns.  Yef it be ani|&thorn;at mai noht studie ne rede, O&thorn;ir labur sal &thorn;ai do, &thorn;at tay|ne sitte noht al dom.  &THORN;a &thorn;at ere noht in ese, man sal giue|&thorn;aim sum &thorn;ing at do, &thorn;at tay ne sitte noht vnait, Ne &thorn;at|tay ne be noght <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="29b">ouir-mikil greuid wid trauaile; &thorn;abbes |sal loke &thorn;aire sekenes.  Lauerd for his pite giue vs sua|to wirk, and sua vre lescuns at vnderstande, &thorn;at we at te|ende til heuin be broght.  Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="49">
<HEAD>XLIX.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence kennis vs sain Benet how we sal gete|&thorn;e tyme of lentin.  Alle timis of &thorn;e yer, he sais,|sulde we wid rihte halde &thorn;e liflade o lentin, bot faa it es|&thorn;at te vertu mai haue.  And for&thorn;ir<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for&thorn;ir</I>, "further," originally|<I>for &thorn;i</I>, "therefore," Lat. "ideo."  The i was written above the|line and easily changed into the abbreviation-mark for <I>ir</I>.</NOTE> cumandis he &thorn;at we|sal in lentin gete vre lif in alle &thorn;ing, &thorn;at we mai amende|vre fautes of o&thorn;ir times in &thorn;e dais of lentin.  &THORN;an may ye|sauflike liue, yef ye gete yu fra alle ille vices, And yef we|do vre entente til vresun wid teris And til lescuns wid|reu&thorn;e of herte and wid abstinens.  In &thorn;a dais sal we here|sum&thorn;ing of godis seruise mare &thorn;an we do an no&thorn;ir tyme,
<PB N="34">|And priue vresuns, and o mare mesur of mete and drinke.|Ilkain salle, wid &thorn;aire ahen gude wille, Offir sum &thorn;ing to|god mare &thorn;an &thorn;ai es cumandid, wid &thorn;e ioy of &thorn;e haly|sprite; &thorn;at es, ye draze yu mare fra mete and drinke, &amp;|fra slepe, and fra speche, And fra gabbingis, &thorn;at ye mai|haly paskis o-byde wid ioy of spiritel langing. bot ilkain| salle mustir til &thorn;abbesse what ye wille offir to god, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="30a">wid|yure azen wil, of vresuns; for yef ye ne do it wid leue of|yure spiritel fadir, ye ne sal haue na mede &thorn;ar-offe, bot|turne yu to vanite.  For &thorn;i sal ye do als tabbesse cumandis|yu at do.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i merci giue vs sua &thorn;is haly lentyn|at yeme, &thorn;at we mai wid ioy of &thorn;e hali spirit hali paskis|obide.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="50">
<HEAD>L.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at te sistirs &thorn;at|ere in labur fer fra &thorn;e kirke, and mai noht cume in|time til &thorn;aire vris, &thorn;abbes sal cumaunde &thorn;aim o &thorn;is maner,|&thorn;at whare sam &thorn;ai wirke, &thorn;at tay do godis seruise And|taire veinis in &thorn;e dute o god.  And als-sua &thorn;a &thorn;at aier by|&thorn;e gate, &thorn;ai ne sal noht leue &thorn;e vris &thorn;at ere stablist, bot sua|als tay mai, sai &thorn;aim And yelde god his seruise.  He giue|vs for his grace, &thorn;at we mai yelde &thorn;e seruise &thorn;at we ah til|hym.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="51">
<HEAD>LI.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet spekis of &thorn;a &thorn;at ere sent owte ani erand|and sal cum o-gain &thorn;at ilke day, &thorn;at tay ne be noht|sua hardy at ete owte, &thorn;oz man pray &thorn;aim, Bot yef &thorn;abbes|giue &thorn;aim leue; yef &thorn;ai do, &thorn;ai sal be cursid.  Lauerd for|&thorn;i, yef it be his wille, he kepe vs fra cursing.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="52">
<HEAD>LII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at &thorn;e ortorie be| nane o&thorn;ir &thorn;ing &thorn;an it es <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="30b">cald.  Of na &thorn;ing sal it|serue bot for to aure, man to god, inne.  When &thorn;e vris|of god es done, &thorn;anne sal alle ga forth and make reuerence|to god.  Yef any wille dwelle for to make priue vrisun,|sho ne sal make noise for to sturbe &thorn;e o&thorn;ir, Bot simpelike|gange in and make hir vresun wid teris and wid reu&thorn;e of|herte, And noht wid heze voice.  &THORN;a &thorn;at wil noht do, &thorn;ai|ne sal noht dwelle eftir in &thorn;e kirke for to noy &thorn;e o&thorn;ir.
<PB N="35">|Lauerd for his pite giue vs sua for to cuntaine vs in &thorn;e|kirke, &thorn;at nane be desturbid for vs.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="53">
<HEAD>LIII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at te gestis &thorn;at|cumis to yu be als faire kald als it ware god hymselfe.|for he salle say at te day of dome: "Hospes fui|&amp;c.;&mdash;&Iacute; was geste, and ye recaiuid me."  Alle sal man|comunlike recaiue, And men of religiun and pilgrims.|Als tit als te gestis cume, &thorn;e priuresse ou&thorn;ir a-no&thorn;ir nunne|sal gange againis tam wid luue &amp; charite.  Yef it be sistir,|first sal &thorn;ai anure to-gidir and si&thorn;in kis; bot bi-fore &thorn;e vre|sal &thorn;ai noht basse for &thorn;enticement of &thorn;e deuil.  Allekin|mekenes sal man muster til &thorn;e gestis.  Ilkain, when &thorn;ai|ga and when &thorn;ai cume, sal alure<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alure</I>, probably corrupt; see Notes.</NOTE> to-gidir ou&thorn;ir wid &thorn;e|heuidis ou&thorn;ir <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="31a">wid al &thorn;e bodi, and Iesu crist sal aure |&thorn;am.  When &thorn;ai ere rechaiuid and aurid, &thorn;abbesse sal|sitte wid &thorn;aim, ou&thorn;ir a-no&thorn;ir nunne, wilke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wilke</I>, i|omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE> sam sho cumandis,|&thorn;at can speke wid &thorn;aim o godis lay for to comfort|&thorn;aim and speke of man-hed.  &THORN;e fasting sal &thorn;abbesse breke|for &thorn;e gestis sake, yef sho will, Bot yef &thorn;e fasting be for|hez feste, &thorn;at sho ne may nan gate breke; bot to&thorn;er sal|foliz &thorn;e reule o fasting. &thorn;abbesse sal giue &thorn;e gestis water|til &thorn;aire hende, And waisse &thorn;aire feet, And alle &thorn;e cuuent|wid hir.  And si&thorn;in sal &thorn;ai sai verse: "Suscepimus, deus|&amp;c.;&mdash;Lauerd, we haue recaiuid &thorn;i merci I-middis ti|tempil."  And ay ta yeme of &thorn;e pouir and of &thorn;e pilegrimis,|for &thorn;ai er kald godis men, And to &thorn;e rike als-sua ba&thorn;e for|aze &amp; for honur. &thorn;abbesse kychin and of hir gestis sal be|bi it ane, &thorn;at te gestis &thorn;at cume noy noht te cuuent.  In|&thorn;at kichin sal tua sistirs serue, &thorn;at tay may do &thorn;e office|&thorn;at apendis &thorn;ar-to.  Yef &thorn;ai haue mikil at do, man sal|finde &thorn;am helpe; And when &thorn;ai haue lesse at do, ga til|o&thorn;ir laburs, whare sua man cumandis &thorn;am.  &THORN;e howse to|&thorn;e gestis sal man biteche a sistir at yeme &thorn;at dowtis god;|sho sal puruay &thorn;at tare be beddis inne; sua sal godis|howse be ordaind.  Wid &thorn;e gestis salle <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="31b">nane speke bot |&thorn;ai &thorn;at hauis leue.  Yef ani sistir metis &thorn;am, mekelike sal
<PB N="36">|sho aske &thorn;air benicun and si&thorn;in passe forz, yef sho hauis|na leue for to speke wid &thorn;am.  Lauerd for his grace giue|vs sua for to herberz his gestis, &thorn;at we may herber wid|him in &thorn;e ioy of heuin.  AmeN.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="54">
<HEAD>LIV.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at nane be sua|hardy at recaiue lettirs ne erand &thorn;at cumis fra &thorn;air|frendis, ne fra nane o&thorn;ir man, ne noht recaiue giftis bot|&thorn;urz &thorn;e leue of &thorn;abbesse.  Yef hir be sente ani &thorn;ing fra hir|frende, sho sal noht recaiue it, ar sho haue leue &amp; musterd|it &thorn;abbesse.  Yef sho giuis hir leue at recaiue it, In &thorn;abbes|pouste salle it be at giue whare hir &thorn;inke.  Bot wrez|hir noht &thorn;at te &thorn;ing es sent to; And yef &thorn;abbesse giuis it|til a-no&thorn;ir, loke &thorn;at sho ne wrez hir noht &thorn;at te &thorn;ing es|sent to, wharefore &thorn;e deuil finde a-chesun in hir; yef sho|dos, &thorn;e reul of discipline sal sho fele.  Lauerd giue vs sua|at yeme &thorn;is sentence and al o&thorn;ir, &thorn;at te deuil finde nan|achesun in vs.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="55">
<HEAD>LV.</HEAD>
<P>Of &thorn;air cla&thorn;ing spekis sain Benet in &thorn;is sentence, and| sais &thorn;at man sal <NOTE PLACE="foot">A verb seems to be omitted, possibly <I>giue</I> or <I>puruay</I>.</NOTE> clazing <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="32a">til ilkain eftir &thorn;at|tay ere, and eftir &thorn;e temprance es of &thorn;e cuntre.  In caald|cuntre es nede of warmer hend.  &THORN;is sal be forlokid &thorn;urz|&thorn;abbes.  Of &thorn;e culur of &thorn;e clad, na of &thorn;e mikilnes, sal|nane speke, bot take suilke als man may finde in &thorn;e cuntre|and of liht chepe bie.  &THORN;abbesse sal loke &thorn;at tay be riht|mesurd.  When &thorn;ai ta &thorn;e newe, &thorn;an salle &thorn;ai yelde &thorn;alde|for to giue to &thorn;e pure.  Tuinne paire cla&thorn;is sal ilkain haue|for to scifte and for to waisse; yef &thorn;ai haue mare, it sal|be scorn.  &THORN;air beddis sal &thorn;abbes ofte ripe, &thorn;at tay ne haue|na propirte.  Yef sho findis ani &thorn;ing wid-vten hir leue,|wid greue discipline sal it be amendid; And for &thorn;i &thorn;at it|es vice of propirte, sal it be scorn als &thorn;ifte.  &THORN;abbes sal|giue til ilk-ain<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ilk ani</I>, for <I>ilk-ain</I> or <I>ilk-ane</I>.</NOTE> als tay haue nede.  &THORN;abbes sal ta yeme of|&thorn;is sentence of &thorn;e dedis of &thorn;e apostils, &thorn;at sho depart til|ilkain als tay haue mister.  Sua sal &thorn;abbes ta yeme of &thorn;e
<PB N="37">|sekenes of &thorn;e nedful, And noht to &thorn;e wikke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wikke</I>, MS. <I>wilke</I>.</NOTE> wille of|&thorn;enuius.  In alle hir iugement sal sho umbe-&thorn;inke hir what|mede sho sal haue at god.  Lauerd giue vs sua at do, &thorn;at|we may haue owre mede of hym.  AmeN.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="56">
<HEAD>LVI.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="32b">Sain Benet sais &thorn;at te Abbes bord sal be ay wid |gestis and wid pilegrimis.  When sho hauis nane|gestis, sho sal take wilke of hir sistirs sam sho wille; bot|&thorn;at sho leue in &thorn;e fraitur an ordene nunne ou&thorn;ir tua &thorn;e|ordir for to gete.  Lauerd giue vs welle at gete oure ordir.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="57">
<HEAD>LVII.</HEAD>
<P>Yef &thorn;are be any &thorn;at can any labur, wid mekenes sal|&thorn;ai it do, als sain Benet cumandis, &thorn;at tabbes|cumaundis taim at do.  gyf &thorn;ai auantis taim of &thorn;air werke,|for &thorn;i &thorn;at sho &thorn;inke sho dose gude tille &thorn;e howse, sho sal|be don owte of hir mister, til sho haue amendid hir faute,|yef sho wille noht be buxum til &thorn;at &thorn;e abbes cumandis hir|at do.  Yef any makis any &thorn;inge &thorn;at sal be salde, Loke|what it is wrz, &thorn;at ye ne sette na felun price &thorn;ar-on.  And|&yogh;e vmbe-&thorn;inke yu of ananie &amp; of sapher his wife, &thorn;at salde|&thorn;aire lande in &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;a apostils; &thorn;ai helde a partie of|&thorn;e price, and a-no&thorn;ir partie broht by-fore &thorn;a apostils; and|sain petir was parcaiuid of &thorn;e tricherie, and askid &thorn;am why|&thorn;ai made propirte of &thorn;at &thorn;ai <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="33a">hauid done in comun; |And tai felle ba&thorn;e dede downe.  Mikil dowte birde &thorn;am|haue &thorn;at dose in &thorn;ing &thorn;at fallis til hali kirke, &thorn;at taire sauls|suffir na dede, als te cors dose here.  In &thorn;e price of &thorn;e|&thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e salle selle, loke &thorn;are be na cuuaitise inne; bot|bettir chepe sal ye selle &thorn;an &thorn;e men of &thorn;e werld dose, &thorn;at|god may be payde of yure sale.  He giue vs for his grace|&thorn;at we may sua wirke and sua selle, &thorn;at he be payde|&thorn;ar-of.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="58">
<HEAD>LVIII.</HEAD>
<P>When any wymmen of &thorn;e sekil, sais sain Benet,|cummis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cummis</I>; instead of the four|downstrokes required to make <I>-mi-</I> there are five; the same|inaccuracy occurs p. 40, l. 25.</NOTE> at aske &thorn;ordir, man salle noght ligh[t]-like<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>lighlike</I>.</NOTE>|gif it tam, &thorn;e entre, bot man sal do als ta-postil sais:
<PB N="38">|"proue &thorn;aire hertis, yef &thorn;ai be to god."  yef sho be stabil|in hir asking, And haitis for to suffir alle &thorn;e uiltez &thorn;at|man wille put hir to, Efter &thorn;e fifte day sal sho be recaiuid|in-til &thorn;e howse, And don in-til &thorn;e celle with &thorn;e nouicis.|&THORN;are sal sho studie and ete and slape.  suilk yeming sal|sho haue, &thorn;at te saule be turnid to god allemihtye; And|ta yeme to hir for to loke yef &thorn;e spirte be to god, and yef| sho dose hir entente to godis seruise, And buxum, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="33b">and|of suffrance.  Man salle muster hir harde &thorn;inges and|smerte, &thorn;e riht gate to god.  Yef sho euir haitis stabilnes,|eftir tua wukis sal hir be red &thorn;is reule of &thorn;ordir, And saye|to hir: "&thorn;is es &thorn;e rihte gate whare-inne &thorn;u salle life.  Yef|&thorn;u may halde it, cum inne; and yef &thorn;u ne may, ga forz al|deliuir."  Yef sho obidis yet, when sho is prouid o many|maners, &thorn;an sal man rede hir &thorn;e reule, &thorn;at sho may wite|witerli whar-to sho salle halde hir.  And at te tuelmonethes|ende, when sho hauis herde &thorn;e reule &thorn;ris, yef|sho haitis for to halde it welle, all &thorn;at man cumandis hir,|&thorn;anne sall sho be recaiuid i-mang &thorn;e cuuent.  bot witte sho|welle, fra &thorn;at day forward may sho noht gange owte, Ne|&thorn;e life of &thorn;e reule fle, ne caste it fra hir nek; For sho|hauid bi-fore laiser for to gange owte.  When sho sall|make hir professe, In &thorn;e Kirke bi-fore &thorn;ame alle sal sho|haite stabilnes and buxumnes, by-fore god and alle his|hali&yogh;es.  &THORN;at sho euir-mare brekis &thorn;at cuuenant, witte sho|welle &thorn;at god sal damne hir with-owtyn ende.  &THORN;is &thorn;ing| salle sho write with hir awne hande; And <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="34a">yef sho canne|noht write, pray ane of hir sistirs; Bot sho hir-selfe sal|make &thorn;e singne of &thorn;e croice, and lay it on &thorn;auter, And|si&thorn;in say &thorn;is verse: "Suscipe me &amp;c.;&mdash;Lauerd, &thorn;u recaiue|me, and I sal liue als te wordes es of &thorn;e; &thorn;at es myne entent,|&thorn;at I confundid be noht."  at &thorn;is verse sal alle &thorn;e|cuuent ansewere hir &thorn;ris; and si&thorn;in "Gloria patri" at te|laste.  When sho es blissed, Fra &thorn;at time forward sal sho be|calde in cuuent.  Yef sho hauis ani katel, parte it i-mang|&thorn;e pouir, Ou&thorn;ir make offrand til &thorn;e kirke, &thorn;at sho ne halde|na &thorn;ing by-hinde; For fra &thorn;at day forward sal sho haue|na pouste of hir Awne body.  Hir clathis &thorn;at sho broth|sal man restore &thorn;e kirke with-alle, &thorn;at sho fra &thorn;at day forward|haue na wille at gange owte of &thorn;e kirke &thorn;ur&yogh;e enticement
<PB N="39">|of &thorn;e deuil.  &THORN;e bref of hir professe sal sho noht|haue, bot in &thorn;e kirke sal be gete.  Lauerd for his grace|giue vs herte and wille in owre ordir to duelle.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="59">
<HEAD>LIX.</HEAD>
<P>When any riche man of &thorn;e sekil, sais sain Benet,|Offirs his do&yogh;tir til god and til haly kirke, And|&thorn;e childe be yunge, &thorn;at it ne kan noht aske &thorn;e peticiun, hir|frendis <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="34b">sal aske for hir.  And when &thorn;ai offir hir hande, |&thorn;ai salle winde &thorn;e tuaile &thorn;ar-a-bowte of &thorn;auter.  And tanne|sal &thorn;ai suere &thorn;at &thorn;ai ne sal neuir mare, ne na man &thorn;urz|&thorn;aim, o na maner giue &thorn;ing to &thorn;e childe, ne sende, whare-&thorn;urz|&thorn;at &thorn;e childe haue wille to propirte.  Bot yef &thorn;ai|wille ani almus do til &thorn;e kirke, do it al opinlike, &thorn;at &thorn;ai|wil giue.  Yef it be lande, and &thorn;ai wil halde it &thorn;aim-selfe,|&thorn;ai sal make chartir, and yelde ilke &yogh;ere &thorn;e ferme &thorn;at &thorn;ai|may liue with-alle.  And sua sal &yogh;e do wid alle &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at|fallis propirlie til &thorn;e child, &thorn;at na &thorn;ing bi-leue with hir|frende, whare-&thorn;urz &thorn;at sho haue wil til propirte; Sain|Benet hauis te sperance of &thorn;o&thorn;ir.  And on &thorn;is ilke maner|sal &thorn;e pure man childe be offird: simpelie make &thorn;aire|peticiun, and bi-fore whitnes offir &thorn;aire childir.  Lauerd|for his grace giue &thorn;at we may wel gyde &thorn;e offerande &thorn;at|owre frendis made of vs.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="60">
<HEAD>LX.</HEAD>
<P>Yef ani preste, sais sain Benet, prais &yogh;erne for to be|recaiuid in-til &thorn;ordir, &yogh;e ne sal noght hastelie|graunt it hym.  Bot yef he duellis in his asking &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&amp;</I> / <I>and</I>.</NOTE>|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="35a">prayis &yogh;erne, Man sal muster him alle &thorn;e disciplines of &thorn;e |reule, &thorn;at he salle yeme with-owtyn reles; &thorn;at it be done als|it is writin, And say til hym: "Amice, ad quid venisti&mdash;Frende,|wharto es &thorn;u cumen?"  Bot to&yogh;-whe&thorn;ir sal &thorn;e|howse be grauntid him, And recaiue benicun, and singe|his messe, yef &thorn;abbes cumandis him.  And yef it sua bitimis,|&thorn;at he ne wyl noght lere na sience, &thorn;e reule of discipline|sal he fele; for he sulde giue o&thorn;ir ensampil of|mekenes.  Yef &thorn;ar be ani labur at do in &thorn;e kirke, Of him|sal man ta yeme what he dose, when he is entird in; And|noght for &thorn;at he es preste and &thorn;ai haue done him reuerence,
<PB N="40">|be vnbuxum.  Yef any clerke desiris to ordir, o &thorn;at|ilke maner at be in fela&yogh;scap, &thorn;ai sal be done in mene|stede, O &thorn;is maner, yef &thorn;ai haite for to holde &thorn;e reule of|discipline and stabil dwelling.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="62">
<HEAD>LXII.</HEAD>
<P>Yef &thorn;abbes prais for preste ou&thorn;ir for dekin at be|ordainde til hym-selfe, He sal loke, &thorn;at &thorn;ai be|dingne &thorn;er-to at be preste.  He salle fle pride &amp; leue alle| ille vices, ar he be preste.  And &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="35b">he do na &thorn;ing bot|&thorn;at man cumandis him to do; And yef he do, he sal be|vndir &thorn;e reule of discipline.  Ne &thorn;at he for-gete noht &thorn;e|ordir &thorn;at he hauis tane, na &thorn;e reule of obedience ne of discipline,|And euir auance hym in godis seruise, And &thorn;inke|&thorn;at he ne come noht to &thorn;e kirke, bot til godis seruise.|And yef &thorn;e cuuent wille, &amp; &thorn;abes consentis &thorn;ar-to, &thorn;ai mai|auance hym for &thorn;e godenes of his life.  Loke &thorn;at he neuir&thorn;e-later|halde &thorn;e reule of stabilnes ba&thorn;e in and owte in|gudenes.  And if he o&thorn;irgate dose, and wil noht be buxum,|bott rebel, whilk<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>whilk</I> appears entirely out of place; cf. Notes.</NOTE> man salle repreue hym ofte.  Yef he wil|noght sua amende, Man salle muster hym til &thorn;e bisschope.|Yef he ne may do him amende, Man sal muster his fautes|alle opinlie, and do him owte of &thorn;e kirke, yef he be|prowde, &thorn;at he wil noght be buxum vnder &thorn;e reule of haly|kirke.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="61">
<HEAD>LXI.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence leris sain Benet vs, how we sal recaiue|&thorn;e vncunyng nunnis &thorn;at cummis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cummis</I>,|cf. p. 37, l. 32, footnote.</NOTE> owte of fer landis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ferlandis.</NOTE>|Yef sho wille als geste wne in &thorn;e kirke, and folow &thorn;e| custume als sho findes, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="36a">And noy nan &thorn;at langes to &thorn;e|kyrke with hir surfait, bot simpelike recaiue &thorn;at sho findis,|sho salle be recaiuid ay to whilis &thorn;at sho wille dwelle.  Yef|sho mustirs ani resun &amp; with luue, &thorn;abbes sal quaintelike|drahe hir to hir, and &thorn;anc<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;ane</I>.</NOTE> gode &thorn;at hir sent.  yef sho|wille &thorn;ar stabilnes make, loke &thorn;at wille be noht refusid.|And als-sua, yef man may persaue, to whilis &thorn;at sho es|geste, &thorn;at sho es surfaitus &amp; il maner, Man sal noght fela&yogh;scap|with hir, bott faire and swetelike latte hir ga, &thorn;at
<PB N="41">|to&thorn;ir haue na shame of hir.  Yef sho be of gude maner,|Man sal noht abide hir asking for to duelle, Bott man sal|prai hir at dwelle, &thorn;at &thorn;e to&thorn;ir mai be amendid &thorn;ur&yogh; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. The second <I>&thorn;e</I> twice.</NOTE>|sampil of hir; For in alle stedis may man serue god.  Yef|&thorn;abbes ses hir life be suilke, sho may do hir in he&yogh;er stede,|if sho wille, &thorn;an hir ordir askis.  Bot loke &thorn;e abbes &thorn;at|sho knaw hir wel &thorn;at sho sal halde in &thorn;e kirke, Ou&yogh;ir &yogh;urh|hir abbes ou&thorn;ir &thorn;ur&yogh; hir lettirs.  For hali write cumandis|&thorn;at &thorn;u sal do to na man<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>na</I> / <I>man</I>.</NOTE> bot als &thorn;u walde man did to &thorn;e.|Lauerd giue vs welle at gete &thorn;is cumandement<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="36b"> And alle |&thorn;o&thorn;ir.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="63">
<HEAD>LXIII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at ilkain be with|order als &thorn;ai cume in, And als tabbes stablis &thorn;aim|eftir &thorn;at &thorn;air lif es. &thorn;abbes sal noht greue &thorn;e cuuent, &thorn;o&yogh;|&thorn;ai be giuin hir at yeme, Ne deliuir pouste haue nane for|to giue of &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at es stablist in comun, Bott vmbe-&thorn;inke|hir &thorn;at sho sal yelde resun of alle hir iugement til god.|als tay ar ordainde, &thorn;at tay be stablist and gang in comun.|&THORN;ai ne salle noht tine &thorn;aire ordir for yu&yogh;hed; For samuel|and daniel, when &thorn;ai where barnis, &thorn;ai demid &thorn;e alde men.|alle sal be als &thorn;ai cume in-til &thorn;ordir, bot ta &thorn;at tabbes|he&yogh;is ou&thorn;ir la&yogh;is for a-chesun. sho &thorn;at cumis at te secunde|owre of &thorn;e day sal be done with hir &thorn;at cumis at &thorn;e first, O|what elde sam sho be.  Til &thorn;e barnis salle man halde|discipline.  &THORN;e yung salle onur &thorn;alde, and &thorn;e alde salle|lufe &thorn;e yunge.  Nane sal calle o&thorn;ir by &thorn;aire name, bot &thorn;e|priures sal calle &thorn;aim hir "sistirs." &THORN;abbesse, for sho es in|godis stede, sal be callid "dame," noht for &thorn;e he&yogh;nes &thorn;at|sho es abbes, bot for &thorn;e onur of god.  Loke &thorn;at sho <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="37a">do |sua, &thorn;at sho be dingne at recaiue &thorn;at onur.  When ane|metis a-no&thorn;ir, &thorn;e yunger sal noht sitte bi hir, bot sho haue|leue; for hali writ cumandis, &thorn;e yunger sal onur &thorn;elder.|&THORN;e barnis sal &thorn;inke on &thorn;aire ordir with discipline in kirke|and in fraitur; with-outyn and with-in, in alle stedis, sal &thorn;ai|haue geting &amp; chastiing.  Lauerd, for &thorn;i mercy giue vs|welle at halde &thorn;is sentence and euir &thorn;i wille do.  AmeN.
</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="64">
<PB N="42">
<HEAD>LXIV.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet leris vs in &thorn;is sentence, how we sal chese|vre abbesse.  Suilk resun, he sais, sal man loke at|&thorn;e lecciun, &thorn;at sho be ordene and &thorn;at al &thorn;e cuuent consentis|to with &thorn;e dute of god.  Sho &thorn;at &thorn;e haler partie of &thorn;e|cuuent chesis, &thorn;ur&yogh; gude life and wisdom sal sho be chosin.|Yef it sua be, &thorn;at alle &thorn;e cuuent chesis ane &thorn;at wil consent|til &thorn;aire vices, &thorn;e abbotis &thorn;at es &thorn;are, and &thorn;e folke of &thorn;e|cuntre, sal defende &thorn;at tat felun lecciun be noht forth broth.|Bott suilk sal &thorn;ai take &thorn;at can guuerne godis howse and| dingne es &thorn;ar-to.  And witte &thorn;ai wel, <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="37b">&thorn;ai sal haue gude|mede, if &thorn;ai do it for &thorn;e lufe of god, And sinne, yef &thorn;ai|leue.  &THORN;e abbes, when sho es ordainde, sho salle vmbe&thorn;inke|hir what charge sho hase recaiuid, And &thorn;at sho sal|yelde resun of alle.  witte sho wele &thorn;at mare bi-houis hir|studie for to auance hir cuuent, &thorn;an maistri for to haue.|sho a&yogh;ht at be wise in goddis law, &thorn;at sho dra&yogh;e til witnes|ba&thorn;e to &thorn;e new law and til &thorn;e alde testament.  Chaste|a&yogh;ht sho at be, and sobir, &amp; ful of pite, And euir he&yogh;e &thorn;e|misericorde of god ouir hir iugement, &thorn;at god do &thorn;at ilke|with hir.  Ille vices salle sho hate, and luue hir sistirs.  In|hir pouste loke &thorn;at &thorn;are be nane vtrage in, Ne &thorn;at sho ne|chaste nan sa fellike, &thorn;at &thorn;ai fle ne falle in wrang trou&yogh;.|&THORN;abbesse salle gete hir welle hir-fra, And euir haue hir|a&yogh;en misdede bi-fore hir siht.  Sho salle noht suffir &thorn;e|beli pipe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>beli pipe</I>, see Notes.</NOTE> be brokin; &thorn;at when sho seis ani of hir sistirs be|chargid with sinne, sho salle noht greue hir<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>greue hir</I> omitted and then|added above the line.</NOTE> sua mikil, &thorn;at|sho fle a-way, bot sho salle be besy more to be luuid &thorn;an| to be dredde.  sho sal <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="38a">nott be trubellus, nor angri, nor|ouir-obstinate, nor iolyose, nor ouir-suspiciose, for &thorn;an sal|sho neuir haue reste. sho sal be wice &amp; discrete in hir|commandmentis, &thorn;at &thorn;ai be ou&thorn;ir efter godde or efter &thorn;e|worlde. sho salle discerne and temper &thorn;e werkis whilk sho|invinis to be done, thynkyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>thyngyng</I>.</NOTE> a-pon &thorn;e discrecion of|sainte Iacob sayng in &thorn;is wise: "If I sulde make my|herdis to labur to mikil in walkyng, &thorn;ai sal alle die on one|day."  Therfore sho sal take &thorn;ir and odir ma examples|of discrecion, &thorn;e moder of vertues, and tempir and dispone
<PB N="43">|all thingis sa, &thorn;at hir demenance be swylke, &thorn;at sisters &thorn;at|er strang and of gude lyuyng may desire and lufe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lufe</I> omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE> it, &amp;|thay &thorn;at er febil may bere it; and namli &thorn;at sho kepe &thorn;is|present reule in all thingis, that when sho hase welle done|hir ministracion, sho may here &thorn;e worde of oure lorde|whilk &thorn;e gude seruande harde, &thorn;at gafe corne to his|seruandis in his tyme: "Amen dico vobis &amp;c.;&mdash;For soth|I say to &yogh;ow, godde sall sett hym ouir all his thingis."</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="65">
<HEAD>LXV.</HEAD>
<P>Sothly, ofte-timis it happins &thorn;at be <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="38b">&thorn;e ordinance |of &thorn;e prioresse greuus sklaunders rysis in monesterys,|whils &thorn;er be sum bownyd with &thorn;e wikkid sprete of|pride, thinkis thame-selfe als gude os thayre abbes, And|takis a-pon thame tyranry, and nurischis sclaunders, and|makis dissensiones in &thorn;e conuente, And nameli in tha|places where &thorn;e prioresse es ordande of &thorn;e same sistir, or of|&thorn;e abbesse, whilk hase made be-fore &thorn;e abbas.  Whilk|inconueniens it es ethy to conseyue; for &thorn;e prioresse is|geuin a mater to be prowd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>prowd</I>,|MS. <I>previd</I> ("tried").</NOTE> in &thorn;e begynnyng of hyr|ordinance, when sho is geuyn in mynde be hir awne|thoghtis &thorn;at sho is lowsid owte of &thorn;e power of hir abbesse,|be-cause &thorn;e same persones made hir prioresse whilk ordanid|&thorn;e abbas be-fore.  Thoro &thorn;at er raysid immonesis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>immonesis</I>, for <I>immondesis</I>.</NOTE> strifis,|bakbytyngis, haterede, dissensiones, And werangus ordinansis.|And when &thorn;e abbas and &thorn;e prioresse er of contrary|opynion, both thayre awne saules bus nedly be in perel in|&thorn;at dissensione, And thay alswa &thorn;at er vnder thame and|fag[n]is<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fagis</I>.</NOTE> both partis fallis in-to grete perel; whilk perel|fallis chefly opon thayme &thorn;at hauis made <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="39a">thame-selfe &thorn;e |autors of chesyng of &thorn;e prioresse.  For &thorn;i hauis sain Benet|forlokid &thorn;at tabbes sal chese whilke sam sho wille, for to|halde pese and charite.  Yef hir ordanment<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ordannent</I>.</NOTE> es in buxumnes,|alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at fallis to &thorn;e kirke sal be als tabes|cumandis, &thorn;at an ne be noht prude of &thorn;at es getyn til|comun.  Yef &thorn;e cuuent askis resonabillike and in mekenes,|And abbes sese it es nede, &thorn;ai sal make priuresse, &thorn;at sho
<PB N="44">|be chosin &thorn;ur&yogh; &thorn;e cunsaile of &thorn;a &thorn;at dutis god.  When &thorn;e|priuresse es ordainde, with mikil reuerence sal sho do &thorn;at|tabbesse cumandis hir, &thorn;at sho do na &thorn;ing a-gain hyr wille|na a-gain hir cumaundement. for &thorn;e mare &thorn;at sho est he&yogh;id|ouir to&thorn;ir, &thorn;e mare a&yogh;h sho at halde &thorn;e cumandement of &thorn;e|reule.  And if sho be of ille vicis and prowde, ou&thorn;ir man|may finde &thorn;at sho hauis &thorn;e haly reule in dispite, sho sal|be repreuid foure si&thorn;e with worde.  Yef sho wil noht|amende, &thorn;e reule of discipline sal sho fele.  Yef sho wil|noht amende sua, sho sal be don owte, and a-no&thorn;ir, &thorn;at es|dingne, be don in hir stede.  Yef sho wil noht be buxum|in cuuent, sho sal be done owte of &thorn;e kirke til sho wil| amende.  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="39b">&thorn;abbesse sal vmbe-&thorn;inke hir &thorn;at sho sal yelde|resun on domes-day of alle hir iugementis, And loke &thorn;at|&thorn;e lowe of envie and hateredin ne brenne noht hir herte.|Lauerd for his mercy defende vs fra envie &amp; hateredin.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="66">
<HEAD>LXVI.</HEAD>
<P>At &thorn;e &yogh;ate, sais sain Benet, sal man do a sister &thorn;at|can wisdome, And can recaiue &amp; &yogh;elde answer;|&thorn;at sho be stabil of worde and dede. by-side &thorn;e &yogh;ate sal|sho haue chaumber, &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;at cum to &thorn;e &yogh;ate, alle timis|finde hir redi and speke with &thorn;aim.  Als tite as ony|smitis on &thorn;e &yogh;ate, Ou&thorn;ir pouir crie, sho sal grace god and|with buxumnes hastelie ancewer &thorn;am and do &thorn;aire erand.|Yef sho hauis mister of help, man sal finde hir helpe at &thorn;e|&yogh;ate.  Yef &thorn;e howse may for&thorn;e it sua, &thorn;an sal it be stablist|o &thorn;is maner, &thorn;at &thorn;e water, &amp; &thorn;e milne, and bakehuse, and|breuhuse, and calgard, and al &thorn;at &yogh;e haue mister of, &thorn;at al|be with-in &thorn;e gard, &thorn;at &yogh;e ne haue na nede at sende owte;|for &thorn;at es noht gude to &thorn;e saule.  &THORN;is reule sal ofte be|redde imang &thorn;e cuuent, &thorn;at nane ascuse &thorn;am of &thorn;is &thorn;ing| &thorn;at &thorn;ai ne do it.  Lauerd for <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="40a">his pite giue vs sua at|vnderstande &thorn;is reule, and si&thorn;in for to wirke, &thorn;at we may|cum til &thorn;e life &thorn;at lastis ay. god gif it vs.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="67">
<HEAD>LXVII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at whilk sister|sua man sendis owte any erand, sal take &thorn;e benicun|are &thorn;ai ga, And cumande hir in &thorn;e vrisun of &thorn;abbes And
<PB N="45">|of alle hir sistirs; And at ilke vre of &thorn;e day &thorn;at [tai] prai<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at prai</I>.</NOTE>|for &thorn;a &thorn;at er vte.  &THORN;at day &thorn;at sho cumis hame, sal sho|recaiue &thorn;e benicun at ilke ure Of &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue misdon|with siht, ou&thorn;ir with iois,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>iois</I> ("joys"), corrupt for <I>erin</I> or the|like.</NOTE> ou&thorn;ir with speche, ou&thorn;ir ani ivil|dedis.  &THORN;ai sal noht telle til &thorn;e to&thorn;ir alle &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue sene|vte &amp; herd, for &thorn;at es ay mikil vice.  Yef any dose, &thorn;e|correccion of &thorn;e reule sal sho suffir.  And &thorn;at ilke sal sho|suffir &thorn;at gase owte of &thorn;e cloister, labur for to do, be it|neuir sua litel, with-owtin leue of &thorn;abbes.  Lauerd for <NOTE PLACE="foot">Here a phrase like <I>his grace</I> (p. 39, l. 21, etc.), <I>his|mercy</I> (p. 44, l. 16, etc.), <I>his pite</I> (p. 44, l. 31, etc.), is missing.</NOTE>|gete vs, &thorn;at we ne do ne saie &thorn;ing &thorn;at til destruciun fallis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="68">
<HEAD>LXVIII.</HEAD>
<P>Yef man cumandis, sais sain Benet, ani &thorn;ing at do,|and it be greue, and sho may noht do it, sho sal|recaiue &thorn;e cumandement<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="40b"> softelie and wid mekenes. yef |sho ses &thorn;at &thorn;e charge of &thorn;e cumandement ouir-gase hir|force, whit mekenes sal sho muster to &thorn;abbes hir sekenes,|and noht with pride, na with gain-sa&yogh;e.  When sho hauis|musterd hir firmite, yef &thorn;e cumandement of &thorn;abbes haldis|for&yogh;e, witte sho wele &thorn;at it es hir prowe til &thorn;e saule; sho|sal recaiue it in obedience in &thorn;e trou&yogh;e of goddis lay.|Lauerd, he giue vs mekenes, for his merci, als he cumandis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="69">
<HEAD>LXIX.</HEAD>
<P>Mikil a&yogh; ye at fle &thorn;is, sais sain Benet, &thorn;at nane defende|ne warne o&thorn;ir for nane achesun, ne for|sibredin, ne for na o&thorn;ir aquaintance; for mikil blame &thorn;an|may cum &thorn;erof.  Yef ani trespassis &thorn;is cumandement,|greuelike sal it be amendid.  Lauerd defende vs fra alle|achesun of sclandir.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="70">
<HEAD>LXX.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence cumandis sain Benet &thorn;at a-chesunnir|sal be defendid in haly kirke, als it es ordainde|and stablist, &thorn;at nane be sua hardy for to curse o&thorn;ir, ne|discipline, bot sho &thorn;at &thorn;abbes giuis &thorn;e pouste.  &THORN;a &thorn;at|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="41a">tresspassis, by-fore &thorn;am alle salle &thorn;ai be chastid, sua &thorn;at &thorn;e
<PB N="46">|o&thorn;ir haue dute &thorn;erof. til &thorn;e barnis sal man halde discipline|ententiuelike, Til &thorn;ai be o fiftene winter elde.  Alle sal|do &thorn;at to &thorn;am with mesur and with resun.  Yef ani sistir|with-outen &thorn;e cumandement of &thorn;abbes dose &thorn;e barnis ani|owterage, &thorn;e reule of disclipine sal &thorn;ai fele; for haly write|cummandis &thorn;at &thorn;u sal do to na no&thorn;ir bot als &thorn;u walde man|did to &thorn;e.  Lauerd for his pite giue vs well at halde his|cumandemens.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="71">
<HEAD>LXXI.</HEAD>
<P>Sain Benet cumandis in &thorn;is sentence &thorn;at al sal make|obediens, and noht alane to &thorn;abbes, bot ilkane to|o&thorn;ir.  &THORN;ur&yogh; &thorn;e life of obediens may ye cum to heuin. &thorn;abbes|and &thorn;e priuresse sal cumande til &thorn;a &thorn;at es vnder &thorn;aim;|&thorn;at na priue cumandement be hid in &thorn;aim. &thorn;e yunger sal|meke &thorn;aim til &thorn;elder with mikil charite.  Yef any es funden|with fawte, be it neuir so litel, with &thorn;abbes, ou&thorn;ir with|priuresse, ou&thorn;ir with ony o&thorn;ir, sho sal acline to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>, MS. <I>io</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;er&thorn;e.  Yef| sho haue whre&thorn;id ani of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="41b">hir sistirs, o what maner sam|it be, hastelike with-vten dwellyng sal sho falle to her fete|and aske hir for-gifnes, and crie hir merci, And ligge &thorn;are|til sho for-giue it hir and giue hir her benicun.  Sho &thorn;at|at &thorn;is amendment hauis an despite, and wille noht do it,|Of hir body sal man take amendement.  Yef sho be rebel|&thorn;ar-again, vte of &thorn;e kirke sal sho be putt.  Lauerd for his|merci giue vs sua obediens and mekenes at halde, and|rebel at fle, &thorn;at we may cum til &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at ay sal be.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="72">
<HEAD>LXXII.</HEAD>
<P>Of tua maner in a lif spekis sain Benet in &thorn;is|sentence, And sais &thorn;at the ille lif, &thorn;at es ful of|wille, it departis man fra god and ledis man til &thorn;e pinis of|helle, And a-no&thorn;ir lif, &thorn;at es gude, &thorn;at departis man fra|helle and ledis man to god almihti.  &THORN;is gude life sal ye|lere with lufe and gudenes, &amp; ilkain auance o&thorn;ir wid onur|and gude dede; &thorn;e sekenes of youre bodi, &thorn;an it cumis,|take it in gude entente and in pacience.  Obedience,| buxumnes, sal ilkain at o&thorn;ir <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="42a">lere hastiuelike, charite &amp;|gudenes ilkain lere o&thorn;ir, and chastite with luue.  Ye sal
<PB N="47">|dute god and yure abbesse with luue and charite.  And &thorn;at|sal lede yow til &thorn;e ioy with-outen ende.  god giue it vs.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="73">
<HEAD>LXXIII.</HEAD>
<P>In &thorn;is sentence mustirs sain Benet mikil mekenes &thorn;at|in hym was.  For pure mekenes mustirs he here|in &thorn;e last ende of his reule.  He sais &thorn;at he ne hauis noht|writyn alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at fallis to rihtuisnes.  Bott wha sam|haldis wel &thorn;ise cumaundementis, he&yogh; god, &thorn;at es fadir of|alle, sal &yogh;elde &thorn;aim &thorn;air mede.  We haue writin &thorn;is reule|for to mustir til &thorn;a &thorn;at ere suuerainis of hali kirke haue|clene luue til god and to &thorn;aire prome, And ilke sistir til|o&thorn;ir.  Bot wha sua wil cume til &thorn;e he&yogh;nes and til &thorn;e|sikirnes of religiun, Loke &thorn;at tay do eftir &thorn;e kening of &thorn;e|haly fadir &thorn;at wnis in manhed in &thorn;e he&yogh;nes &thorn;at lastis ay.|Of what boke sam ye here, of anikin kening of &thorn;alde lai|ou&thorn;ir of &thorn;e neu testament, Ou&thorn;ir what sum it es, &thorn;an es it|&thorn;e riht reule of &thorn;is life here.  Of na boke ne make &yogh;e force,|bot &yogh;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="42b">may ga &thorn;e right gate to god alle-mihti. &thorn;e life of |&thorn;e haly armitis and &thorn;aire cumandemens, And &thorn;e reule of|sain basili, alle suilke &thorn;ingis salle &yogh;e fili&yogh;.  Til hali men,|&thorn;at gude lif haldes &amp; luuis obedience and gude vertus, &thorn;at|may halde &thorn;is lif.  Bot we, sais sain benet, &thorn;at er febil|and for-getil and of febil lif, &thorn;is gude lif schamis vs, And|confundis.  Bot ye &thorn;at wille cume hastelike to &thorn;e he&yogh;e|ioy &thorn;at lastis ay, Haldes first &thorn;ur&yogh; &thorn;e helpe of iesu crist|&thorn;is litil beginning of &thorn;e reule &thorn;at I haue writin yu, And|salle ye cume til &thorn;e he&yogh;nes of mare vertu &thorn;ur&yogh; &thorn;e kenning|&thorn;at I haue musterd.  &THORN;a &thorn;at it vnderstandis and haldis,|Til &thorn;aim sal be oppind &thorn;e &yogh;atis of heuin.  Lauerd, bigining|and ending of alle gude dedis, giue vs<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vs</I> omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE> sua &thorn;is reule of|sain benet for to &yogh;eme, &thorn;at te rengne of heuin be oppind|til vs.  Godde gif it vs for his misericorde.  AmeN.|Qui viuis &amp; Regnas, Deus, Per Omnia Secula Seculorum.|AMEN.
</P></DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="version">
<PB N="48">
<HEAD>II. THE NORTHERN METRICAL VERSION|OF|The Rule of St. Benet.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(Cotton MS. Vespasian A. 25, British Museum.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="prolog">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="66a">Regula beati benedicti anglicis verbis translata.</HEAD>
<L>All &thorn;at wyll lely lyue in land</L>
<L>Als sant Benet has ordand,</L>
<L>Or wyll gyf &thorn;air deuocioun</L>
<L N="4">Vn-to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">4, 5, 26, and often: MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>e</SUP>, <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>is</SUP>, <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>i</SUP>.</NOTE> rowle of religioun,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is boke &thorn;ay may see sett</L>
<L>&THORN;e suthfast rewle of sant Benett</L>
<L>With sere pontes &thorn;at partens &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L N="8">Nyght &amp; day how &thorn;ay sall do.</L>
<L>Monkes &amp; als all leryd men</L>
<L>In latyn may it lyghtly ken,</L>
<L>And wytt &thorn;arby how &thorn;ay sall wyrk</L>
<L N="12">To sarue god and haly kyrk.</L>
<L>Bott tyll women to mak it couth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leris no latyn in &thorn;ar &yogh;outh,</L>
<L>In ingles is it ordand here,</L>
<L N="16">So &thorn;at &thorn;ay may it lyghtly lere.</L>
<L>For ilkon &thorn;at &thorn;ar-to er vun</L>
<L>Er haldyn it clerly for to kun</L>
<L>And to fulfyll it att &thorn;ar myght</L>
<L N="20">In word and dede both day &amp; nyght.</L>
<L>And ryght to gar &thorn;is reule up-ryse,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wytty man says on &thorn;is wyse:<Q>Asculta, o filia, disciplina[m]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>disciplina</I>.</NOTE> magistre tue&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Doghter, he says, tak tent &amp; lere</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;e techynges of &thorn;i maystres here,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="66b">And lat &thorn;ine eris bowand be</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bydynges of &thorn;i moder fre,</L>
<L>Whylk moder es cald haly kyrk,</L>
<L N="28">
<PB N="49">Whas wyll vs aw alway to wyrk.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ou sall fande to fulfyll</L>
<L>All &thorn;at &thorn;i modir tels &thorn;e vntyll,</L>
<L>And be bowsum to &thorn;i souerayn;</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;an sall &thorn;ou turn to god o-gayn,</L>
<L>Fro wham &thorn;at &thorn;ou depayrtyd es</L>
<L>Thurth &thorn;ine awin vn-bowsumnes.</L>
<L>And doghter, to my tale tak tent:</L>
<L N="36">For godes sak we sall assent</L>
<L>All fleschly wyll for to for-sak</L>
<L>And gostly armurs vntill vs tak,</L>
<L>Thurth obediens by day and nyght</L>
<L N="40">O-gans &thorn;e fend, our fa, to fyght.</L>
<L>Doghter, when &thorn;ou dose ony dede,</L>
<L>Pray specially god &thorn;e to spede,</L>
<L>And what werk so &thorn;ou sall to wend,</L>
<L N="44">Pray hym at bryng it tyll gude end,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at, sen he vowches saue</L>
<L>For hys doghters here vs to haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we neuer with oure wykkydnes</L>
<L N="48">Wreth hym, &thorn;at oure fader es,</L>
<L>So for to mak hym turn hys mode</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="67a">To hald fro vs hys gostly gode,</L>
<L>Or vs deseryd by &thorn;at skyll</L>
<L N="52">Fro &thorn;e blys &thorn;at he boght vs tyll,</L>
<L>And put vs vn-to pyen for &thorn;i,</L>
<L>Als wykkyd saruandes er worthy,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whylk, yf &thorn;ay dyde wele, myght wend</L>
<L N="56">To blys &thorn;at es with-outyn end.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor suld we vs a-vyse</L>
<L>Out of our syn sone for to ryse</L>
<L>And our hertes vnto heuyn at rayse,</L>
<L N="60">Als haly wrytt on &thorn;is wyse sayse:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e houre es now, if we tak kepe,</L>
<L>In whilk vs aw to ryse fro slepe."</L>
<L>&THORN;at is, we suld ryse out of syn,</L>
<L N="64">And wyrk so &thorn;at we heuyn may wyn,</L>
<L>And opyn our eghen to cryst on hyght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at namyd es ailastand lyght,</L>
<L>And opyn our eris, hys vose to here,</L>
<L N="68">
<PB N="50">Als bokes vs bydes on &thorn;is manere:<Q>"Hodie si vocem eius audieritis,|Nolite obdurare corda uestra&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;e here hys vose &thorn;is day,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="67b">Turn noght &yogh;oure hertes fro hym oway"&mdash;</L>
<L>Bott tyll hys voce &yogh;e tak gude hede,</L>
<L N="72">And fandes to fulfill yd<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fulfillyd</I>.</NOTE> in dede,</L>
<L>Sen god hase geuen &yogh;ow eris &amp; wytt;</L>
<L>For on &thorn;is wyse says haly wrytt:<Q>"Qui habet aures audiendi audiat."</Q></L>
<L>Crist vs kens on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="76">And says: "he &thorn;at hase eris suld here</L>
<L>&THORN;e law of god, and &thorn;an tak hede</L>
<L>To fulfyll yd<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fulfyllyd</I>.</NOTE> in word and dede."</L>
<L>For &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>us</SUP>.</NOTE> &thorn;e haly gost wyll ken</L>
<L N="80">Thruth haly kyrk all cristyn men:<Q>"Venite, filii, audite me&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Cums hider, suns, my wordes to here!</L>
<L>&THORN;e drede of god I sall &yogh;ow lere."</L>
<L>Haly kyrk, for our be-houe,</L>
<L N="84">Leris how we oure lord sall lufe</L>
<L>And lede oure lyf to hys lykyng</L>
<L>And drede [hym] ouer<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>drede ouer</I>.</NOTE> all oder thyng.</L>
<L>Ryn we suld, whyls we haue day,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at mirknes mare vs noght &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>&THORN;at mens, we suld lyf wele ilkane,</L>
<L>Or we with dynt of dede be tayne.</L>
<L>For in oure lyf here may we chese,</L>
<L N="92">Whyder we our-self wyll saue or lese.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="68a">And oure lord sekes in world all-wase</L>
<L>Who wyll be sauyd, and &thorn;usgayt sayse:<Q>"Quis est homo qui vult vitam&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Whilk man is he &thorn;at lyf wyl haue</L>
<L N="96">And se gude days, hys saule to saue?</L>
<L>Als-so say of hym am I fayne."</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou &thorn;an answer o-gayne</L>
<L>And says &thorn;us:<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>us</SUP>.</NOTE> "lord, &thorn;at man am I,"</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;an to &thorn;e says god almyghty:</L>
<L>
<PB N="51">"Man, if &thorn;ou wyll haue lastand lyf</L>
<L>And won in welth with-outyn stryf,</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wyse be-houes &thorn;e do,</L>
<L N="104">Als I sall tell &thorn;e vn-to:<Q>Proibe linguam tuam a malo&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>In &thorn;e begining, still &thorn;i tung,</L>
<L>And spek no uyl of ald na &yogh;ong,</L>
<L>And spayr &thorn;i lipes, &amp; hald &thorn;am still,</L>
<L N="108">So &thorn;at &thorn;ay opyn noght with ill!</L>
<L>Turn fro euil, &amp; seke to gude,</L>
<L>And seke to pese with mayn &amp; mode!"</L>
<L>And &thorn;us if we wyll wirk alway,</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;an wyll oure lord &thorn;us tyll vs say:</L>
<L>"Myne eghen on &yogh;ow sall luk ful clere,</L>
<L>And min eris sall &yogh;our prayers here,</L>
<L>And when &yogh;e to me call or cry,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;an sall I say &thorn;us: Here am I."</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="68b">What mirth to man myght mor acord</L>
<L>&THORN;an to here &thorn;is voce of oure lord?</L>
<L>Lo, how mekly &amp; how euen</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at he vs teches &thorn;e way to heuen!</L>
<L>Now, sen our mighty lord Iesus</L>
<L>Vnto hys kyngdom euer cals vs,</L>
<L>Ordand we vs in word &amp; dede</L>
<L N="124">At wend to hym with-outen drede</L>
<L>And with our werk mak vs worthy</L>
<L>In endles blis to beld hym by!</L>
<L>For of &thorn;at blis may we not spede,</L>
<L N="128">Bot if our werks be worthy mede,</L>
<L>And if he ask here in oure steuen:</L>
<L>"Whylk er &thorn;o men sall won in heuen?"</L>
<L>Als dauid in &thorn;e sawter boke</L>
<L N="132">Askes of oure lord, who likes to loke:<Q>"Domine, quis habitabit in tabernaculo tuo?"</Q></L>
<L>&THORN;us of our lord he askes &amp; says:</L>
<L>"Lord, who sall won in &thorn;i palays</L>
<L>Or ryst a-pon &thorn;i haly hyll?"</L>
<L N="136">And &thorn;us oure lord<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lord</I> omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE> answers &thorn;er-till:<Q>"Qui ingreditur sine macula."</Q></L>
<L>
<PB N="52"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="69a">He answers &thorn;us by prophet steuen,</L>
<L>Wysand vs &thorn;e way to heuen:</L>
<L>"He &thorn;at enters &thorn;is world within</L>
<L N="140">Clensid clen of all hys syn,</L>
<L>And always wyrkes &thorn;at ryghtwis es,</L>
<L>And says no thyng bot suthfastnes;</L>
<L>&THORN;at in hert hase no wykkyd thoght,</L>
<L N="144">Ne with hys tong no uil hase wroght;</L>
<L>&THORN;at to hys neghburs dose no noy</L>
<L>In stede ne stayll, &thorn;are staite to stroy;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ay &thorn;at standes and dwels til end</L>
<L N="148">Ogans &thorn;e fandyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fendyng</I>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e fend,</L>
<L>And wyll not doy efter hys rede,</L>
<L>Ne suffer hym in &thorn;am hafe no stede,</L>
<L>Bot settes &thorn;air hert &amp; &thorn;are powere</L>
<L N="152">All vnto crist, &thorn;at boght &thorn;am dere;</L>
<L>And for godes sake who will assent</L>
<L>To be bowsum and obidient,</L>
<L>And for his luf lyfes halily,</L>
<L N="156">And es not egh in hert for &thorn;i,</L>
<L>Bot knaws &thorn;at &thorn;aire gude dedes ilkon</L>
<L>Er of &thorn;e grace of god allon."</L>
<L>For thurth oure mightes, mor no les,</L>
<L N="160">May we begyn nonekyns gude.<NOTE PLACE="foot">159-160. See Notes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euil dedes er of oure awn entent,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="69b">And all gude dedes fro god er sent.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor hym suld we lofe all-ways</L>
<L N="164">With &thorn;e prophett, &thorn;at &thorn;usgayt says:<Q>"Non nobis, domine, sed nomini tuo da gloriam&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Lord, vntil vs be no loueyng,</L>
<L>Bot to &thorn;i naym ouer alkins thyng!"</L>
<L>For of oure-self we haf bot sin,</L>
<L N="168">And al gude bose in &thorn;e bygin,</L>
<L>Namly &thorn;at helpes to hele of saule.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-for on &thorn;is wyse says sant paule:<Q>"Gratia dei sum id quod sum&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>All &thorn;at in erth to me es ton,</L>
<L N="172">Itt is of &thorn;e grace of god allon.</L>
<L>Mine awn power es noght to prayse,</L>
<L>
<PB N="53">Bot wirchep be to god always."</L>
<L>And who so makes myrth, mor or min,</L>
<L N="176">In god be-houes his ioy begin;</L>
<L>For all oure comforth in hym dwels,</L>
<L>Als hym-self in &thorn;e godspel tels.</L>
<L>He says: "who to my wordes takes hede</L>
<L N="180">And fandes to fulfill &thorn;am in dede,</L>
<L>I sall mak hym wele like to be</L>
<L>A ful wyse man in all degre,</L>
<L>Whylk man, for his hous sal last,</L>
<L N="184">A-pon a ston hase byggid itt fast.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="70a">When it sall windes or flodes fell,</L>
<L>Euer may itt stand stifli &amp; wele,</L>
<L>And harm &thorn;air-to may &thorn;ai do none,</L>
<L N="188">Be-caus itt es biggid on a stone.</L>
<L>&THORN;is stone es crist, &thorn;at we on call.</L>
<L>He gifes vs force, &thorn;at we not fall,</L>
<L>And ilka day til vs he techis</L>
<L N="192">Thurth haly wordes, &thorn;at his men prechis,</L>
<L>And als thurgh law of hali kyrk,</L>
<L>How we in world sall wisely wirk.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e days of oure lifyng</L>
<L N="196">Er lent vs allane for &thorn;is thyng:</L>
<L>For we suld here oure mis amend</L>
<L>Thurgh hali kirk, os crist hase kend;</L>
<L>&THORN;air-for god lens vs oure lif-days,</L>
<L N="200">Als &thorn;e appostil proues &amp; says.</L>
<L>He says: "kan &yogh;e not vnder-stand</L>
<L>&THORN;e sufferance of god alweldand?</L>
<L>Vnto penance it suld &yogh;ow lede</L>
<L N="204">To mak a-mendes for &yogh;oure misdede."</L>
<L>Of swilk sufferance god schewes til vs</L>
<L>In his godspel, whaire he says &thorn;us:<Q>"Nolo mortem peccatoris sed vt magis&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>I wil not &thorn;e dede of sinful man,</L>
<L N="208">Bot &thorn;at he turn hym &amp; lif &thorn;an;</L>
<L>And if he of me ask mercy,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="70b">Ful gladly for-gyf hym wyl I."</L>
<L>&THORN;us if we &thorn;is question craue,</L>
<L N="212">Whilk &thorn;ai er &thorn;at heuyn sal haue</L>
<L>
<PB N="54">And won with god in blisses clere,</L>
<L>Answer haue we halili here.</L>
<L>And hardeli if we ful-fill</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;e offese &thorn;at fals &thorn;aim vntill</L>
<L>&THORN;at er ordand in blisses to be,</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires of &thorn;at ilk blis er we.</L>
<L>&THORN;an is it gude &thorn;at we here dresse</L>
<L N="220">Our hartes with all oure bisines</L>
<L>For to fulfill, in &thorn;at we may,</L>
<L>Godes bidinges both night &amp; day;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at we may nott be oure might,</L>
<L N="224">Pray hym to perfourn it right,</L>
<L>And for to grant vs might &amp; maine,</L>
<L>Thurgh his grace, &thorn;at most may gaine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may fle fro paines of hell</L>
<L N="228">And be worthi in blis to dwell.</L>
<L>Gude councel es to man &amp; wife,</L>
<L>Whils we lend in &thorn;is dedely life,</L>
<L>Vn-to swilk warkes for to take hede</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;at vs to lastand life may lede,</L>
<L>And gif vs fully, all folk in-fere,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="71a">To iesu skoles his laus to lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er &thorn;e laus of haly kirk,</L>
<L N="236">Of whilk vs aw not to be irk.</L>
<L>Al if vs thynk it hard to take,</L>
<L>We sall it suffer for godes sake;</L>
<L>And if sere enmis vs assayle,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;aire-for we sall not fayntly faile,</L>
<L>Bot thynk, if it be heuy &amp; hard,</L>
<L>What mede we sal haue afterward.</L>
<L>For who to wele-lifing sall win,</L>
<L N="244">With greuauns grete &thorn;aim<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;aim</I>; the first letter looks like a p.</NOTE> bus bigin;</L>
<L>Bot sethin a swetnes haue &thorn;ai sall</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last swetest of all.</L>
<L>For who so wil godes lesons lere</L>
<L N="248">May saue &thorn;air saules, &amp; hele &thorn;aim here,</L>
<L>And mak [&thorn;aim] thrugh<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS.|<I>mak thrugh</I>.</NOTE> meknes heueyn</L>
<L>Comuners in &thorn;e kyngdom of heuyn.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="1">
<PB N="55">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De iiiior condicionibus religionis.</HEAD>
<L>In &thorn;is ilk rewle of sant Benett</L>
<L N="252">Er sere folk in sere plasses sett</L>
<L>To serue god in sere degre,</L>
<L>Men or wemen whider &thorn;ai be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum er gude &amp; sum not so;</L>
<L N="256">Four maners mai men fynd of &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first es men here or women</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;air awn kynde wyll clerly ken,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="71b">And wilfully alway wil wirke</L>
<L N="260">Efter &thorn;e laus of haly kirke,</L>
<L>And euer-mor be bowsum &amp; baine</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e sawes of &thorn;eir sufferaine,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai may leire in &thorn;is boke</L>
<L N="264">Efter-ward, who likes to loke.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund maner es ful perfite</L>
<L>Als to be anger or eremete,</L>
<L>A-gains &thorn;e fend thurgh faith to feght</L>
<L N="268">With dedes of penance day &amp; night,</L>
<L>Not ainly bi lereing on buke,</L>
<L>Bot bi &thorn;e order &thorn;at &thorn;ai tuke.</L>
<L>And penance &thorn;at &thorn;ai put &thorn;aime to</L>
<L N="272">Sal mak &thorn;am myghty so to do.</L>
<L>Anely life all if &thorn;ai lede,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e deuel haue &thorn;ai no drede.</L>
<L>For god makes &thorn;am so mekli of mayne</L>
<L N="276">And stalworth to stand him a-gayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al his dartes may &thorn;am not dere,</L>
<L>Ne his faindinges may &thorn;am not fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid degre es not so gude:</L>
<L N="280">Men or wemen of wilful mode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at order of religion takes,</L>
<L>And al obseruaunce &thorn;at syne for-sakes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nowder will be obidient</L>
<L N="284"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="72a">Vntyl sufferayne ne til couent</L>
<L>For no thing &thorn;at men telles &thorn;am til,</L>
<L>Bot lifes efter &thorn;air wordly will</L>
<L>And serues more to worldly thyng</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;an vnto god, of heuen kyng.</L>
<L>
<PB N="56">Syngne of religion haue &thorn;ai non,</L>
<L>Ne takyn, bot tonsure allon.</L>
<L>Vnto no hird &thorn;ai wil tak kepe,</L>
<L N="292">Bot raykes forth als raueand schep.</L>
<L>And whar-to so &thorn;ai turn &thorn;air mode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at think &thorn;aym law and reson gude.</L>
<L>And whar-to &thorn;ai haue no likyng,</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;at think &thorn;am es vn-lefful thyng.</L>
<L>Be no rewle wil &thorn;ai be arrest,</L>
<L>Bot lifes als ane vnskilful best.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fortt degre &yogh;it es &thorn;air als</L>
<L N="300">Of sum &thorn;at er in order fals,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lightli leues al heuy thing</L>
<L>And folous euer &thorn;air flessh likyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai raik o-bout in sere contresse,</L>
<L N="304">For &thorn;ai &thorn;air likyng wil not lese.</L>
<L>In non abbay wil &thorn;ai dwell,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="72b">Bot wendes a-bout fro cel to cel</L>
<L>And tels lesynges here &amp; &thorn;air</L>
<L N="308">To gar men mak &thorn;am mery fare.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai lede &thorn;air lif in lechori</L>
<L>And in dronkynnes &amp; in clotony.</L>
<L>&THORN;air lifyng es ay war and were;</L>
<L N="312">&THORN;air-for of &thorn;am I spek no fare,</L>
<L>Bot to &thorn;e first I wend o-gayn</L>
<L>For to perfourn our processe playn,</L>
<L>To tel what pontes falles &thorn;am vnto,</L>
<L N="316">And als what dedes &thorn;am aw to do</L>
<L>&THORN;at for godes sake here sett</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e band of sant Benett.</L>
<L>Whare priores<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>priours</I>.</NOTE> es principall,</L>
<L N="320">And what pontes &thorn;er-to suld fall,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is begynnyng sal be kend.</L>
<L>God help &thorn;at it myght haue gude end!</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Vlterius de priorissa et eius condicionibus.</HEAD>
<L>A Priores aw for to be</L>
<L N="324">Principall in gude degre</L>
<L>
<PB N="57">Both in &thorn;e abba &amp; with-oute,</L>
<L>Whar so sche ganges or rides o-boute,</L>
<L>And to be honored euer hir aw;</L>
<L N="328">Bot in her-self sche sal be law,</L>
<L>Pryde in hert for to haue none,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="73a">Bot loue god euer of al his lone</L>
<L>And wirchip him werld al-wais,</L>
<L N="332">Als &thorn;e apostel plainly sais</L>
<L>Vn-to all folk, who so it be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at takes swilk staite of dignite:<Q>"Accepistis spiritum adepcionis."</Q></L>
<L>He sais: "&yogh;e take &thorn;e gaste of mede,</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;at lele folk vnto lif suld lede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whilk gaste we call &amp; cry</L>
<L>Vnto our lord god al-myghty,</L>
<L>And 'fader, abbot,' &thorn;us we say."</L>
<L N="340">Bi &yogh;er wordes vnderstand we may</L>
<L>&THORN;at soueranse aw no thing to do</L>
<L>Bot anely als crist kens &thorn;am to,</L>
<L>Ne no thyng suld &thorn;ai tech ne lere,</L>
<L N="344">Ne no thyng bid by &thorn;aire power,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at myght turn in feld &amp; towne</L>
<L>&THORN;air sogetes to saluacioune.</L>
<L>Techyng sal be to &thorn;am it beres</L>
<L N="348">Als gastly sede sawn in &thorn;air eres,</L>
<L>And to teching &thorn;ai sal be bayne</L>
<L>Als gude soietes to &thorn;air souerane.</L>
<L>For wele wit sche, &amp; so wit &thorn;ai,</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;at in dome, on &thorn;e dredful day,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="73b">Sal reknyng by, how sche &thorn;am leres,</L>
<L>And als who wele hir lessons heres,</L>
<L>And both &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai haue &thorn;air mede</L>
<L N="356">Efter &thorn;air lif &thorn;at &thorn;ai here lede.</L>
<L>A priores may knaw wele &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Sche beres &thorn;e charch of a hird-man.</L>
<L>And als a graue bihoues hir be,</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at cure hase tayn to kepe hir fe.</L>
<L>And hir awn sawle wele may sche saue,</L>
<L>Al if hir schepe vnryght wyl raue:</L>
<L>If scho gude techyng tell &thorn;am to</L>
<L N="364">
<PB N="58">And chastes als hir aw to do,</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e rewle &thorn;at crist hase kend,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai wil not &thorn;air mys amend,</L>
<L>Bott reklisly hir rede refuse,</L>
<L N="368">To crist &thorn;an may scho hir excuse</L>
<L>In dome, a-pon &thorn;e dredful day,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e prophet &thorn;usgate say:<Q>"Iusticiam tuam [non] abscondi<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>tuam abscondi</I>.</NOTE> in corde meo,|Voritatem tuam &amp; salutare tuum dixi."</Q></L>
<L>&THORN;us for hir werk scho may haue mede,</L>
<L N="372">And &thorn;ai dampned for &thorn;air mysdede.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="74a">Also we se &yogh;it to &thorn;e same:</L>
<L>Of priores who takes &thorn;e name,</L>
<L>In dede and saw her bus assent</L>
<L N="376">To fulfil it to duble intent;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, scho sal in wark fulfyll</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at scho sal tech o&thorn;er vntill,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at al hir doghters dere</L>
<L N="380">&THORN;at godes law lightly wil lere,</L>
<L>Bi wordes allayn may haue knawyng,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai sal do in al thyng,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er, &thorn;at of hertes er herd</L>
<L N="384">And oute of mesure more fraward,</L>
<L>Mai be informed bi hir dede</L>
<L>And lere how &thorn;ai &thorn;air lif suld lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;us aw hir-self in dede to do</L>
<L N="388">Al &thorn;at scho sal tech o&thorn;er vnto.</L>
<L>And when scho hir sugetes reproues,</L>
<L>On al maners luk hir be-houes,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at scho hafe not done &thorn;o dedes</L>
<L N="392">Whilk scho vntil oder for-bedes.</L>
<L>For &thorn;an hir lare is not to prays,</L>
<L>And crist &thorn;an vnto hir &thorn;us sais:<Q>"Quare tu enarras iusticiam tuam&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Whi teches &thorn;u in rightwisnes,</L>
<L N="396"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="74b">And &thorn;u &thorn;i-self mor synful es?</L>
<L>&THORN;u hates my techyng &amp; my lare,</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ou &thorn;i-self hase sined mare,</L>
<L>And my wordes putes &thorn;ou &thorn;e be-hinde,</L>
<L N="400">
<PB N="59">For of my teching ert &thorn;ou blind.</L>
<L>Ful wele &thorn;ou may perceaue &amp; se</L>
<L>A litil mote in &thorn;i sister ee,</L>
<L>Bott a grete balk in &thorn;in awn</L>
<L N="404">Vnto &thorn;i sight may not be knawn."</L>
<L>&THORN;us nedes &thorn;am-self for to be clere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er folk sall tech &amp; lere.</L>
<L>A Priores aw to be slike,</L>
<L N="408">&THORN;at scho luf ilkon in-like</L>
<L>And noght til on for fauor spare</L>
<L>And mak a-no&thorn;er to trauel mare,</L>
<L>Bot serue ilkon in &thorn;air degre</L>
<L N="412">Samen, als sisters aw to be.</L>
<L>For haly writ sais wele &thorn;air-bi:</L>
<L>"In crist we er all o body."</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at serues vnto a lord,</L>
<L N="416">In anhede aw &thorn;am to a-corde.</L>
<L>And right als god takes no rewarde,</L>
<L>For riches &thorn;at no man be sparde,</L>
<L>Ne non put doun for pouerte,</L>
<L N="420"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="75a">So suld it emang sisters be.</L>
<L>For crist on cristyn folk es heued</L>
<L>And we his lyms &thorn;at here er leuyde;</L>
<L>And godes seruandes in haly kirk,</L>
<L N="424">&THORN;at er ordand his werk to wirk,</L>
<L>Aw to be lufid in ewyn degre</L>
<L>Of hir &thorn;at sal &thorn;air souerayn be.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De eadem.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This heading, like several of the following, is written|in the right margin.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>A Priores &thorn;at wil wirchep win</L>
<L N="428">Aw to chastes on maners th[r]in<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>thin</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;am &thorn;at scho sese wil be schrews,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e apostil playnly schews;<Q>"Argue, obsecra, &amp; increpa!"</Q></L>
<L>&THORN;at es to mene on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="432">&THORN;ai &thorn;at er herd &amp; lath to lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;am sal scho chasti with hardnes</L>
<L>Of werk &amp; word, als worthy es.</L>
<L>
<PB N="60">And &thorn;ay &thorn;at er meke &amp; obedient</L>
<L N="436">And to hir saws wil euer assent,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal be chastede, when &thorn;ai sin,</L>
<L>With fair wordes &thorn;am forto wyn.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &thorn;at wil hir lare despise</L>
<L N="440">Or als rebels o-gans hir rise,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="75b">With &thorn;am aw hir for to trete</L>
<L>With preson &amp; with penance grete;</L>
<L>And sone when &thorn;at scho mai persaiue</L>
<L N="444">&THORN;air syn, lat noght &thorn;e tym ouer wayue,</L>
<L>Bot chaistese &thorn;am &amp; tery noght</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e wark &thorn;at &thorn;a[i ha]ue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;aue</I>.</NOTE> wroght</L>
<L>For parel &thorn;at mai fall &thorn;arby,</L>
<L N="448">Als wos proued of &thorn;e prophet hely</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er mo &thorn;at men may tell,</L>
<L>How grete drede es yn sin to dwell.</L>
<L>Bot first hir-self, &amp; right non els,</L>
<L N="452">Sal councel &thorn;am, als crist vs tels,</L>
<L>Bi wordes warli anes or twis.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai wil not &thorn;air-for rise,</L>
<L>To chastese &thorn;am scho sal not spare</L>
<L N="456">With penance hard, als I said aire.</L>
<L>For hali writ sais on &thorn;is wise:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e fole with word may non chastese."</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai wil set bi no man saw,</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;arfor &thorn;am bus haue harder aw.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;is sam, als clerks may kun,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wiseman sais: "chastise &thorn;i sun</L>
<L>And bete him with a wand, I rede,</L>
<L N="464">&THORN;an liuers &thorn;ou his saule fro drede."</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="76a">De eadem.</HEAD>
<L>A Priores aw for to wite,</L>
<L>Als beres witnes in haly writ,</L>
<L>Who mekel takes in town or felde,</L>
<L N="468">Of mekil be-houes &thorn;am rekni[n]g<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>reknig</I>.  The scribe seems|first to have written <I>-in-</I>, then to have altered <I>-in-</I> into <I>-ni-</I>,|forgetting, however, that there should be an n also after i|(or a contraction mark above it).</NOTE> &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>And so hir aw to vnderstand</L>
<L>
<PB N="61">What hard wark scho takes on hand</L>
<L>To gouerne &thorn;e saules of sere women</L>
<L N="472">And all &thorn;air erthly maners ken:</L>
<L>Sum gude, sum ill, sum eueyn bitweyn,</L>
<L>Als es in ilk a-semble sene.</L>
<L>And &thorn;air-for scho &thorn;at &yogh;eme &thorn;am sall</L>
<L N="476">Bus haue hir euynly vntil all</L>
<L>And fully knaw what falles &thorn;am to,</L>
<L>Als a gude hird aw for to do,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at al hir flok may proue</L>
<L N="480">And encrese vnto cristes bi-houe.</L>
<L>No gude hirdes sal set &thorn;air thoght</L>
<L>On erthli gudes, &thorn;at gase to noght,</L>
<L>Mor &thorn;an &thorn;e saules for to saue</L>
<L N="484">Of wham &thorn;ai sal here keping haue.</L>
<L>For mor we suld &yogh;ern hele of saule</L>
<L>&THORN;an of bodi, os sais sant paule.</L>
<L>And also crist in his godspell</L>
<L N="488">Of &thorn;is same makes minde o-mell:<Q>"Primum querite regnum dei&mdash;</Q></L>
<L> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="76b">First sal &yogh;e seke &thorn;e blis of heuyn</L>
<L>And &thorn;e rightwisnes of it ful euyn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an all &thorn;at nedes &yogh;ou vntill</L>
<L N="492">Sal &yogh;e haue at &yogh;our awne wyll."</L>
<L>And for&thorn;ermare &yogh;it may men rede:</L>
<L>Oure lord here if we luf &amp; drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal no thing here fro vs fayle</L>
<L N="496">&THORN;at to our saule hele may a-vayle.</L>
<L>And man or woman &thorn;at here wil haue</L>
<L>Cure of saules fro syn to saue,</L>
<L>Vnto reknyng sall &thorn;ai cum</L>
<L N="500">For &thorn;o saules on &thorn;e day of dom.</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e saules &thorn;ai hase in welde</L>
<L>And for his awn saule sall he &yogh;elde</L>
<L>Reknyng to crist, &thorn;e domes-man.</L>
<L N="504">It nedes &thorn;at &thorn;ai a-vise &thorn;am &thorn;an</L>
<L>For to do &thorn;at in &thorn;am es;</L>
<L>For if ony of &thorn;air schep peris,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e faute be not in &thorn;am fun,</L>
<L N="508">
<PB N="62">&THORN;air awn saule &thorn;en haue [&thorn;ai] vn-bun.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>haue vn bun</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And souerans &yogh;it sal haue &thorn;er mede</L>
<L>For saules &thorn;ai wyn with word or dede,</L>
<L>With gude ensampil &thorn;at &thorn;ai gife,</L>
<L N="512"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="77a">Or with gude lifyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai lif,</L>
<L>Or els with rightwise chastisyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;am falles gret mede for al swilk thyng.</L>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De adhibendis ad consilium sororibus.</HEAD>
<L>In all tymes, when oght es to do</L>
<L N="516">&THORN;at any grete charge fals vnto,</L>
<L>&THORN;e priores sal to-geder call</L>
<L>All &thorn;e conuent, grete &amp; small,</L>
<L>&THORN;at orderd er, both old &amp; &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="520">And ask &thorn;air counsel in &thorn;at thing.</L>
<L>When ilkon hase said &thorn;air a-vise,</L>
<L>&THORN;e priores &thorn;an, if scho be wise,</L>
<L>Sal se who a-cordes reson vnto,</L>
<L N="524">And efter &thorn;air rede sal scho do.</L>
<L>And god schews his myght, be &yogh;e bald,</L>
<L>Als wele in &yogh;ong folk als in ald;</L>
<L>And &thorn;airfor sal in swilk a thing</L>
<L N="528">Samyn com both olde &amp; &yogh;yng,</L>
<L>And mekely ilkon sai &thorn;air saw</L>
<L>And nother let for luf ne aw.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai al &thorn;er sawes hafe saide,</L>
<L N="532">Als scho assentes &thorn;ai sal be paide,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="77b">Als gude discipels sall al-ways</L>
<L>Be paide, what so &thorn;air maistres sais.</L>
<L>And scho with gude descrecioun</L>
<L N="536">Sal rewle hir wordes bi right reson,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai aw be day &amp; night</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;is rewle in all &thorn;er myght,</L>
<L>And in no ponte, for gude ne ill,</L>
<L N="540">To wirk efter &thorn;air awn will,</L>
<L>Bot euer to be bowsum &amp; bayn</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e sawes of &thorn;air sufferane.</L>
<L>And who so wil not for grete harte,</L>
<L N="544">
<PB N="63">With greuauns aw to be gart.</L>
<L>Bot luke &thorn;e priores for no thing</L>
<L>Pase &thorn;e right rewle of chastising,</L>
<L>Bot soberly to wirk al-way</L>
<L N="548">For drede of dome in &thorn;e last day.</L>
<L>When oder lese thynges er to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;e priores cal hir to</L>
<L>iii or iiii wysest women,</L>
<L N="552">And do als &thorn;air counsel wil ken,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at scho hase witnes al-ways,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e wise man witnes &amp; says:<Q>"Fac cum consilio, et post factum non penitebis!&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Do al &thorn;i dedes be gude counsell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Originally <I>counsaile</I>, or the like.  Cf. 1518.</NOTE></L>
<L N="556">&THORN;an sall &thorn;e noght rew &thorn;i trauayle."</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="78a">&THORN;air-for a souerayn sal not do,</L>
<L>Bot if scho ask counsel &thorn;air-to</L>
<L>Ow&thorn;er of sum or els of all,</L>
<L N="560">Efter &thorn;e thyng es grete or small.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="4">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De vijtem operibus misericordie.</HEAD>
<L>Here er &thorn;e warkes on raw to rede</L>
<L>&THORN;at sesis oure sins &amp; makes mede.</L>
<L>First sal we luf god loud &amp; still</L>
<L N="564">With al our hert &amp; al our will,</L>
<L>And syen our neghburs sal we luf</L>
<L>Als our-self for our saul be-houe;</L>
<L>No man ne women slay with wrang</L>
<L N="568">No&thorn;er with word ne wapyn strang.</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er mens we sal not steyl</L>
<L>Ne couet here no<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>, MS. <I>ne</I>.</NOTE> wordly wele.</L>
<L>Fals witnes we sal non bere,</L>
<L N="572">Bot honor al &thorn;at cristynd ere.</L>
<L>Godes naym we sal not tak in vayn,</L>
<L>Ne swer it bot for thyng sartayn.</L>
<L>And to non here sal we do</L>
<L N="576">Bot als we wold war don vs to.</L>
<L>Oure awn self we sal deny,</L>
<L>
<PB N="64">And folow oure lord god al-myghty,</L>
<L>Pine oure flesch with penance grete,</L>
<L N="580">And couet non delicius mete,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="78b">Fast &amp; do gude almus-dede,</L>
<L>And cleth &thorn;e naked &thorn;at hase nede.</L>
<L>Seke men suld we viset wele,</L>
<L N="584">And bring &thorn;e dede vn-to biriele,</L>
<L>Help al &thorn;o &thorn;at harmes haues,</L>
<L>And counsaile &thorn;am &thorn;at counsele craues,</L>
<L>And rek not of &thorn;is erthli gude,</L>
<L N="588">Bot vnto [crist] turn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>vnto turn</I>.</NOTE> al our mode.</L>
<L>In our hertes sal we hold non ire,</L>
<L>Ne vengeance sall we non desire.</L>
<L>Fals frenschep we sal non make,</L>
<L N="592">Trew charite so for to sake.</L>
<L>We sal not swer on euyn ne morn</L>
<L>For fardnes for to be for-sworn.</L>
<L>Euyl for euyl we sal not &yogh;elde,</L>
<L N="596">Bot mayntene right in town &amp; felde;</L>
<L>And if we wranges of o&thorn;er take,</L>
<L>We sal it suffer for godes sake.</L>
<L>Our enmys aw vs for to lufe,</L>
<L N="600">And noght ban &thorn;am &thorn;at vs reproue;</L>
<L>For mekely suld we, mor &amp; les,</L>
<L>Suffer reproue for rightwisnes.</L>
<L>With pride in hert we sal not rise,</L>
<L N="604">Ne be to slaw in god saruyse.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="79a">No vs aw lightly to lac,</L>
<L>Ne speke no harme be-hind &thorn;air bac.</L>
<L>In god we sal set al our thoght</L>
<L N="608">And think &thorn;at of our-self es noght</L>
<L>Bot sin &amp; sorow &amp; wrechidnes,</L>
<L>And ilka gude dede of god es.</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of dome vs aw to drede,</L>
<L N="612">An vn-to hell we suld take hede,</L>
<L>And were vs euer with al our mayn</L>
<L>Fro filth of sin, &thorn;at sarues payn,</L>
<L>And couaite heuyn euer inwardly,</L>
<L N="616">And thynk ilk day &thorn;at we sal dy,</L>
<L>
<PB N="65">And rewle our warkes by reson ryght,</L>
<L>And think &thorn;ai er euer in godes sight;</L>
<L>If euyl thoghtes our hertes tak,</L>
<L N="620">Kast &thorn;am oute for godes sake;</L>
<L>And kepe our moth fro grete carpyng</L>
<L>Of wikkidnes or of wordly thing.</L>
<L>Vn-to prayers we sal vs spede,</L>
<L N="624">And hali lessones here &amp; rede;</L>
<L>And for our mysdedes don be-forn</L>
<L>Suld we mourn both euyn &amp; morn.</L>
<L>In praers to god we [sal] vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>And praers to god we vs</I>.  See Notes.</NOTE> schriue</L>
<L N="628">And mak a-mendes so in our life.</L>
<L>We sal hate to wirk our awn will</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="79b">Or our flesch &yogh;ernyng to fulfill;</L>
<L>And on al wise we sal be bayn</L>
<L N="632">Vnto &thorn;e saws of our souerayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we aw our obidience to.</L>
<L>And also if we se hir do</L>
<L>O&thorn;erwise or wer, als god for-bede,</L>
<L N="636">&THORN;an scho teches vs to do in dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal we ordand our wirkyng</L>
<L>Als crist vs teches, in al thyng:<Q>"Secundum opera eorum nolite facere!"</Q></L>
<L>He sais &thorn;us: "workes efter &thorn;er saw,</L>
<L N="640">And to &thorn;air dedes luke &yogh;e not draw!"</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, if &thorn;ai wirk wrang,</L>
<L>And tech &yogh;ou grathly for to gang.</L>
<L>We sal not couet in our mode</L>
<L N="644">With folk for to be haldyn gude.</L>
<L>Godes bidynges we sal fulfill</L>
<L>Airly &amp; laite and loud &amp; still,</L>
<L>And luf clennes and chastite,</L>
<L N="648">And frendly vnto al folk be.</L>
<L>Fast suld we fle al vayn louyng,</L>
<L>And mak no strif with old no &yogh;ing.</L>
<L>To old folk suld we do honour,</L>
<L N="652">And febil we sal sucoure.</L>
<L>For our enmes sal we pray,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="80a">Til a recorde be redy ay,</L>
<L>
<PB N="66">And seker help ay sal we haue</L>
<L N="656">Of godes mercy our saules to saue.</L>
<L>&THORN;er er &thorn;e pontes of perfite lifyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at nedful er to old &amp; &yogh;ing;</L>
<L>For if we wil &thorn;am gladli do,</L>
<L N="660">Ful fair reward fals vs vnto,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es in endles blis to dwell,</L>
<L>Als crist sais &thorn;us in his godspel:<Q>"Oculus non vidit, nec aures audiverunt&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>None eghen mai se, ne eris here,</L>
<L N="664">Ne hertes thynk &thorn;e blisses clere</L>
<L>Whilk god ordand to &thorn;er bi-houe</L>
<L>&THORN;at yn &thorn;air liues hym lely luf."</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor es gude &thorn;at we tak hede</L>
<L N="668">Hym for to luf &amp; als to drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at vn-to slik blis may vs bryng.</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;at lord be euer loueyng!</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="5">
<HEAD>V.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De obediencia ad deum.</HEAD>
<L>Now wil I tel, who wil tak tent,</L>
<L N="672">How we sal be obedient</L>
<L>To honowr god with ilka lym</L>
<L>And luf no thynk better &thorn;an hym.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="80b">God suld we luf for thynges thre,</L>
<L N="676">Namely al &thorn;at hase dignite</L>
<L>And in haly kirk to sing &amp; rede:</L>
<L>For he til vs merkes slik mede,</L>
<L>And for drede of &thorn;e payns of hell,</L>
<L N="680">And for &yogh;ernyng in blis to dwell.</L>
<L>For merit of &thorn;er thynges thre</L>
<L>Suld we euermor bowsum be,</L>
<L>And hertli faunde for to fulfil</L>
<L N="684">All &thorn;at oure souerayn telles vs till.</L>
<L>&THORN;an wil god of our wark be paide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an vntil vs salbe saide,</L>
<L>Als crist sais in &thorn;e sauter buke</L>
<L N="688">Thurgh &thorn;e prophet, who likes to luke:</L>
<L>"Als sone als euer he heres my will,</L>
<L>Bowes he baynly me vntill."</L>
<L>
<PB N="67">&THORN;us may be saide be old &amp; &yogh;yng</L>
<L N="692">&THORN;at baynly bowes to godes bedyng.</L>
<L>And also &yogh;it our lord iesus</L>
<L>Vntil his techers tels &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"Who so heres &yogh;ou, he heres me."</L>
<L N="696">&THORN;an be &thorn;er sawes wele may we se:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai &thorn;at er to &thorn;er souerayn bayne,</L>
<L>To god he dose &thorn;e same o-gayne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore who so wil be bown</L>
<L N="700"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="81a">To lif bi rewle of religiown,</L>
<L>Fro tyme &thorn;ai wit &thorn;er souerayn will,</L>
<L>In wark &thorn;ai sal it fast fulfill;</L>
<L>&THORN;air souerayn wil &amp; &thorn;er wirkyng</L>
<L N="704">Suld go to-geder euyn als a thing.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at wil do &thorn;us in dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e way to heuyn it wil &thorn;am lede.</L>
<L>And harder it es &thorn;an o&thorn;er ways,</L>
<L N="708">Als god vntil vs suthli sais:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e way of lif, who likes to layte,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal find both hard &amp; straite."</L>
<L>For whi al &thorn;at wil com &thorn;er-till</L>
<L N="712">Mai not wirk with &thorn;er awin will;</L>
<L>Bot hard or softe whider it semys,</L>
<L>Ai bus &thorn;ai do os o&thorn;er demys.</L>
<L>&THORN;an of &thorn;er wark es crist wele paide,</L>
<L N="716">&THORN;at &thorn;us til his discipils saide:<Q>"Non veni facere voluntatem meam &amp;c.;&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>I com not to wirk myne entent,</L>
<L>Bot aynly his &thorn;at hase me sent."</L>
<L>Ensampil &thorn;us he techis vs til</L>
<L N="720">&THORN;at we sal wirk our souerains wil.</L>
<L>Obediens &thorn;us, if it be stabil,</L>
<L>To god &amp; man es acceptabil,</L>
<L>Not to tary ne gruch o-gayne,</L>
<L N="724">Ne to answer with worde in vayn,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="81b">Ne to be heuy in hert or thoght,</L>
<L>For swilk obedience profites noght.</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;e hert &amp; wark acorde,</L>
<L N="728">It es not likand til our lord;</L>
<L>For al if we fulfil &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L>
<PB N="68">We gete &thorn;er-for no grace to mede,</L>
<L>Bot titter payn, &thorn;at ordand es</L>
<L N="732">To &thorn;am &thorn;at vses vnbousumnes.</L>
<L>And if we answer oght o-gayn,</L>
<L>Ful mekil mor mun be his payn.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="6">
<HEAD>VI.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;erfor es alway gude to do</L>
<L N="736">Als &thorn;e prophet telles vs to;</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e sauter &thorn;us he sais:</L>
<L>"I said &thorn;at I sal &yogh;eme my wais</L>
<L>In ilka tyme, both old &amp; &yogh;ung,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ung</I> corrected from <I>&yogh;ing</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="740">&THORN;at I trispast not in my tung;</L>
<L>To &yogh;eme my moth also I seke,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wises I am maide meke,</L>
<L>And gude warkes hafe I non don els."</L>
<L N="744">Lo, how &thorn;e prophet playnly tels:</L>
<L>Wise men sum tyme letes to say</L>
<L>Wordes &thorn;at menes bot wele alway,</L>
<L>Becaus &thorn;ai wil no ianglers be.</L>
<L N="748"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="82a">&THORN;an of mare force may we se</L>
<L>&THORN;at euyl wordes suld non here speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk with wo er worthi wreke.</L>
<L>And mykel spekyng who so vse,</L>
<L N="752">If it oft gayn, sum tym it nuse.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e wisman witnes &amp; sais:</L>
<L>"If &thorn;u vse many wordes always,</L>
<L>Fro syn on no<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>, MS. <I>on</I>.</NOTE> wise may &thorn;ow fle."</L>
<L N="756">And in a-no&thorn;er stede sais he</L>
<L>&THORN;at in a manes tung es contende</L>
<L>Life &amp; dede to fa &amp; frende.</L>
<L>And namly &thorn;ai &thorn;at soietes er,</L>
<L N="760">Gret spekyng &thorn;ai suld for-bere.</L>
<L>For til a maistres fals ij thynges:</L>
<L>To spek &amp; tech hir vnderlynges.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e discipels suld be stil</L>
<L N="764">And here what es tald &thorn;am vntil.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai oght wil aske or haue,</L>
<L>With gret reuerence &thorn;ai sal it craue,</L>
<L>And al spekyng &thorn;ai sal for-bere,</L>
<L N="768">
<PB N="69">And hering, &thorn;at &thorn;e saule may dere,</L>
<L>And gif &thorn;am vnto god allayn,</L>
<L>Whas trauel &thorn;ai haf vnder-tayne.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="7">
<HEAD>VII.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><HEAD>De xij gradibus humilitatis.</HEAD>
<L>Of meknes may we merure take</L>
<L N="772"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="82b">Of crist, &thorn;at sais &thorn;us for our sake</L>
<L>In his gospel, als clerkes ken,</L>
<L>Confortand al cristin men:<Q>"Qui se humiliat exaltabitur&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Misplaced.</NOTE></Q></L>
<L>Who highes him-self, he bese made law."</L>
<L N="776">Proude men reproues he in &thorn;is saw.</L>
<L>And &thorn;am to confort &thorn;at er meke,</L>
<L>&THORN;us he says, who so wele seke:<Q>"Qui se exaltat humiliabitur&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Misplaced.</NOTE></Q></L>
<L>He &thorn;at laws hym-self here,</L>
<L N="780">He salbe high in heuyn clere."</L>
<L>&THORN;us schews he wele, &amp; suth it es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at oute of pride comes al eghnes.</L>
<L>And for [&thorn;e] prophet<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>for prophet</I>.</NOTE> wald it fle,</L>
<L N="784">In &thorn;e sauter &thorn;us sais he:<Q>"Domine, non est exaltatum cor meum&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Lord, my herte ne mi eghen sight</L>
<L>Haf I not rasit vp in hight,</L>
<L>Ne in gret thinges haf I not gayn</L>
<L N="788">To mak maruayls many ayn,</L>
<L>Bot my lif mekly haf I spende,</L>
<L>And highed my saule in-to &thorn;i hende.</L>
<L>&THORN;er-for, lord, fra scham me schylde,</L>
<L N="792">Als &thorn;e moder dose &thorn;e childe."</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83a">If we our dedes wil duly drese</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e meret of mekenes</L>
<L>And win vnto &thorn;e hight of heuyn,</L>
<L N="796">To whilk mekenes may lede vs heuyn,</L>
<L>Hus bus be-gin with hert &amp; wil</L>
<L>To rase &thorn;e stegh &thorn;at rechis &thorn;er-til,</L>
<L>Bi whilk Iacob in visioun</L>
<L N="800">Saw angels wend both vp &amp; doun.</L>
<L>
<PB N="70">And &thorn;is ilk stegh, als clerkes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>clerkes</I>, MS. <I>crakes</I>.  See Notes.</NOTE> tels,</L>
<L>To vnderstandyng es not els</L>
<L>Bot thurgh heghnes doun to descend</L>
<L N="804">And thurgh lawnes vpward to wend.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;e stegh, with-outin strife,</L>
<L>Es likand til our erthli life,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk stegh thurgh our mekenes euyn</L>
<L N="808">God rases vp right to &thorn;e heuyn.</L>
<L>Two sides &thorn;er-of may signifi</L>
<L>Both oure saules &amp; our bodi,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whilk sides, als men may se,</L>
<L N="812">Er xij steles ordand to be,</L>
<L>Whilk er xij degrese of mekenes,</L>
<L>And right way vnto heuyn &thorn;at es.</L>
<L>And who so likes &thorn;at way to lere,</L>
<L N="816">&THORN;e xij degres &thorn;us may &thorn;ai here.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="1">
<HEAD>Primus gradus humilitatis.</HEAD>
<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83b">
<L>The first degre of meknes ryght</L>
<L>Es euer to set be-for our sight</L>
<L>&THORN;e drede of god in ilk degre,</L>
<L N="820">So &thorn;at it neuer for-getin be,</L>
<L>And thinke how &thorn;ai &thorn;at him for-sakes</L>
<L>&THORN;air mede in hell with murnyng takes;</L>
<L>And who so hym wil luf &amp; drede,</L>
<L N="824">In heuyn sal &thorn;ai haf &thorn;air mede.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor our lord ay suld we luf,</L>
<L>And drede him for our saule bi-houe,</L>
<L>And kepe fro sin &amp; fro foly</L>
<L N="828">Al &thorn;e limes of our body,</L>
<L>And do oway al flesch likinges,</L>
<L>Thynkand &thorn;at god &thorn;at sese al thinges</L>
<L>&THORN;at we in world here euer wroght</L>
<L N="832">Ou&thorn;er in wark, or word, or thoght&mdash;</L>
<L>For, als &thorn;e prophet proues &amp; sais,</L>
<L>God enserches &amp; sese al-wais</L>
<L>&THORN;e hertes &amp; &thorn;e ententes of men,</L>
<L N="836">Als clerkes on &thorn;is maner may ken:<Q>"Scrutans corda &amp; renes deus."</Q></L>
<L>And also &yogh;it &thorn;e prophet sais:</L>
<L>
<PB N="71">"Lord, &thorn;ou wate my wil alwais,</L>
<L>And thoghtes &thorn;at in my hert er hide,</L>
<L N="840">Vnto &thorn;e er &thorn;ai knawne &amp; kide."</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor who wil life wele alway,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84a">In his hert sal he think &amp; say:</L>
<L>"Be-for godes sight I salbe clene,</L>
<L N="844">Yf I waste myne euil dedes be-dene."</L>
<L>It is for-bed &thorn;us for &thorn;is skill</L>
<L>Any to folow &thorn;er fleschly will;</L>
<L>Als haly write comaundes &amp; sais:</L>
<L N="848">"Turn &thorn;e fro flesch likynges<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fleschlikynges</I>.</NOTE> alwais."</L>
<L>And pray we god with wil &amp; thoght</L>
<L>&THORN;at his wil in vs euer be wroght!</L>
<L>Hali write schews certan skil,</L>
<L N="852">Whi we sal not wirk our awn wil.</L>
<L>For sum warkes &thorn;at vs think perfite,</L>
<L>In godes sight er dedely delite.</L>
<L>Sum &thorn;at &thorn;e bodi thynk gude &amp; fine</L>
<L N="856">Wil lede &thorn;e saule vntil hel pyne.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;i of slike rekles warkes</L>
<L>Sais haly writ, os kens &thorn;ir clerkes:<Q>"Corrupti sunt et abhominabiles&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>&THORN;ai er corrumpid &amp; maide ful vile</L>
<L N="860">&THORN;at uses with filth &thorn;air flesch to file."</L>
<L>And when so we &yogh;ern ony thing</L>
<L>&THORN;at may fall vnto flesch likyng,</L>
<L>Thinke we god waites vs weterly!</L>
<L N="864">Als &thorn;e prophet sais &thorn;us &thorn;erby:</L>
<L>"Al my desire both day &amp; nyght,</L>
<L>Lord, es set be-for &thorn;i sight;</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84b">And al mi<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mi</I>, MS. <I>in</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;arnyng may &thorn;ou se,</L>
<L N="868">Il or gude wheder it be."</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor euyl desire suld we fle,</L>
<L>For dede es euer in &thorn;e entre,</L>
<L>Redey to fel vs in &thorn;at fit;</L>
<L N="872">And &thorn;erfor &thorn;us sais hali writ:</L>
<L>"Wend &thorn;ou not, for hard ne nesch,</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e &yogh;arnynges of &thorn;i flesch&mdash;<Q>Secundum desideria cordis non ambules!"</Q></L>
<L>
<PB N="72">&THORN;en, sen we wote our lord iesus</L>
<L N="876">Es euer bihaldand vntil vs,</L>
<L>And sese who sekes to godes seruyse</L>
<L>And wil not als wriches vnwise,</L>
<L>And als we wote oure gude angel</L>
<L N="880">Al our warkes to god wil tel,</L>
<L>Al be it neuer so litil a schar&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;an es wisdom to be-war</L>
<L>No warkes to do our god to greue.</L>
<L N="884">For al if he here lene vs leue</L>
<L>For to a-mend vs, whils we may,</L>
<L>Neuer-&thorn;e-lese on &thorn;e last day</L>
<L>Sal he reherce &amp; sai vs til:</L>
<L N="888">"&THORN;us did &thorn;ou, &amp; I held me stil."</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="2">
<HEAD>Secundus gradus humilitatis.</HEAD>
<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="85a">
<L>Ane o&thorn;er degre our meknes proues:<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the right margin: <I>ij gradus</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at es who hir awn wil not lufes,</L>
<L>Ne hase no likyng to fulfil</L>
<L N="892">&THORN;at hir desire entisice hir til,</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;ir wordes makes hir myrour,</L>
<L>Whilk iesus saide, our sauiour:<Q>"Non veni facere voluntatem meam&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>I com not to do myn entent,</L>
<L N="896">Bot his allaine &thorn;at hase me sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es my fader in heuyn on hight;</L>
<L>His wil I do both day &amp; night."</L>
<L>And hali writ wil proue ful playn</L>
<L N="900">&THORN;at our awn wil es worthi payn,</L>
<L>And who so of &thorn;er wil here misses</L>
<L>Serues &thorn;e croun of endles blisses.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor for-sake we here our wil,</L>
<L N="904">&THORN;at we may cum &thorn;at blis vntil.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="3">
<HEAD>iij gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The third degre es &thorn;is to take:</L>
<L>Who &thorn;at gladli for goddis sake</L>
<L>Wilbe obedient with &thorn;er mayne</L>
<L N="908">Vnto [&thorn;e] wil<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Vnto wil</I>.</NOTE> of &thorn;eir souerayne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at with gude cher wil fulfil</L>
<L>What so &thorn;air souerayne tels &thorn;am vntil;</L>
<L>
<PB N="73">Al[s] be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Albe</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e apostil es pupplist,</L>
<L N="912">&THORN;at sais &thorn;us of our lord crist:</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="85b">"He wos meke to his fader rede</L>
<L>And obedient vnto &thorn;e dede."</L>
<L>[. . . . .]<NOTE PLACE="foot">A line is omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L N="916">To gif ensaumpil mor &amp; lese,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld so obedient be</L>
<L>To &thorn;eir souerayns in &thorn;er degre,</L>
<L>And tent no thyng to &thorn;er awn wil,</L>
<L N="920">Bot &thorn;er souerayns fast to fulfil</L>
<L>With obedience in word &amp; dede;</L>
<L>Than es &thorn;er wark worth mikyl mede.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="4">
<HEAD>iiij gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The<NOTE PLACE="foot">The h|in <I>The</I> was added subsequently.</NOTE> fourt degre of mekenes clere</L>
<L N="924">Es of al &thorn;ai &thorn;at suffers here</L>
<L>And dose what so &thorn;er souerayn sais</L>
<L>Al if &thorn;e wark be wrang alwais</L>
<L>Or greuus til &thorn;am for to do,</L>
<L N="928">&yogh;et sal &thorn;ai sone assent &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And do it wele with al our mayn</L>
<L>With-outyn ony grochin ogayne,</L>
<L>And irk not &thorn;an, or it be done;</L>
<L N="932">Als hali writ wil tech ful son:<Q>"Qui perseuerauerit vsque in finem&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>He &thorn;at lastes vntil &thorn;e end,</L>
<L>Salbe safe &amp; vnto blis wende."</L>
<L>And also haly writ sais &thorn;us</L>
<L N="936"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="86a">Ane o&thorn;er claus [to] comford<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>claus comford</I>.</NOTE> vs:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i hert," he sais, "sal comford take</L>
<L>To be souerand for godes sake."</L>
<L>In o&thorn;er places he proues alway</L>
<L N="940">How souerand men to god suld say:<Q>"Propter te mortificamur tota die&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Lord, we suffer<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>suffor</I>.</NOTE> here with sere payn</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e day for &thorn;i sake for to be slayn."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Partly on erasure.  See Notes.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at mens: "we suffer payn mekely</L>
<L N="944">Als lams &thorn;at er lede for to dy,</L>
<L>
<PB N="74">And we er not ouercumen &thorn;er-in,</L>
<L>For mede we hope &thorn;erby to wyn;</L>
<L>Bot al we suffer it for iesus</L>
<L N="948">And for his sake &thorn;at so lufyd vs,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with his awn wil &amp; his rede</L>
<L>For our sake wold suffer dede</L>
<L>So to saue vs thurth his grace."</L>
<L N="952">And also in ane o&thorn;er place</L>
<L>May meke men say on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Lord, &thorn;ou hase asayde vs here</L>
<L>With angers a-gayns our desire,</L>
<L N="956"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="86b">Als siluer es asaide with fire,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hase vs <NOTE PLACE="foot">A participle (<I>don, led, put, set</I>?) is omitted.</NOTE> vnto &thorn;e snare</L>
<L>And made vs to haue angers &thorn;air."</L>
<L>For to assay vs in swilk thing,</L>
<L N="960">If we be meke to his bidyng,</L>
<L>And also for to schew &thorn;at we</L>
<L>Suld to a souerayn bowsum be</L>
<L>And wirk efter &thorn;er wil alway,</L>
<L N="964">Vnto our lord &thorn;us may he say:</L>
<L>"Lord, o-bouen set hase &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Souerayns to wham vs bus bew."</L>
<L>&THORN;us for god sake we suld be bown</L>
<L N="968">To suffer sere persecucioun,</L>
<L>What so men wil vn-til vs do;</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e gospel techis vs to:</L>
<L>Who so betes vs on a scheke,</L>
<L N="972">To bede o&thorn;er we suld be meke,</L>
<L>And wrang of vs who wil oght haue,</L>
<L>To bede &thorn;am mor &thorn;an &thorn;ai wold craue;</L>
<L>&THORN;an es our mekenes mykil at prase;</L>
<L N="976">Als sant paule &thorn;e appostil sais:</L>
<L>It be-houes folk of religioun</L>
<L>Suffer tenes &amp; tribulacioun,</L>
<L>And honor &thorn;am &thorn;at dose &thorn;am scath,</L>
<L N="980">Whider &thorn;ai be wele paide or wrath.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="87a">And &thorn;er meret it may not eke,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ai in &thorn;er hertes be meke</L>
<L>To suffer wilfuly alwais</L>
<L N="984">
<PB N="75">What so men to &thorn;am dose or sais,</L>
<L>And be not greuyd with word ne dede;</L>
<L>Swilk mekenes makes vs mykil mede.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="5">
<HEAD>v gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The fift degre es to be swift</L>
<L N="988">Eftir our sin to seke to schrift,</L>
<L>And trewly tel with-outyn trayne</L>
<L>Al our lif &amp; nothing layne,</L>
<L>Als hali writ on &thorn;is wise sais:</L>
<L N="992">"Vnto god sal I schew my wais,</L>
<L>And al my sines with mayn &amp; mode</L>
<L>Sal I schew to god so gude;</L>
<L>For his mercy may mend &amp; pas</L>
<L N="996">All wikkidnes &thorn;at in world euer was."</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &thorn;at &thorn;us &thorn;er sines wil bete,</L>
<L>&THORN;us may &thorn;ai sai with &thorn;e pro[p]hete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>prohete</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Lord, all &thorn;e sines &thorn;at er myn awne,</L>
<L N="1000">Vnto &thorn;e haue I made &thorn;am knawn;</L>
<L>And all onright &thorn;at euer I dide,</L>
<L>Lord, vnto &thorn;e I haue not hide;</L>
<L>Bot I sal pronunce for sertane</L>
<L N="1004">All my mysdedes my-self ogayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore, der lord, do &thorn;ou to me</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="87b">Efter &thorn;i grace so grete plente,</L>
<L>And lord, not efter my misdede,</L>
<L N="1008">Bot efter &thorn;i mercy graunte me mede."</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="6">
<HEAD>vjtus gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The sext degre of mekenes &thorn;an:</L>
<L>Who salbe meke, man or woman,</L>
<L>Bus hald &thorn;am-self vile &amp; worthy</L>
<L N="1012">Al maners of charch to vnderly,</L>
<L>And think &thorn;ai er worthi to do</L>
<L>Mor &thorn;an oni wil put &thorn;am to,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ai er worthi to haue</L>
<L N="1016">Wor &thorn;an any on &thorn;am vouches safe,</L>
<L>So litil be &thorn;am-self to set,</L>
<L>Say &thorn;an &thorn;us with &thorn;e prophet:<Q>"Consumptus sum et humiliatus&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>I am wastid wor &thorn;an I wend,</L>
<L N="1020">
<PB N="76">For myne awn kind not I kend.</L>
<L>Now als a best meke sal I be</L>
<L>Aneli, lord, for luf of &thorn;e."</L>
<L>God len vs so to be bowsum,</L>
<L N="1024">&THORN;at we may til his kingdom cum.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="7">
<HEAD>vij gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The seuent degre &thorn;an of &thorn;e twelue</L>
<L>Es &thorn;at vs aw to law our-selue,</L>
<L>And in hert hald vs vnworthi</L>
<L N="1028"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="88a">To cum in any gude company,</L>
<L>And of our-self we sal say &thorn;en</L>
<L>Os &thorn;e prophet wil clerely ken:<Q>"Ego sum vermis &amp; non homo&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>I am a worm &amp; no woman."</L>
<L N="1032">And &thorn;usgaite folos &thorn;ar-on &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"Mine awne condicions wil I ken,</L>
<L>Reproue &amp; oute-kast of al women.</L>
<L>My hyghnes in herth &thorn;en wil I knaw,</L>
<L N="1036">Bot, lord, &thorn;i law hase mayd me law.</L>
<L>Wele es me yn &thorn;is lif here</L>
<L>To be so meke &thorn;i laws to lere."</L>
<L>God len vs so his laws to lufe,</L>
<L N="1040">&THORN;at we bide in blis obufe.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="8">
<HEAD>viij gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The aght degre of meke lifyng</L>
<L>Es &thorn;at non sal do no thing,</L>
<L>Ne no wark &thorn;at es for to wirk,</L>
<L N="1044">Bot efter &thorn;e rewle of &thorn;er kirk</L>
<L>Or be ensampil to vnderstand</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am we knaw er wele lifand.</L>
<L>For ensawmpil of o&thorn;er dede</L>
<L N="1048">Salbe merure vs for to lede</L>
<L>In our doing both nyght &amp; day,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we folow our rewle alway.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="9">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="88b">ix gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The neyntt degre to ald &amp; &yogh;ong</L>
<L N="1052">Es &thorn;at vs aw to &yogh;em our tong</L>
<L>And spek not bot we be requerde.</L>
<L>For hali writ &thorn;us hase vs lerde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at who so mykil speking vse,</L>
<L N="1056">
<PB N="77">Of sin &thorn;ai may not &thorn;am excuse;</L>
<L>And gret spekers er not worthy</L>
<L>For to cum in gude company.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor es gude to take reward</L>
<L N="1060">With onest folk &thorn;at spech be spaird,</L>
<L>And ordan vs to spek no thyng</L>
<L>Bot honestly to godes loueyng.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="10">
<HEAD>x gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The x degre es &thorn;us to lere:</L>
<L N="1064">Not to lagh with ouer-lyght cher</L>
<L>Ne with laghing our voce to raise.</L>
<L>For hali writ &thorn;us leres &amp; sais:</L>
<L>"A fole," he sais, "bi day &amp; nyght</L>
<L N="1068">In laghyng rais his vose on hight."</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor es gude to man &amp; childe</L>
<L>For to ler at be laghter-myld</L>
<L>And of al cowntnanse myld &amp; stil</L>
<L N="1072">With-outyn ony mater of il.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="11">
<HEAD>xj gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The xj wisses &thorn;us alway:</L>
<L>Al if vs aw litil to say</L>
<L>And in laghing not rudely rise,</L>
<L N="1076"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="89a">&yogh;it es gude &thorn;at we vs avise,</L>
<L>When so we speke bi morn or noun,</L>
<L>To say our wil in wordes foune,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at our wordes be wittely.</L>
<L N="1080">For &thorn;us &thorn;e wisman sais &thorn;erbi:<Q>"Sapiens in paucis verbis expedit&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>He &thorn;at is wise in word &amp; dede,</L>
<L>His wark with fone wordes wil he spede."</L>
<L>And naymly women nyght &amp; day</L>
<L N="1084">Aw to vse fune wordes alway.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part" N="12">
<HEAD>xij gradus.</HEAD>
<L>The twelft degre wele for to seke</L>
<L>Es, of &thorn;am &thorn;at salbe meke,</L>
<L>Not aynli to be meke in wil,</L>
<L N="1088">Bot in wark mekely to fulfil</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at es to &thorn;am cumand:<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>cunand</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To gang, or ride, or sit, or stand,</L>
<L>
<PB N="78">In kirk, in closter, in town &amp; feld,</L>
<L N="1092">In way, in &yogh;erd, in &yogh;outh &amp; eld.</L>
<L>With law lowting &thorn;ai salbe bayn</L>
<L>With-outyn ony gruching o-gayn.</L>
<L>Vnto erth down sal &thorn;ai luke</L>
<L N="1096">Sorowand for syn, os sais &thorn;e buke</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="89b">Of &thorn;e pupplicane, &thorn;at prayde</L>
<L>Vnto god &amp; &thorn;usgaite saide:<Q>"Miserere mihi peccatori&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Lord, al thinges wele knaw &thorn;ou can;</L>
<L N="1100">Haue mercy on me, sinful man!</L>
<L>I am vn-worthi, lord," said he,</L>
<L>"To lift myn eghen vp vnto &thorn;e</L>
<L>Or for to luke vp vnto heuyn."</L>
<L N="1104">And also sais &thorn;e &thorn;rophet hewyn:<Q>"Curuatus sum &amp; humiliatus sum nimis&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>I am bowed to &thorn;e erth," he sais,</L>
<L>"And so I am meke mayd alwais."</L>
<L>Now haue I tald &thorn;ir twelf degrese</L>
<L N="1108">&THORN;at er of meknes for to chese,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk may bring vs for to be</L>
<L>With god in perfite charite</L>
<L>And al our lif lely to lede</L>
<L N="1112">With-outyn trauel or ony drede.</L>
<L>We sal do gladli of custum</L>
<L>&THORN;at air til vs wos ful irksum,</L>
<L>And not aynli payn to eschew,</L>
<L N="1116">Bot allayn for luf of iesu.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at lufe &amp; swete delite</L>
<L>&THORN;at in vs salbe so parfite,</L>
<L>Oute of al wais it sal vs wise</L>
<L N="1120">And bryng vs vnto endles blis.</L>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="90a">VIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De officiis in noctibus.</HEAD>
<L>In tyme of winter, in Descember,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e kalandes of Nouember</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e pase, es risyng right</L>
<L N="1124">At &thorn;e aght our of &thorn;e nyght,</L>
<L>And after mydnyght for to rest,</L>
<L>
<PB N="79">&THORN;at &thorn;ar mete may bi wele degest.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;ai rise to syng &amp; rede;</L>
<L N="1128">And after &thorn;an who so hase nede</L>
<L>May haue &thorn;er meditaciounes</L>
<L>In sawters, saulms, &amp; orisowns.</L>
<L>And fro al tyme of pase bi al left</L>
<L N="1132">Vn-to &thorn;o same kalandes cum eft,</L>
<L>&THORN;an es it ordand on &thorn;is wise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nunes sal vnto matens rise</L>
<L>When &thorn;e day be-gyns to daw,</L>
<L N="1136">&THORN;at &thorn;ai litters bi light may knaw.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="9-18">
<HEAD>IX-XVIII.</HEAD>
<L>Mor how &thorn;ai sal serues do,</L>
<L>Nedes not her to tel &thorn;am to;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai knaw &thorn;er salmes &amp; ilka verse.</L>
<L N="1140">&THORN;arfor &thorn;e rowle I wil reherce,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai sal do wirchep alway,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai to god sal sing or say.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="19">
<HEAD>XIX.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vbique credimus diuinam esse presenciam&mdash;</HEAD>
<L>We trow &amp; wele we vnderstand</L>
<L N="1144"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="90b">&THORN;at our lord god alweldand</L>
<L>In ilka place es redi bown</L>
<L>To here our prayer &amp; orisown;</L>
<L>And euyl &amp; gude, al heres he,</L>
<L N="1148">Rich &amp; pouer in ilk degre.</L>
<L>And most we trow he be present</L>
<L>In haly kirk bi &thorn;is entent</L>
<L>&THORN;at his seruaundes most comynli</L>
<L N="1152">Serues him &thorn;er, als es worthy.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sen we wote &thorn;at he es &thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;er</I>, originally <I>&thorn;air</I>, or the like.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oure mynd on hym suld be &thorn;e mayr</L>
<L>To serue hym dredfully always,</L>
<L N="1156">Als &thorn;e prophet vs teches &amp; sais:<Q>"Seruite domino cum timore!"</Q></L>
<L>He sais &thorn;us: "serues &yogh;or god in drede,</L>
<L>Hopand of hym to haue &yogh;or mede."</L>
<L>And wisely, sais he, we suld sing</L>
<L N="1160">
<PB N="80">Lessons vn-to goddes loueyng.</L>
<L>In ayn o&thorn;er plase sais he</L>
<L>&THORN;at angel[s]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>angel</I>.</NOTE> sal our synging se:<Q>"In conspectu anglorum psallam tibi."</Q></L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner til vs he teles</L>
<L N="1164">And sais: "lord, in sight of angels</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="91a">Sal we syng to &thorn;i wirchep."</L>
<L>&THORN;an aght vs for to tak gude kepe</L>
<L>&THORN;at our prayer &amp; orisoune</L>
<L N="1168">Be done with gude deuocioune,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at our hert &amp; moth acord;</L>
<L>&THORN;an es it likand til our lord</L>
<L>And vnto his angels also,</L>
<L N="1172">Sen we may se, al &thorn;at we do</L>
<L>And &thorn;at we say bi day or nyght,</L>
<L>Al es set befor &thorn;are sight.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="20">
<HEAD>XX.</HEAD>
<L>Bi gude ensaumpil may we se,</L>
<L N="1176">How bayn &amp; bowsum we wold be</L>
<L>Vn-to a lord, her whar we lif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ony gude myght til vs gif.</L>
<L>We wold hym loute, es not at layn,</L>
<L N="1180">And til his bidyng be ful bayn</L>
<L>With al wirchep &thorn;at we may weld.</L>
<L>&THORN;an of mor force in town &amp; feld</L>
<L>Wirchep suld we til him bede</L>
<L N="1184">&THORN;at in heuyn sal merk vs our mede.</L>
<L>With sorow of syn we suld him seke</L>
<L>And wirchep with wordes meke.</L>
<L>For haly writ lely vs leres</L>
<L N="1188">&THORN;at law hertes lightly he heres.</L>
<L>Our prayers suld be ordand euyn</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="91b">Schort &amp; clen to god of heuyn,</L>
<L>Bot if deuocioun cum emang</L>
<L N="1192">And likyng for to hald &thorn;am lang.</L>
<L>For haly writ &thorn;us leli leres:</L>
<L>Heuyn es thirld with schort prayers;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, if &thorn;at &thorn;ai be</L>
<L N="1196">
<PB N="81">Mellid with no kyns vanite,</L>
<L>Bot vnto godes wirchep alway.</L>
<L>God grant vs grace so for to pray.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="22">
<HEAD>XXII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quomodo sanctimonialles dormiant.</HEAD>
<L>All samyn o nyghtes lig &thorn;ai sall,</L>
<L N="1200">If a hows wil herber &thorn;am all,</L>
<L>And ilkon serly in a bede,</L>
<L>And ilkon in a kirtil clede</L>
<L>And girdid o-bown on al wise,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>alwise</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1204">&THORN;at &thorn;ai may be redy to rise.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ar be gret company,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al may not in a hows ly</L>
<L>In sere bedes, als I said hare,</L>
<L N="1208">&THORN;an ald women &amp; wise of lare</L>
<L>May haue &yogh;ong nouices, &thorn;at &thorn;ai lere,</L>
<L>To lig in a bed both infere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e hows whar [&thorn;ai] lig<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>whar lig</I>.</NOTE> o nyght,</L>
<L N="1212">Candel or laumpe sal euer be lyght.</L>
<L>And kniues to bed &thorn;ai sal non bere,</L>
<L>For dred &thorn;at &thorn;ai myght do &thorn;am dere.</L>
<L>When tyme es ordand, on al wise,</L>
<L N="1216"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="92a">With-outyn tareyng luk &thorn;ai rise</L>
<L>And hast &thorn;am hertly for to cum</L>
<L>Vnto godes serues al &amp; sum.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is es &thorn;e encheson why</L>
<L N="1220">&THORN;at &thorn;ai sal al in a hows ly:</L>
<L>Be-caus no idilnes sal vse,</L>
<L>Ne fro godes serues &thorn;am excuse.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="23">
<HEAD>XXIII.</HEAD>
<L>And if &thorn;ar ony vn-bowsum bene,</L>
<L N="1224">Or prowd in hert, os sum er sene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;ar rewle ne &thorn;er souerayn</L>
<L>Wil not bow, bot gruch o-gayn,</L>
<L>Twise preuely &thorn;ai salbe blamyd</L>
<L N="1228">And, bot &thorn;ai sese, opynly schamyd.</L>
<L>And if ane wil not mend her so,</L>
<L>
<PB N="82">Opyn reprofe falis hir vnto</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;e couent euer-ilkane.</L>
<L N="1232">And if sche &yogh;it be ouer-tayn,</L>
<L>And sche ken &thorn;e perils of cursing,</L>
<L>Sche salbe cursid for &thorn;at same &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>And if sche wil not mend hir mynd,</L>
<L N="1236">&THORN;an bodely sche salbe pynd.</L>
<L>And in hert penance sal sche lende,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="92b">Vntill sche wil hir mys amend.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="24">
<HEAD>XXIV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Modus castigacionis.</HEAD>
<L>Noman suld curs mor ne lese</L>
<L N="1240">Bot for thyng &thorn;at ful greuus es.</L>
<L>And so sal penance mor &amp; myn</L>
<L>Be gyfyn &amp; getyn efter &thorn;e sin,</L>
<L>Als light penance for litil thing,</L>
<L N="1244">And for gret greuus chastying.</L>
<L>Als if a non be nyght or day</L>
<L>Forget &thorn;at sche suld sing or say</L>
<L>Or ony werk &thorn;at sche suld wirk</L>
<L N="1248">In couent or yn hali kirk,</L>
<L>Sche salbe suspend fro &thorn;e mete</L>
<L>Al tyme &thorn;at hir felows sal ete.</L>
<L>Allayn at mete syne sal sche sit,</L>
<L N="1252">&THORN;at o&thorn;er may hir trispas wit.</L>
<L>Sum seruyse salbe fro her let</L>
<L>[. . . . .]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Here, for the second time, a whole line is omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mor &thorn;an for o&thorn;er on raw,</L>
<L N="1256">&THORN;at sche may so hir trispase knaw.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="25">
<HEAD>XXV.</HEAD>
<L>Mor greuus syns if on wil wirk,</L>
<L>Sche salbe suspend fro &thorn;e kirk,</L>
<L>Fro mete, &amp; fro al<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fro al</I>, MS. <I>for al</I>.  Cf. 2463.</NOTE> company</L>
<L N="1260">&THORN;at sche myght oght be cumfort bi.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="93a">Allone by hir-self sal sche do</L>
<L>What wark so sche es put vnto,</L>
<L>So for to punych hir body;</L>
<L N="1264">
<PB N="83">Als &thorn;e appostil speks &thorn;erbi:</L>
<L>Swilk men, he sais, sal trauel tast</L>
<L>With grete fullyng &thorn;er flesch to wast,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;er saules may safly cum</L>
<L N="1268">Bi-for god on &thorn;e day of dom.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="26">
<HEAD>XXVI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vt non communicent cum ex-communicatis.</HEAD>
<L>[If] None or nouese, mor or lese,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Notes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Comyn with &thorn;am &thorn;at cursed es,</L>
<L>Or cum vntyl hir whar sche dwels</L>
<L N="1272">To ete or speke or do oght els,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same payn sal &thorn;ai vnderly</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche suffers for hir foly,</L>
<L>Vntil &thorn;ai haue &thorn;at mys amend,</L>
<L N="1276">Bot if &thorn;ar souerayn haf &thorn;am send:</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;ai baldly speke &amp; do</L>
<L>Als far os &thorn;ai haf leue vnto.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="27">
<HEAD>XXVII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De pertinentibus ad custodem.</HEAD>
<L>Ane Abbot or a priorese,</L>
<L N="1280">&THORN;at so ouer oder kepers es,</L>
<L>Aw besily for to be-gyn</L>
<L>To hele &thorn;am &thorn;at er hurt with syn,</L>
<L>Thurgh haly lernyng &thorn;am to lech,</L>
<L N="1284">Als crist &thorn;us in &thorn;e gospel tech;</L>
<L>He sais: "to hel folk es no nede</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="93b">Ficiciens her for to bede,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o men &thorn;at er seke &amp; sore</L>
<L N="1288">Nedes for to haue medcyns mor."</L>
<L>A souerayn aw &thorn;arfor to send</L>
<L>To &thorn;e synful, &thorn;air mys to mend,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e eldest &amp; &thorn;e most wise,</L>
<L N="1292">Bi &thorn;air resons to ger &thorn;am rise,</L>
<L>And tech &thorn;am turmentes for to take</L>
<L>And suffer &thorn;am for godes sake,</L>
<L>And so assay bi &thorn;er soft saw</L>
<L N="1296">The synful to meknes at draw.</L>
<L>
<PB N="84">For ane sinful al suld &thorn;ai pray</L>
<L>&THORN;at god wise hir to better way.</L>
<L>Ilka hird aw to do &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="1300">So &thorn;at non of his schep perise.</L>
<L>And in case &thorn;at on perist were,</L>
<L>Ensaumpil of crist may we ler</L>
<L>To comford &thorn;am at our power.</L>
<L N="1304">For he tels vs on &thorn;is maner</L>
<L>Bi ensaumpil how a hird-man</L>
<L>A febil schepe warest &amp; wane:</L>
<L>He left al his flok os him list</L>
<L N="1308">And went to seke ane &thorn;at he myst;</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="94a">And sune when he had fon &thorn;at same,</L>
<L>A-pon his bak he broght it ham;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erof wos he so wele payd,</L>
<L N="1312">&THORN;at to his neghburs &thorn;us he said:<Q>"Congratulamini mihi quia inueni ouem quam &amp;c.;&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Bes glad &amp; makes mery with me!</L>
<L>My schep wos lorn, &amp; fun es he."</L>
<L>So aw a souerayn for to seke</L>
<L N="1316">&THORN;am &thorn;at dose wrang, with wordes meke,</L>
<L>And fathly faund with myght &amp; mayne</L>
<L>To get &thorn;am til &thorn;e flok ogayne.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="28">
<HEAD>XXVIII.</HEAD>
<L>And if it fall, als god for-bede,</L>
<L N="1320">&THORN;at ony haue don gret mysdede</L>
<L>And wil not mend her bi no way</L>
<L>For noght &thorn;at men may do or say,</L>
<L>For fair wordes ne for chaistying,</L>
<L N="1324">Ne for dred of &thorn;e gret cursyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;e souerayn nyght &amp; day</L>
<L>Ger al hir sisters for hir pray.</L>
<L>And if sche non wise wil amend,</L>
<L N="1328">&THORN;an, als &thorn;e appostil hase vs kend,</L>
<L>Sche salbe catchid fro cumpany,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er bi not hermyt hir by.</L>
<L>For thurgh a schep &thorn;at rote hase hent</L>
<L N="1332">May many schep with rote be schent.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="94b">So may a synful man do scath</L>
<L>
<PB N="85">Vnto him-self &amp; o&thorn;er bath.</L>
<L>Swilk foles es best forto for-sake,</L>
<L N="1336">Sen &thorn;at &thorn;ai wil no mercy take.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="29">
<HEAD>XXIX.</HEAD>
<L>And if ane so for wikkid dede</L>
<L>Leue hir abbay &amp; hir wede,</L>
<L>And lif in world efter &thorn;er wil,</L>
<L N="1340">And sine wold turn &thorn;e hows vntil,</L>
<L>&THORN;e penance to hir sche sal restore</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at dede &thorn;at sche went oute fore,</L>
<L>And profer hir-self to suffer payne</L>
<L N="1344">At &thorn;e ordenance of hir sofferayne,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at men may hir meknes knaw</L>
<L>Thurgh hir lifyng, if it be law.</L>
<L>And if sche eft a-way wil go,</L>
<L N="1348">Eft sal sche be resauyd so.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e third tyme if sche be gone,</L>
<L>A-gayn hir aw not to be tone,</L>
<L>Bot whar hir list &thorn;an lat hir pas,</L>
<L N="1352">Als sche &thorn;at neuer of order was.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="30">
<HEAD>XXX.</HEAD>
<L>Chastying aw mesured to be</L>
<L>To ald &amp; &yogh;ung in sere degre.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e trispas of childer &yogh;ing</L>
<L N="1356">Aw men to vse soft schastisyng,</L>
<L>Als fastyng &amp; betyng with wande</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="95a">And no&thorn;er strakes of staf ne hande.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai wil of wordes haf drede,</L>
<L N="1360">To bete &thorn;am &thorn;an it es no nede.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="65">
<HEAD>LXV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De prepocita, id est subpriorissa.</HEAD>
<L>In &thorn;is maner it ordand es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a president subpriores</L>
<L>Sal non be chosin for no chanch</L>
<L N="1364">Bot by &thorn;e priores puruyanch.</L>
<L>For [if] it<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>For it</I>.</NOTE> wor done o&thorn;er-wise,</L>
<L>
<PB N="86">Strif &amp; debate myght lightly rise.</L>
<L>For if sche wor chosin be &thorn;o same</L>
<L N="1368">&THORN;at chays &thorn;e priores by nayme,</L>
<L>&THORN;an thurgh eggyng of &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>A highnes in hir hert myght lend,</L>
<L>Thinkand &thorn;us in hir awn rede:</L>
<L N="1372">"If &thorn;at &thorn;e priores wor dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;o same by wham sche chosin es,</L>
<L>Wold ches me vnto priores."</L>
<L>And so perchanch in swilk a case,</L>
<L N="1376">If contek in &thorn;e couent rase,</L>
<L>&THORN;e subpriores so with pride</L>
<L>A-gayns hir souerayn suld sone chide,</L>
<L>And gete o&thorn;er of hir assent</L>
<L N="1380">To maynteyn hir in swilk entent</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="95b">And for to supplant hir souerayn;</L>
<L>And in swilk case myght sum be slayn</L>
<L>And perels fall, als folk may fele.</L>
<L N="1384">And &thorn;arfor es it ordand wele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at subpriores &amp; segerstone</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er offecers ilkon</L>
<L>Sal non be chosin bi no way</L>
<L N="1388">Bot als &thorn;e priores wil puruay.</L>
<L>And who so o&thorn;er-wise hase chose,</L>
<L>&THORN;e priores aw &thorn;am to depose</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er in &thorn;ar stede to take</L>
<L N="1392">In gude luf &amp; for godes sake.</L>
<L>Subpriores sal euer be bayne</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e saws of hir souerayne,</L>
<L>And no thing wirk a-gayns hir wil</L>
<L N="1396">Arely ne layte, ne loude ne stil.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e mor high state &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mor &thorn;am aw &thorn;er rewle to saue.</L>
<L>And if sche groch oght for to do</L>
<L N="1400">Of thyng &thorn;at touches &thorn;e rewle vnto,</L>
<L>Or if sche maynteyn mor or lese</L>
<L>For to myspay hir priores,</L>
<L>Or els rebel a-gayns hir rise,</L>
<L N="1404">Be word sche salbe warnyd thrise,</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;e iiij tyme, bot if sche mende,</L>
<L>
<PB N="87">Be chasted als &thorn;e rewle hase kende.</L>
<L>And if sche wil not mend hir so,</L>
<L N="1408"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="96a">Sche salbe pute hir office fro,</L>
<L>And ordand in hir stede to be</L>
<L>On &thorn;at es abil to &thorn;at degre.</L>
<L>And if sche wil not mend hir &yogh;it,</L>
<L N="1412">Oute of &thorn;air flok sche salbe flit.</L>
<L>Bot euer &thorn;e priores bus nede</L>
<L>Haue gude discreciun in hir dede.</L>
<L>Scho bus wirk be non enuy,</L>
<L N="1416">Bot for &thorn;e luf of god anely,</L>
<L>Be charite &amp; concience clene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE> rewle right to maynteyn.</L>
<L>And if sche so ordand hir dede,</L>
<L N="1420">Of god &thorn;an getes sche mykil mede.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="31">
<HEAD>XXXI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De eleccione celararie.</HEAD>
<L>A Celerer sal schosin be</L>
<L>Bi counsel of &thorn;e comunalte</L>
<L>And fully bi &thorn;e hale assent</L>
<L N="1424">Of &thorn;e priores &amp; &thorn;e couent,</L>
<L>Wise &amp; meke &amp; of myld thews,</L>
<L>Not prowd ne lither, like to schrews,</L>
<L>Not slaw ne grochand in hir dede,</L>
<L N="1428">Bot swilk als wil god loue &amp; drede.</L>
<L>Scho sal tak &yogh;eme to mor &amp; les</L>
<L>Bi puruyance of &thorn;e Priores.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="96b">For al sal cum into her hend</L>
<L N="1432">&THORN;at salbe in hir offece spend.</L>
<L>Hir offece sal sche gladly do,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eme wele &thorn;at es takyn her to.</L>
<L>And who so askes hir skilwis thyng,</L>
<L N="1436">Sche sal not greue &thorn;am with groching.</L>
<L>Bot if it a-cord not with wit,</L>
<L>Mekely sal scho warn &thorn;am it.</L>
<L>And if it aw forto be done,</L>
<L N="1440">Scho sal it gif gladly &amp; sone.</L>
<L>So vnto hir gret mede may rise,</L>
<L>
<PB N="88">Als &thorn;e appostel sais on &thorn;is wise:<Q>"Qui bene administrauerit,|gradum bonum sibi adquirit&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Who serues wele, with hertes fre,</L>
<L N="1444">Wins to &thorn;am-self a gud degre."</L>
<L>A celerer aw to be myld &amp; meke</L>
<L>For to serue &thorn;am &thorn;at er seke,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ong childer, &amp; gestes pore,</L>
<L N="1448">And o&thorn;er &thorn;at askes at &thorn;e dore.</L>
<L>Vnto al swilk tent sal sche take</L>
<L>And serue &thorn;am for godes sake,</L>
<L>Witand of all swilk doing</L>
<L N="1452"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="97a">On domesday sal [sche]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sche</I> or <I>scho</I> is omitted after (or before) <I>sal</I>.</NOTE> mak reknyng.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e vessel of &thorn;e abbay</L>
<L>Aw hir to &yogh;eme in right aray,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at non perise ne be lorn</L>
<L N="1456">Be hir defaute ne euyn ne morn.</L>
<L>Scho sal not saue hir-selu vntil,</L>
<L>Bot wirk al be [hir] souerayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>albe souerayn</I>.</NOTE> wil.</L>
<L>Fair of answer sal sche be</L>
<L N="1460">To euer ilkon in &thorn;er degre.</L>
<L>For meke answer es mykil at prays,</L>
<L>Als hali writ witnes &amp; says:<Q>"Sermo bonus super datum optimum&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Fair wordes in ilka plase</L>
<L N="1464">Er oboun o&thorn;er giftes of grace."</L>
<L>A celerer sal gladly fulfil</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at fals hir offece vntil,</L>
<L>And gladly gif when o&thorn;er craue,</L>
<L N="1468">And mekely ask what so<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so</I>, see Notes.</NOTE> wil haue.</L>
<L>And if scho so rewle al hir dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may scho serue ful mykil mede.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="32">
<HEAD>XXXII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De officio sacriste.</HEAD>
<L>The Priores, &amp; o&thorn;er nane,</L>
<L N="1472">Aw for to ches a segerstane</L>
<L>To ring &thorn;e bels in right aray</L>
<L>
<PB N="89">Til al &thorn;er seruys nyght &amp; day.</L>
<L>And wisely aw hir forto wirk</L>
<L N="1476"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="97b">To kepe enourmentes of &thorn;e kirk,</L>
<L>Als chalese, boke, &amp; vestmentes,</L>
<L>Relekes, waxe, &amp; annual rentes.</L>
<L>Er aw to ordan al bedene,</L>
<L N="1480">Als vessel, close, &amp; kep &thorn;am clene.</L>
<L>Indentures suld &thorn;ai be<NOTE PLACE="foot">We had expected a transitive verb.</NOTE> ilkon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e priores sal kepe &thorn;e tone,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at when on sal out flit,</L>
<L N="1484">By &thorn;er endenturs may &thorn;ai wit,</L>
<L>What thynges efter on er left</L>
<L>To hir &thorn;at sal resaf &thorn;am eft.</L>
<L>And who so wil reklesly wirk</L>
<L N="1488">Or files &thorn;e &thorn;inges of haly kirk,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salbe chasted greuusly</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;er warkes es worthi.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="35">
<HEAD>XXXV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De septimariis coquine.</HEAD>
<L>In &thorn;e kechin sal &thorn;ai serue oboute,</L>
<L N="1492">Ilkon &thorn;er wouke with-outyn doute,</L>
<L>And serues sal non refuse,</L>
<L>Bot if skilwis caus &thorn;am excuse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai til o&thorn;er thinges takes tent</L>
<L N="1496">Mor profetabil to &thorn;e couent.</L>
<L>And euer &thorn;am aw to tak rewarde</L>
<L>At euer &thorn;e eldest most be sparde.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="98a">And when on hase endid hir wouke,</L>
<L N="1500">Besily hir aw to luke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>albe</I>.</NOTE> clene &thorn;at to hir fell,</L>
<L>Both howses, clothes, &amp; wessell,</L>
<L>To liuer os clene os scho kan</L>
<L N="1504">Vnto hir &thorn;at sal serue &thorn;an,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at, if oght wantand be,</L>
<L>In whom defaut es, may men se.</L>
<L>And who so &thorn;us salbe seruand</L>
<L N="1508">May tak a sop wele be-for-hand,</L>
<L>
<PB N="90">So &thorn;at &thorn;er penance bi not gret</L>
<L>Forto bide til &thorn;e latter mete,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ai sal with meri cher</L>
<L N="1512">Serue ilkon on sides sere.</L>
<L>When on hase seruyd a wouk to end</L>
<L>And sal oute of &thorn;er seruys wend,</L>
<L>Kneland bi-for &thorn;e couent</L>
<L N="1516">&THORN;us sal scho say with gud entent<Q>"Benedictus es, domine, qui adiuuisti me&mdash;</Q>:</L>
<L>Blissid be &thorn;ou, lord, &thorn;at neuer falled,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hase me helpid &amp; counseld!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Originally <I>counsailed</I>, or the like.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thris on &thorn;is wise sal scho say,</L>
<L N="1520">And blisyng take, &amp; wend hir way.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="98b">And scho &thorn;at enters in seruese,</L>
<L>Kneland sal say on &thorn;is wise:<Q>"Deus, in adiutorium meum intende&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Lord, to my helping &thorn;ou take hede,</L>
<L N="1524">And hast &thorn;e hertly me to spede!"</L>
<L>And with hir hed scho sal bow down</L>
<L>And mekely take hir benysoun;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise when sche don has,</L>
<L N="1528">Vntil hir serues sal scho pas.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="45">
<HEAD>XLV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De delinquentibus in ecclesia.</HEAD>
<L>If &thorn;at on faile in ony thing,</L>
<L>In verses or saulms to rede or sing,</L>
<L>Or in lessons &thorn;am er kend,</L>
<L N="1532">Bot &thorn;ai mekely &thorn;at mys amend</L>
<L>&THORN;air in presens of company,</L>
<L>Grete payn sal &thorn;ai vnderly.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e nouices, whils &thorn;ai er &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="1536">Aw to be scorid for swilk a thing.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="46">
<HEAD>XLVI.</HEAD>
<L>And als who so wil fayntly faile</L>
<L>And not trewly do &thorn;er trauayle</L>
<L>In kechin, celer, or in cels,</L>
<L N="1540">In bakkows, brewhows, or ourels,</L>
<L>Or els &thorn;at loises mor or les</L>
<L>
<PB N="91">Bi resoun of &thorn;er reklesnes,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="99a">And comes not son to &thorn;er souerayne</L>
<L N="1544">For &thorn;at trispas to tak &thorn;er payne,</L>
<L>Bot layns it stil, os no man wist,</L>
<L>Til it with o&thorn;er be puplist,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal mor payn to &thorn;am be layde</L>
<L N="1548">&THORN;an if &thorn;am-self &thorn;e suth had saide.</L>
<L>For if none wit &thorn;erof bot &thorn;ay,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;er souerayn suld &thorn;ai sai</L>
<L>Or til &thorn;er confessure in hi,</L>
<L N="1552">&THORN;at may &thorn;am mend al preuely.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="47">
<HEAD>XLVII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De horis assignandis.</HEAD>
<L>Subpriores, als woman wise,</L>
<L>Sal kepe &thorn;e oures of god seruyse,</L>
<L>Or<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I>, MS. <I>Er</I>.</NOTE> els a-no&thorn;er bi her assent</L>
<L N="1556">Vnto &thorn;at office sal tak tent,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at seruyse bi day &amp; nyght</L>
<L>In ilk seson be rewlid right.</L>
<L>And scho sal assigne old &amp; &yogh;ing</L>
<L N="1560">Til all &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal rede or sing,</L>
<L>And se &thorn;at non sal syng ne rede</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at er abil vnto &thorn;at dede.</L>
<L>And dredefully ilkon sal do</L>
<L N="1564">Al &thorn;at &thorn;ai er assigned vnto.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="39">
<HEAD>XXXIX.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De mensura ciborum.</HEAD>
<L>Who to &thorn;e kechin sal tak tent</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="99b">Sal ordan wele for &thorn;e couent</L>
<L>Euer-ilk-a day ij maners of mete,</L>
<L N="1568">Bi-caus &thorn;at who so may not ete</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ton for nokins nede,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e to&thorn;er &thorn;ai may &thorn;am fede.</L>
<L>So til a couent suffes may</L>
<L N="1572">ij maner of potege ilka day.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ai hafe appils or o&thorn;er thing</L>
<L>Ordand of &thorn;eir awn growyng,</L>
<L>
<PB N="92">&THORN;en sal &thorn;ai make seruys of slike</L>
<L N="1576">Vnto euer-ilkon in-like.</L>
<L>To ilka lady suffise may</L>
<L>A pond of bred a-pon a day,</L>
<L>Wheder &thorn;ai wil ete ons or twise.</L>
<L N="1580">If it be ordand on &thorn;is wise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer-ilkon wil of hir laue</L>
<L>&THORN;e third part til hir sopper saue,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e celerer wil it seme</L>
<L N="1584">Swilk seruys for to saf &amp; &yogh;eme.</L>
<L>And who so wendes gret trauel til</L>
<L>Salbe seruyd at &thorn;er souerans wil,</L>
<L>With mor or les &thorn;at es to mene,</L>
<L N="1588">Bot euer &thorn;at non outrage be sene;</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="100a">For no thyng es [als] gret<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>es gret</I>; cf. p. 28, ll. 11-12.</NOTE> enmy</L>
<L>Vnto godes folk als glotony.</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;us sais iesus crist,</L>
<L N="1592">Als witnes wele &thorn;e euaungelest:<Q>"Videte ne grauentur corda uestra|crapula et ebrietate&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Greues not &yogh;our hartes for no nede</L>
<L>With glotony &amp; dronkenhede."</L>
<L>And les mesur in ilka thing</L>
<L N="1596">Salbe vsid to childer &yogh;yng.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="40">
<HEAD>XL.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De mensura potus.</HEAD>
<L>The mesure salbe of &thorn;er drink</L>
<L>Set efter &thorn;er souerayn think,</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;ai trauel arely &amp; late,</L>
<L N="1600">And after &thorn;e plais es cald or hate;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hete</I>;|cf. 2004.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;ai neuer assent vntil</L>
<L>&THORN;air flesch &yogh;ernyng fully to fil.</L>
<L>Softly sal &thorn;ai tast, &amp; fair,</L>
<L N="1604">Drynk &thorn;at may &thorn;er hedes inpair,</L>
<L>Als myghty wyne or nobil aile.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e wisman tels slik a taile:</L>
<L>"Wyne &thorn;at es myghty &amp; strang</L>
<L N="1608">Mase witty men forto wirk wrang."</L>
<L>
<PB N="93">&THORN;arfor es wit, to lest &amp; mast,</L>
<L>Wine or aile softly to tast.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai in slik places be,</L>
<L N="1612">&THORN;at &thorn;ai of no&thorn;er haf plente,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="100b">Swilk os &thorn;ai find &thorn;en sal &thorn;ai fande,</L>
<L>And loue god hertly of his sande.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="33">
<HEAD>XXXIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vt nichil proprium habeant.</HEAD>
<L>In relegion, als it es knawn,</L>
<L N="1616">Sal &thorn;ai haf no thing of &thorn;er awn,</L>
<L>Ne no &thorn;ing clame be propirte,</L>
<L>Bot al &thorn;ing sal in comun be.</L>
<L>No giftes sal [&thorn;ai] gif<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sal gif</I>.</NOTE> ne take</L>
<L N="1620">Bot anly for &thorn;eir souerayn sake,</L>
<L>Ne no &thorn;ing sal &thorn;ai clayme ne craue</L>
<L>Bot als &thorn;er souerayn wouches saue.</L>
<L>Tabels, boke, ne o&thorn;er gere</L>
<L N="1624">With-outyn hir wil sal &thorn;ai none were,</L>
<L>Bot whatkyn &thorn;ing so on haf sall,</L>
<L>&THORN;at salbe comun vnto &thorn;am all.</L>
<L>Scho &thorn;at wil not wirk on &thorn;is wise,</L>
<L N="1628">Scho salbe warned anes or twise;</L>
<L>And if scho so mend not hir hert,</L>
<L>With greter payn scho salbe gert.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="34">
<HEAD>XXXIV.</HEAD>
<L>For haly writ witnes &amp; sais</L>
<L N="1632">How &thorn;ai &thorn;at wons so in abbais</L>
<L>Aw to haue leuer of al thing</L>
<L>&THORN;at leful es to &thorn;eir lifing.</L>
<L>And ilkon aw in-like to haue,</L>
<L N="1636">And efter mor aw non to craue.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="101a">Bot euer-ilkon, als I air saide,</L>
<L>Of hir part sal hald hir paide.</L>
<L>And if ony be so vnbayne</L>
<L N="1640">In word or werk to groch ogayn,</L>
<L>And scho &thorn;er-of &thorn;an be ascried,</L>
<L>With penance sal scho be chastid.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="36">
<PB N="94">
<HEAD>XXXVI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De sororibus infirmis.</HEAD>
<L>When ony of godes saynd[s]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>saynd</I>.</NOTE> es seke,</L>
<L N="1644">All &thorn;e o&thorn;er sal with hertes meke</L>
<L>Confort hir &amp; with hir dwell,</L>
<L>Als crist vs kens in his gospell:</L>
<L>"Seke I wos," suthly sais he,</L>
<L N="1648">"And kindly com &yogh;e vnto me.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &yogh;e did o&thorn;er in my name,</L>
<L>Vnto my-self &yogh;e did &thorn;e same."</L>
<L>&THORN;ai &thorn;at er seke sal vnder-take</L>
<L N="1652">&THORN;at o&thorn;er &thorn;am serues for gode sake</L>
<L>And forto fulfil charite,</L>
<L>And nothing for &thorn;er awn degre.</L>
<L>In seknes suld &thorn;ai haf sufferans</L>
<L N="1656">And loue god euer of alkyn chanch.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e mor &thorn;ai er meke &amp; stil,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mor mede es ordand &thorn;am til.</L>
<L>And so a souerayn sal euer be meke</L>
<L N="1660"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="101b">And bowsum to &thorn;am &thorn;at er seke,</L>
<L>And with gude [wil] alway<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>gude alway</I>.</NOTE> to spend</L>
<L>On ony &thorn;ing &thorn;at myght &thorn;am mend,</L>
<L>And ordan seruandes &thorn;am vntil,</L>
<L N="1664">&THORN;at wil &thorn;am serue with gude wil,</L>
<L>And honest place for to be in,</L>
<L>Whor &thorn;ai may [s]it<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>it</I>, apparently a blunder for some verb, possibly <I>sit</I> or <I>li</I>.</NOTE> with-outyn dyn.</L>
<L>Bathes &amp; bawmes sal &thorn;ai haue</L>
<L N="1668">Als oft-sithes os &thorn;ai wil craue.</L>
<L>And gladli sal men<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>men</I> omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE> to &thorn;am gete</L>
<L>Flesch or fisch, what &thorn;ai wil ete.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai er fulli amend,</L>
<L N="1672">Lif furth als &thorn;e rewle hase kend.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="37">
<HEAD>XXXVII.</HEAD>
<L>A souerayn aw forto be-hald</L>
<L>&yogh;apli vnto &yogh;ong &amp; ald,</L>
<L>
<PB N="95">&THORN;at euer-ilkon in &thorn;er degre</L>
<L N="1676">Be ordand als &thorn;am aw to be,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e &yogh;ong may trauel tast,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e eldest be hordand mast.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="38">
<HEAD>XXXVIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De leccione ad prandium.</HEAD>
<L>The couent, when &thorn;ai set at mete,</L>
<L N="1680">For to rede sal &thorn;ai not for-gete.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sunnday sal on begin,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at wouke scho sal not blin.</L>
<L>Vnto hir felos sal scho say,</L>
<L N="1684"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="102a">Besekand &thorn;at &thorn;ai for hir pray.</L>
<L>And sone when &thorn;at scho enters in,</L>
<L>&THORN;is vers to say scho sal be-gin:<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>salbe gin</I>.</NOTE><Q>"Domine, labia mea aparies&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>Lord, opin my lippes als gastly lech,</L>
<L N="1688">And my moth sal &thorn;i louyng tech."</L>
<L>Hir souerain sal blis hir gud spede,</L>
<L>And so scho sal be-gin<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>salbe gin</I>.</NOTE> to rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an of al nose &thorn;ai salbe stil</L>
<L N="1692">And grathly tak entent hir til.</L>
<L>If any of &thorn;am nede oght to haue,</L>
<L>Softly with signes &thorn;ai sal it craue.</L>
<L>And scho &thorn;at redes sal sithen ete</L>
<L N="1696">With &thorn;am &thorn;at serues at &thorn;e mete.</L>
<L>And in order &thorn;ai sal not rede,</L>
<L>Bot who so best can do &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L>And most likandly tels &amp; leres</L>
<L N="1700">Vnto &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;e lesson heres.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="41">
<HEAD>XLI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>In quibus horis reficiantur.</HEAD>
<L>Of time of mete now es to lere,</L>
<L>In times &amp; sesons of &thorn;e &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Fro pas right vnto witsunnday</L>
<L N="1704">At &thorn;e sext our ete sal &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk es midday for to mene,</L>
<L>And sine sal &thorn;ai soupe bedene.</L>
<L>
<PB N="96"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="102b">In somer, fro witsunday be past,</L>
<L N="1708">Wedinsday &amp; friday sal &thorn;ai fast,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ai o&thorn;er swink or swete</L>
<L>In hay or corn with trauel grete.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai non slike trauel done,</L>
<L N="1712">On &thorn;os days sal &thorn;ai fast to none.</L>
<L>And on o&thorn;er days, als I air saide,</L>
<L>At mydday sal &thorn;er mete be graide.</L>
<L>Bot al &thorn;is salbe purued playn</L>
<L N="1716">At &thorn;e ordinance of &thorn;er souerayn.</L>
<L>What seson so scho putes &thorn;am to,</L>
<L>With-outin groching sal &thorn;ai do.</L>
<L>Fro time &thorn;at december be-gin</L>
<L N="1720">Vntil clene lentyn cum in,</L>
<L>At hi none sal &thorn;ai ete;</L>
<L>&THORN;er lesons sal &thorn;ai not for-gete.</L>
<L>In lentyn sal non to mete gang,</L>
<L N="1724">Or efter &thorn;e our of euyn-sang;</L>
<L>And al seruys &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai sai</L>
<L>Efter mete bi light of day,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at al be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>albe</I>.</NOTE> rewlid right</L>
<L N="1728">At wend to bede bi dais lyght.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="42">
<HEAD>XLII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vt non loquantur post complectorium.</HEAD>
<L>In times when &thorn;ai sal soup infere,</L>
<L>&THORN;en sal &thorn;ai set efter soppere</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="103a">Al in a stede, whor &thorn;ai wil sit,</L>
<L N="1732">And rede lessons of hali writ</L>
<L>Or els of liues of hali men,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gastly comfort may &thorn;am ken.</L>
<L>Tales of trofils &thorn;ai sal non tel,</L>
<L N="1736">Ne o&thorn;er maters &thorn;an of mel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may let haly orisoun</L>
<L>Or driue &thorn;am fro deuocioun.</L>
<L>On fastyngdais, in ilka place,</L>
<L N="1740">Efter euynsang a litil space</L>
<L>In a stede &thorn;ai sal set down.</L>
<L>And mak a schort colaciown.</L>
<L>
<PB N="97">And als son os &thorn;ai haf done,</L>
<L N="1744">Al samen sal &thorn;ai wend ful son</L>
<L>Vnto complin, mor &amp; myn.</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;e our of complin</L>
<L>In &thorn;er hertes al sal &thorn;ai hurd,</L>
<L N="1748">And non haue lef to spek a word,</L>
<L>Bot gestes or o&thorn;er &thorn;inges it gar&mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai spek it myght be-war&mdash;</L>
<L>Or if &thorn;er souerayn say &thorn;am to</L>
<L N="1752">Nedeful thinges &thorn;ai er to do.</L>
<L>Vnto hir sal &thorn;ai answer &thorn;an</L>
<L>Als curtesly als euer &thorn;ai kan.</L>
<L>And preuely so sal &thorn;ai say,</L>
<L N="1756">&THORN;at non &thorn;am here bot scho &amp; &thorn;ay.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ay</I> was subsequently altered into <I>day</I>; cf.  Notes.</NOTE></L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="103b">And o&thorn;er speking salbe none</L>
<L>Fro tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue complyn done.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="43">
<HEAD>XLIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vt cito veniant ad missam &amp; ad mensam.</HEAD>
<L>Als son als &thorn;ai here &thorn;e beles</L>
<L N="1760">To mes, matyns, or oght els,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;ai hast &thorn;am on al wise</L>
<L>Sone to com to godes seruyse.</L>
<L>Wheder so euer &thorn;ai sit or stand,</L>
<L N="1764">Al thyng sone sal &thorn;ai lef of hand</L>
<L>And wightly to &thorn;e kirk at win;</L>
<L>Bot neuer-&thorn;e-les &thorn;ai sal not ryn.</L>
<L>And who es not redy grayd,</L>
<L N="1768">When gloria efter &thorn;e first saulm es said,</L>
<L>In order &thorn;en &thorn;ai sal not be,</L>
<L>Bot stand in &thorn;e lawest degre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai be of &thorn;er souerayn sene</L>
<L N="1772">And of &thorn;air sisters al be-dene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>albe dene</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai sal with repentans</L>
<L>Mak amendes for swilk a chanch.</L>
<L>For in &thorn;am-self &thorn;ai sal haue schame</L>
<L N="1776">
<PB N="98">&THORN;at &thorn;ai er worthi to ber slik blaym.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e quer sal &thorn;ai stand algate,</L>
<L>And al if on cum neuer so late;<NOTE PLACE="foot">1775-1778 were written, by mistake,|in this order: 1776, 1778, 1775, 1777.  Then, by way of|correction, the letters b, d, a, c were added in the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="104a">For els sum wold take no kepe,</L>
<L N="1780">Bot o&thorn;er ianglyng or els slepe,</L>
<L>And als for &thorn;ai &thorn;at standes in quere</L>
<L>Sal haue part of al &thorn;at &thorn;ai here.</L>
<L>And if on dwel so lang oway</L>
<L N="1784">At ony of &thorn;e houres of &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same &thorn;an salbe &thorn;eir mede,</L>
<L>And no&thorn;er sal &thorn;ai sing ne rede.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e lawest stede sal &thorn;ai stand,</L>
<L N="1788">Bot if &thorn;eir souerayn &thorn;am command.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e mete so sal it fair</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at er not redi &thorn;air</L>
<L>To say &thorn;e grace &amp; take &thorn;er sete;</L>
<L N="1792">&THORN;ai sal bide to &thorn;e latter mete.</L>
<L>And who so wil not be chastid,</L>
<L>Til langer efter sal scho bide</L>
<L>And sine be hir allayn to sit,</L>
<L N="1796">And sum seruice sal hir want &yogh;it</L>
<L>Of mete or drynk &thorn;at myght hir glade,</L>
<L>Vntil scho haue amendes mayde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same payn es to &thorn;am puruayde</L>
<L N="1800">&THORN;at bides [not] til<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>bides til</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e grace be sayde</L>
<L>Efter mete, als it es vsed,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai haue caus to be excused.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="44">
<HEAD>XLIV.</HEAD>
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="104b">De modo satisfaccionis.</HEAD>
<L>Scho &thorn;at es for cursed kend</L>
<L N="1804">And wilfully wil hir amend,</L>
<L>Scho sal wait &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e day</L>
<L>When &thorn;e couent in &thorn;e schapiter pray,</L>
<L>And doun scho sal fall in &thorn;e flore</L>
<L N="1808">Opon hir face be-for &thorn;e dore,</L>
<L>And oblis hir vntil &thorn;er fete</L>
<L>Murnand sore hir mys to bete.</L>
<L>And ilk day<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ilkday</I>.</NOTE> sal &thorn;is be hir mese,</L>
<L N="1812">
<PB N="99">Vntil hir souerayn bid hir sese.</L>
<L>And if hir souerayn &thorn;edir hir call,</L>
<L>Vntil hir fete first sal scho fall,</L>
<L>And sine lig in hir aller way</L>
<L N="1816">Besekand &thorn;am for hir to pray.</L>
<L>If hir souerayn, &thorn;at hase power,</L>
<L>Gif hir leue to cum in quer,</L>
<L>On hir knes doun sal scho fall,</L>
<L N="1820">&THORN;at scho may be sene of &thorn;am all.</L>
<L>&THORN;is penance ilk day<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ilkday</I>.</NOTE> sal scho do,</L>
<L>Vntil hir souerayn se &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>And when scho ful mendyng may trow,</L>
<L N="1824">Scho sal say: "sese! it suffes now."</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="48">
<HEAD>XLVIII.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De operibus cotidianis.</HEAD>
<L>All &thorn;at wons in religioun</L>
<L>Aw to haue sum ocupacioun</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er in kirk of hali bedes</L>
<L N="1828"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="105a">Or stodying in oder stedes.</L>
<L>For ydilnes, os sais sant paul,</L>
<L>Es grete enmy vnto &thorn;e saul.</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor es ordand &thorn;at &thorn;ai</L>
<L N="1832">Sum gude warkes sal wirk alway,</L>
<L>And sum certane times of &thorn;e &yogh;er</L>
<L>To wirk with hand, os men may her.</L>
<L>Fro pase, thurgh al cristyndome,</L>
<L N="1836">Til &thorn;e kalandes of october cum,</L>
<L>Vnto prime sone sal &thorn;ai rise,</L>
<L>And sine ilkon wirk on &thorn;er wise</L>
<L>What so es most nedeful labore</L>
<L N="1840">Vntil &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e third oure.</L>
<L>And lessons sal &thorn;ai rede &thorn;an next</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e third our vnto &thorn;e sext.</L>
<L>And efterward thurgh wirchep <NOTE PLACE="foot">The rhyme-word is missing,|possibly <I>kete</I>, 'glad,' 'gladdened,' 'strengthened.'</NOTE></L>
<L N="1844">Fro oures &amp; mes wend vnto mete.</L>
<L>And efter mete, &thorn;en sal &thorn;ai slepe,</L>
<L>And silence al samen sal &thorn;ai kepe,</L>
<L>
<PB N="100">So &thorn;at none do o&thorn;er disese,</L>
<L N="1848">Bot ilkon paid o&thorn;er to plese.</L>
<L>Sone efterward, when &thorn;is es done</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai haf said &thorn;e our of none,</L>
<L>Vntil &thorn;eir werk &thorn;en sal &thorn;ai gang</L>
<L N="1852"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="105b">Vnto &thorn;e tyme of euynsang,</L>
<L>To scher or bind, if it be nede,</L>
<L>Or dike or els do o&thorn;er dede.</L>
<L>For vnto trauel wor we born,</L>
<L N="1856">And al our elders vs be-forn.</L>
<L>Bot trauel aw mesurd to be</L>
<L>Til ilkon efter &thorn;er degre,</L>
<L>To men or women, old or &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="1860">Ilkon to do diuers &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Fro october, os I are sayd,</L>
<L>Vnto lentyn es &thorn;us puruayd:</L>
<L>In orisons &amp; in &thorn;er oures</L>
<L N="1864">And lessons salbe &thorn;er laboures.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De obseruanciis in xlesima.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Originally belongs to the following chapter.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>In lentyn tyme &thorn;en sal &thorn;ai rise</L>
<L>Arly, &amp; say &thorn;er seruyse</L>
<L>And orisons til godes honoure,</L>
<L N="1868">Vntil it be past &thorn;e third oure.</L>
<L>&THORN;an to &thorn;e tent our sal &thorn;ai wirk,</L>
<L>And sine til non serue in &thorn;e kirk.</L>
<L>And in lentyn aw &thorn;am to luke</L>
<L N="1872">&THORN;at ilkon haue ordand a buke,</L>
<L>Whilk salbe red right to &thorn;e end,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e cours of &thorn;e rewl hase kend.</L>
<L>And who so groches oght here-o-gayn</L>
<L N="1876"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="106a">Salbe punest with greuus payne.</L>
<L>Who tentes to trofils &amp; wil not rede</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ouertayn with &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L>With payn &thorn;ai sal amendes make,</L>
<L N="1880">So &thorn;at o&thorn;er ensaumpil take.</L>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="49">
<HEAD>XLIX.</HEAD>
<L>In lentyn aw &thorn;am to be clere</L>
<L>Be-for all o&thorn;er times of &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>
<PB N="101">In haly bedes &thorn;at tyme to lif,</L>
<L N="1884">And vnto god haly &thorn;am gif,</L>
<L>Abstenand &thorn;am fro drynk &amp; mete,</L>
<L>And gif &thorn;am vnto penance grete,</L>
<L>And fand to fle al flesch likyng</L>
<L N="1888">And honor god ouer alkines &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>With clene desire so sal &thorn;ai bide</L>
<L>&THORN;e tyme of paise, &thorn;ai sal &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>And kepe &thorn;at, lord, so with clene life,</L>
<L N="1892">&THORN;at medcyn es to man &amp; wife.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="50">
<HEAD>L.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ai &thorn;at sal walk bi way, or wirk,</L>
<L>And may not cum to haly kirk,</L>
<L>In what stede so &thorn;ai be sett,</L>
<L N="1896">&THORN;eir seruyse sal &thorn;ai not for-gete,</L>
<L>Bot kepe all &thorn;e oures of &thorn;e day</L>
<L>With als grete honoure os &thorn;ai may,</L>
<L>And say &thorn;er seruyse in ilk seson</L>
<L N="1900">With wil &amp; gude deuocioun.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="51">
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="106b">LI.</HEAD>
<L>And if on sal on erand wend</L>
<L>Furthward vnto ony frend</L>
<L>A &thorn;inkes to com a-gayn &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="1904">Al if men vnto mete &thorn;am pray,</L>
<L>For to ete sal &thorn;ai not assent,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ai asked leue, or &thorn;ai went.</L>
<L>And who so trispas in &thorn;is &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="1908">&THORN;ai ryn in peryl of cursyng.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="52">
<HEAD>LII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De oracione in secretis.</HEAD>
<L>In chapiter or kirk who likes to lend,</L>
<L>When godes seruys is sayd til end,</L>
<L>To mak &thorn;eir meditaciouns</L>
<L N="1912">In haly prayers &amp; orisouns,</L>
<L>So preuely &thorn;en sal &thorn;ai pray,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non o&thorn;er here quat &thorn;ai say.</L>
<L>And preualy furth sal &thorn;ai wyn,</L>
<L N="1916">
<PB N="102">&THORN;at &thorn;ai let none &thorn;at lefes &thorn;erin.</L>
<L>&THORN;us euer ilkon sal hald silence,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai sal pray in godes precens,</L>
<L>Noght with crying ne voce ful grete,</L>
<L N="1920">Bot with murnyng on brest to bete.</L>
<L>Who so wil not do os I tel,</L>
<L>In prayng &thorn;ai sal not dwel,</L>
<L>Bot furth &thorn;ai sal be had in hy,</L>
<L N="1924"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="107a">&THORN;at o&thorn;er be not harmyd &thorn;erby.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="53">
<HEAD>LIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De hospitibus suscipiendis.</HEAD>
<L>A Priores aw to be prest</L>
<L>Forto resaue ilka gude gest</L>
<L>And at hir myght &thorn;am mere make</L>
<L N="1928">Soueraynly for godes sake,</L>
<L>Namely &thorn;am &thorn;at er pilgrams knawn,</L>
<L>And pouer &thorn;at hase not of &thorn;er awn.</L>
<L>For god vntil [vs] &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>vntil &thorn;us</I>.</NOTE> sal say</L>
<L N="1932">In dome, a-pon &thorn;e dredful day:<Q>"Hospes eram et colligistis me&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>I wos a gest in my degre,</L>
<L>And in &yogh;our hous &yogh;e herberd me."</L>
<L>&THORN;an aw vs gestes &amp; gud pilgrims</L>
<L N="1936">For to releue in al &thorn;ere lims</L>
<L>And for to refresch in al right,</L>
<L>Als it es det be day &amp; nyght,</L>
<L>And oblis &thorn;am kissink of pese</L>
<L N="1940">Perfite luf forto encres.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai cum, bi day or nyght,</L>
<L>And also when &thorn;ai wend to flight,</L>
<L>Loute vnto &thorn;am aw grete &amp; small</L>
<L N="1944">Or els vnto &thorn;er fete at fall,</L>
<L>Witand wele in &thorn;at sesoune</L>
<L>&THORN;ai honour crist in &thorn;er persoune.</L>
<L>For who so resaues &thorn;e pure man</L>
<L N="1948"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="107b">In crist name, resaues crist &thorn;an.</L>
<L>A souerayn sal ger gestes kepe</L>
<L>
<PB N="103">With honour &amp; with gret wirchepe</L>
<L>Or rede to &thorn;am, or ger be rede,</L>
<L N="1952">How hali men &thorn;er liues lede,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I> is a mistake, possibly for <I>&thorn;er</I> or <I>it</I>.</NOTE> be to &thorn;am puplist,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai sal lif be &thorn;e law of crist.</L>
<L>A priores hir fast sal breke,</L>
<L N="1956">And silence, when scho suld not speke,</L>
<L>To myrth hir gestes in &thorn;at scho may,</L>
<L>Bot if it be dere fasting day</L>
<L>And ymbrin-days or els vigil,</L>
<L N="1960">Whilk ilka man es bun vntil.</L>
<L>Bot al if scho brek, be &yogh;e bold,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Originally <I>bald</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e couent sal &thorn;eir right curs hald.</L>
<L>Scho sal gif water vnto &thorn;er hend<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hand</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1964">And wesch &thorn;eir fete, als crist hase kend.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai so do, &thorn;ai sal reherce,</L>
<L>Word bi word, &amp; say &thorn;is verce:<Q>"Suscepimus, deus, misericordiam tuam in medio&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>We haue resauyd, lord, &thorn;i mercy</L>
<L N="1968">In &thorn;e mydes of &thorn;e hows<NOTE PLACE="foot">Originally <I>&thorn;i|hows</I>.</NOTE> haly."</L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner crist wil vs ken</L>
<L>To resaue pilgrims &amp; pouer men,</L>
<L>For when we &thorn;am resaue with wil,</L>
<L N="1972"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="108a">Crist resaue we vs vntil.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gestes kechin salbe set</L>
<L>Allone, &thorn;at it no no&thorn;er let,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai be seruyd at ese,</L>
<L N="1976">And ilkman redy &thorn;am to plese.</L>
<L>And luk &thorn;er bedes ordand bene</L>
<L>With litter larch &amp; clothes clene,</L>
<L>And swilk seruandes assigned &thorn;am til</L>
<L N="1980">&THORN;at wil &thorn;am serue with gude wil.</L>
<L>None aw &thorn;am do forto greue,</L>
<L>Ne speke with &thorn;am with-outyn leue,</L>
<L>Bot loutand hals &thorn;am wher &thorn;ai go</L>
<L N="1984">And with blissing pase furth &thorn;am fro.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="54">
<PB N="104">
<HEAD>LIV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vt nichil accipiant sine lisencia.</HEAD>
<L>If litters or bils be sent to rede,</L>
<L>Or o&thorn;er giftes of greter mede</L>
<L>Be send fro frendes in feld or toun</L>
<L N="1988">Til women of religioun,</L>
<L>Scho sal resaue non hir vntil,</L>
<L>Bot scho first wit hir souerayn wil.</L>
<L>And if hir frendes fer or nere</L>
<L N="1992">Send hir gudes or giftes sere,</L>
<L>Or scho &thorn;am tak for ony nede,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="108b">To &thorn;e priores scho sal &thorn;am bede.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;e priores at hir wil</L>
<L N="1996">Gif &thorn;o giftes a-noder vntil,</L>
<L>Scho vnto wham &thorn;e giftes whor sent,</L>
<L>Sal not be greuyd in hir entent,</L>
<L>If hir presand be so puruayd,</L>
<L N="2000">Bot in hert sal scho hold hir payde.</L>
<L>For what &thorn;er souerayn dose ilk dele</L>
<L>Aw &thorn;am to think worthi &amp; wele.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="55">
<HEAD>LV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De indumentis.</HEAD>
<L>Thay sal be clede ful wele, we wate,</L>
<L N="2004">Efter &thorn;er place es cald or hate.</L>
<L>For in cald stedes who so er sted,</L>
<L>&THORN;am nedes forto be better cled;</L>
<L>In who er in hate cuntre,</L>
<L N="2008">Sich clething to &thorn;am may be.</L>
<L>And al it sal be puruayd playne</L>
<L>At &thorn;e ordinance of &thorn;eir souerayne.</L>
<L>In comun places for alkins note</L>
<L N="2012">Sufficis a kirtil &amp; a cote;</L>
<L>And mantels sal &thorn;ai haue certayne,</L>
<L>In winter dubil, in somer playne;</L>
<L>And changing kirtils sal &thorn;ai haue</L>
<L N="2016">In nyghtes &thorn;er o&thorn;er forto saue.</L>
<L>Schos &thorn;ai sall haue, whor &thorn;ai dwel,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="109a">Swilk os &thorn;ai may find for to sel.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e farest &thorn;ai sal not by,</L>
<L N="2020">
<PB N="105">Bot &thorn;e vilist ful bowsumly.</L>
<L>And &thorn;eir souerayn aw forto se</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;air gere euynly o[r]dand<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>odand</I>.</NOTE> be,</L>
<L>Mete for &thorn;am &thorn;at sal it fang,</L>
<L N="2024">And no&thorn;er to schort ne to lang.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai tak new, &thorn;e old sal &thorn;en</L>
<L>Be partid til pouer women.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai sal went in cuntre,</L>
<L N="2028">&THORN;air clething sal mor honest be;</L>
<L>And home a-gayn when &thorn;ai cum eft,</L>
<L>&THORN;en sal &thorn;ai were slik os &thorn;ai left.</L>
<L>Vntil &thorn;eir beddyng sal &thorn;ai haue</L>
<L N="2032">At suffise &thorn;am fro cauld to saue.</L>
<L>And oftsithes sall &thorn;er bed be sene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no tresure be &thorn;am be-twene,</L>
<L>Ne no gude &thorn;at to &thorn;am may gayne;</L>
<L N="2036">Who so it hase, sall soffer payne.</L>
<L>For whi &thorn;er souerayn sal &thorn;am bede</L>
<L>All vnto &thorn;am &thorn;at es nede.</L>
<L>Bot when scho gifes, scho sal be-hald<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>salbe hald</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2040">To &thorn;is &thorn;at holi writ hase tald</L>
<L>And set to se for certayne</L>
<L>In &thorn;e dedes of &thorn;e appostil[s]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>appostil</I>.</NOTE> playne:<Q>"Diuidebatur singulis, prout cuique opus erat."</Q></L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="109b">He tels how crist depairtid hase</L>
<L N="2044">Intil ilkon, os myster was.</L>
<L>So suld a souerayn in hir daile</L>
<L>Tak reward to seke &amp; haile,</L>
<L>To &yogh;ing or old, wheder &thorn;ai be,</L>
<L N="2048">And serue ilkon in &thorn;eir degre.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="56">
<HEAD>LVI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De mensa priorisse.</HEAD>
<L>A Priores bord aw forto be</L>
<L>Euer-mor vntil al gestes fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to mene vnto pouer men.</L>
<L N="2052">And when non cumes, scho sal take &thorn;en</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e eldest &amp; &thorn;e most nedy</L>
<L>Of hir sisters &thorn;at wons hir by,</L>
<L>
<PB N="106">In stede of pouer folk, &thorn;am to fede;</L>
<L N="2056">So may scho wyn hir mykil mede.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="57">
<HEAD>LVII.</HEAD>
<L>If ony woman can oght do</L>
<L>&THORN;at ony wining falles vnto,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e prophet of &thorn;eir wyning</L>
<L N="2060">Vnto &thorn;eir souerayn sal &thorn;ai bryng.</L>
<L>And if ony hafe pryde &thorn;er-by,</L>
<L>It sal be tayn fro &thorn;am in hy,</L>
<L>And neuer more sal &thorn;ay negh nere,</L>
<L N="2064">Bot &thorn;e priores gif &thorn;am power.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="110a">And &thorn;at sal not fall, bot scho se</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai be meke &amp; obidient be,</L>
<L>And wil gif al &thorn;eir wyning fayn</L>
<L N="2068">To &thorn;e ordenance of &thorn;er souerayn,</L>
<L>And wil luf god in ilka place,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gifes to &thorn;am swilk giftes of grace.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="58">
<HEAD>LVIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De probacione suscipiendorum.</HEAD>
<L>All if a woman ful eld haue,</L>
<L N="2072">And religion wil to hir craue,</L>
<L>And hase non entisment &thorn;er-til</L>
<L>Bot oblis hir awn wil,</L>
<L>Fully resauyd sal scho not be,</L>
<L N="2076">Or tyme &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ai</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>t</SUP>.  See Notes.</NOTE> hir perseuerans se</L>
<L>And prow hir both be nyghtes &amp; days,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e appostil playnly says.</L>
<L>Hir hert &amp; wil er both to proue,</L>
<L N="2080">If &thorn;ai be gifin til godes bi-houe,</L>
<L>And mak &thorn;am forto vnderstand</L>
<L>&THORN;e hardnes of religioun band.</L>
<L>And if scho bide iiij days or fyue</L>
<L N="2084">And schews grete lawnes in hir liue,</L>
<L>Vnto hir salbe graunte entre;</L>
<L>Bot als a gest &yogh;it sal scho be</L>
<L>And sine a place forto haue grayde,</L>
<L N="2088"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="110b">Als vnto nouysces es puruayd,</L>
<L>And a mastres her forto lere</L>
<L>
<PB N="107">Hir obseruandes &amp; seruys sere,</L>
<L>And to schew hir both gude &amp; ill</L>
<L N="2092">&THORN;at scho salbe obidient til.</L>
<L>And if scho be willy always</L>
<L>To suffer what hir mastres sais,</L>
<L>Sithen efter ij moneth space,</L>
<L N="2096">&THORN;an sal &thorn;ai bring &thorn;is rewle in place</L>
<L>And tel vntil hir opinly</L>
<L>&THORN;is law &thorn;at hir aw to lif by.</L>
<L>When it es red on right array,</L>
<L N="2100">&THORN;e priores sal til hir say:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is rewle if &thorn;ou may &yogh;eme &amp; saue,</L>
<L>We grant &thorn;e entre here to haue;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou may not &thorn;erwith lend,</L>
<L N="2104">We grant &thorn;e lefe frely to wend."</L>
<L>And if scho &thorn;an wil langer dwel,</L>
<L>Scho sal bide in &thorn;e noues sel</L>
<L>At gud laser to lig &amp; rise,</L>
<L N="2108">So &thorn;at scho may hir wele awise</L>
<L>In hir hert, if scho be bald</L>
<L>&THORN;e rewle to tak &thorn;at scho es tald.</L>
<L>When sex moneths er fully gon,</L>
<L N="2112">&THORN;en sall &thorn;is rewel eft furth be ton</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="111a">And red to hir, os mykil os nedes,</L>
<L>How scho sal rewle both wordes &amp; dedes.</L>
<L>And if scho &yogh;it wil lely last,</L>
<L N="2116">When xij moneths er playnly past,</L>
<L>&THORN;is sal eft be to hir red,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at scho be not lyghtli led,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at scho wit be on &amp; on</L>
<L N="2120">&THORN;e pontes wher-to scho hase hir tone.</L>
<L>And if scho so with a-visement</L>
<L>Hete to fulfil with gude entent</L>
<L>What so &thorn;ai deme bi day or nyght,</L>
<L N="2124">&THORN;en sal scho be resauyd right</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e kirk emang &thorn;am all;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at day &thorn;erin dwel scho sall.</L>
<L>In hir-self &thorn;en sal scho knaw</L>
<L N="2128">&THORN;at scho sal neuer, for godes aw,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at rewle reklisly gang,</L>
<L>
<PB N="108">Sen &thorn;at scho es avised so lang.</L>
<L>To chapitur sine scho salbe tayn</L>
<L N="2132">In-mang &thorn;e couent euer-ilkayn,</L>
<L>And vnto god &thorn;er sal scho hete,</L>
<L>Falland doun be-for &thorn;er fete,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="111b">&THORN;at scho sall fathfuly fulfill</L>
<L N="2136">Al &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue told hir till.</L>
<L>Vnto mary, cristes moder dere,</L>
<L>And to al halows of heuyn clere</L>
<L>Sal scho hete &thorn;er &thorn;am emang.</L>
<L N="2140">&THORN;an may scho wit: if scho do wrang</L>
<L>Or maynten it not with hir mayine,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hirmayine</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al wil &thorn;ai witnes hir ogayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal scho make blithly hir bown</L>
<L N="2144">And puruay hir peticioun.</L>
<L>With hir awn hand it salbe wroght,</L>
<L>Or with a-no&thorn;er, if scho can noght;</L>
<L>Bot scho sal luke &thorn;at it be lele,</L>
<L N="2148">And set &thorn;erto signet or sele.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e awter scho sal it lay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er wordes &thorn;en sal scho say:<Q>"Suscipe me, domine, secundum eloquium|tuum, et viuam, &amp; non confundar."</Q></L>
<L>And &thorn;ir same [wordes] on<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>same on</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;is wise</L>
<L N="2152">Sal &thorn;ai ilkon reherce thrise</L>
<L>With "gloria patri" put &thorn;erto</L>
<L>And "Sicut erat" sine also.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nouese &thorn;an be-for &thorn;am all</L>
<L N="2156">Al flat vnto &thorn;e erth sal fall,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="112a">Besekand &thorn;am on ilka side</L>
<L>For to pray for hir &thorn;at tide.</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at day sal scho rekynd be</L>
<L N="2160">On &thorn;e couent in hir degre.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at scho hase &thorn;en,</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er sal scho &yogh;if &thorn;am to pouer men,</L>
<L>Besekand &thorn;am for hir to pray,</L>
<L N="2164">Or els vnto hir awn abbay.</L>
<L>Vnto hir-self scho sal haue noght</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at scho hase &thorn;eder broght.</L>
<L>
<PB N="109">Vntil o&thorn;er scho sal it take,</L>
<L N="2168">And hir awn wil scho sal for-sake.</L>
<L>Hir awn wedes scho sal lay doun</L>
<L>And take cloths of religioun.</L>
<L>Hir cloths sal &thorn;an albedene</L>
<L N="2172">Be samyn layd &amp; kepid clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at if case fall at &thorn;e &yogh;ere end</L>
<L>&THORN;at scho in-to &thorn;e world wil wend,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same wede &thorn;at scho can for-sake,</L>
<L N="2176">&THORN;at sal scho were &amp; with hir take.</L>
<L>Bot hir bil of peticioun</L>
<L>Sall leue stil in religioun.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="59">
<HEAD>LIX.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De nouicijs iuuenibus suscipiendis.</HEAD>
<L>[M]ay fal &thorn;at ou&thorn;er man or wife<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. p. 9, l. 22 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2180"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="112b">Wold haue &thorn;er child <NOTE PLACE="foot">A prep. (<I>in</I>) or verb (<I>lede,|lere</I>) seems to be omitted.</NOTE> haly life,</L>
<L>And offer it vnto haly kirk;</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wise &thorn;am aw to wirk:</L>
<L>If &thorn;er child be so &yogh;ung,</L>
<L N="2184">&THORN;at it can not tel with tung<NOTE PLACE="foot">2183 and 2184 were written,|by mistake, in the reverse order.  Then the letters b and a|were added in the margin.  Cf. 1775 ff.  The words <I>it</I> and|<I>not</I> in 2184 were omitted and then added above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>What es to leue ne what to take,</L>
<L>&THORN;en sal &thorn;e frendes peticions make.</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;ai sal &thorn;e childes hand</L>
<L N="2188">And bil &amp; &thorn;er awn offerand</L>
<L>With reuerence, os &thorn;e rewle hase kend,</L>
<L>And law al on &thorn;e awter end.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai mak peticioun,</L>
<L N="2192">A certayn soume &thorn;ai sal lay doune,</L>
<L>Or els hete of &thorn;er gudes to gif</L>
<L>Whor-of &thorn;er child may lere to lif.</L>
<L>Til it-self sal &thorn;ai gif no thing,</L>
<L N="2196">Gold ne siluer, broch ne ryng,</L>
<L>Bot opinly it gif sal &thorn;ai</L>
<L>Vnto god &amp; to &thorn;e abbay,</L>
<L>And childer &thorn;at frenchep hase none,</L>
<L N="2200">For godes sake &thorn;ai salbe tone.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="63">
<PB N="110">
<HEAD>LXIII.</HEAD>
<L>And fro time &thorn;ai resauyd be,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="113a">Al salbe sarued in o degre,</L>
<L>Rich &amp; pure, &amp; &yogh;ong &amp; old,</L>
<L N="2204">In form os be-for es told.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e &yogh;ong, whor so &thorn;ai err,</L>
<L>Sal ordan<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ordan</I>, corrupt for honor or the like?  Cf. p. 9, l. 13.</NOTE> &thorn;am &thorn;at er elder,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e elder in alkins &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="2208">Sal luf &amp; lere &thorn;am &thorn;at er &yogh;ing.</L>
<L>"Damisel" &thorn;e &yogh;ongest es,</L>
<L>&THORN;e elder "madaum" &amp; "mastres."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Priores als principall</L>
<L N="2212">Es "lady" &amp; leder of &thorn;am all,</L>
<L>And not al for hir awn bi-houe,</L>
<L>Bot for hir staite &amp; cristes luf.</L>
<L>And whor so euer &thorn;ai gang o-boute,</L>
<L N="2216">&THORN;e &yogh;onger sal &thorn;e elder loute</L>
<L>And do &thorn;am reuerence, als es right,</L>
<L>In word &amp; dede, be day &amp; nyght.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="64">
<HEAD>LXIV.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De eleccione priorisse.</HEAD>
<L>A Priores aw to be chosen</L>
<L N="2220">&THORN;e best in lifyng leli losen,</L>
<L>Be ordinance &amp; bi hali assent</L>
<L>And councel of al &thorn;e couent,</L>
<L>Takand non for luf ne mede,</L>
<L N="2224">Ne leueand non for aw ne drede;</L>
<L>Bot for gude luf &amp; for godes sake</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="113b">A worthi souerayn sal &thorn;ai take,</L>
<L>Whilk &thorn;ai knaw perfite &amp; stabil,</L>
<L N="2228">And als emang &thorn;aim most abill</L>
<L>Of wit &amp; cunsel &amp; of cunyng,</L>
<L>And vsand euynhed in al thing.</L>
<L>And if it fel, os god forbede,</L>
<L N="2232">&THORN;at ony wold for worldly mede</L>
<L>Samyn be &thorn;am-self assent,</L>
<L>With-outyn consel of &thorn;e couent,</L>
<L>Forto chese swilk a souerayn</L>
<L N="2236">
<PB N="111">Als to &thorn;er bedynges wold be bayn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air doyng wor fundyn slike,</L>
<L>&THORN;en sal &thorn;e bisschop of &thorn;at rike</L>
<L>Swilk a priores sone depose,</L>
<L N="2240">And mak on bi &thorn;eir aller chose.</L>
<L>And foles &thorn;at in &thorn;er fath wil fayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salbe chastid fro cownsaile,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at in godes hows may be</L>
<L N="2244">A gude &yogh;emer of godes men&yogh;e.</L>
<L>For wit &thorn;ai wele &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal cum</L>
<L>To reknyng on &thorn;e day of dome</L>
<L>For &thorn;er myschesing &thorn;am omang,</L>
<L N="2248">Als sche sal for hir warkes wrang.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai chese wele &amp; lely,</L>
<L>&THORN;an falles a ful grete mede &thorn;erby,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="114a">So &thorn;at &thorn;ai tak gude rewarde</L>
<L N="2252">&THORN;at noder on be spede ne o&thorn;er sparde</L>
<L>For no ponte &thorn;at men may pruefe,</L>
<L>Bot anely for our lordes lufe.</L>
<L>When scho es chosin on &thorn;is maner</L>
<L N="2256">And confermyd in hir playne power,</L>
<L>&THORN;en aw hir forto luke allayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>alleyn</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at charch &thorn;at scho hase tayn</L>
<L>And vnto wham hir aw to &yogh;eld</L>
<L N="2260">Reknyng both in &yogh;outh in eld,</L>
<L>Ill or wele whe&thorn;er scho spend</L>
<L>&THORN;e charch &thorn;at scho hase tayn in hend.</L>
<L>Al if scho be highest in degre,</L>
<L N="2264">In hir-self lawest sal scho be.</L>
<L>Hir aw to be gude of forthoght</L>
<L>What thinges es to wirk &amp; what noght,</L>
<L>Chaste &amp; sober, meke &amp; myld,</L>
<L N="2268">Of bering bowsum os a child.</L>
<L>Sin &amp; vices sal scho hate</L>
<L>And luf hir sisters ayrly &amp; laite.</L>
<L>Scho salbe sober in al thyng</L>
<L N="2272">And naymly in hir chastying,</L>
<L>To lay on &thorn;am &thorn;at vnder hir er</L>
<L>No euyer band &thorn;an &thorn;ay may ber,</L>
<L>
<PB N="112"> <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="114b">&THORN;at whils scho rubes a-way &thorn;e rust,</L>
<L N="2276">&THORN;e vessel fal not al to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>alto</I>.</NOTE> dust.</L>
<L>Hir maistri euer sal mesurd be,</L>
<L>Thinkand on hir awn frelte</L>
<L>Lik to a rede in a forest,</L>
<L N="2280">&THORN;at bows with wind &amp; wil not brest.</L>
<L>Scho sal so her what ilkon sais,</L>
<L>And be wise in hir wordes alwais.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De condicionibus Priorisse.</HEAD>
<L>A Priores hertly sal hast</L>
<L N="2284">Al vice &amp; syns away to waist</L>
<L>And ordan for &thorn;am gastly bute,</L>
<L>Or tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue takin rute,</L>
<L>And ordan alway hir entent</L>
<L N="2288">For to be lufid of hir couent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai hir honor in word &amp; dede</L>
<L>For luf &amp; not aynly for drede.</L>
<L>Scho sal not be contrarius</L>
<L N="2292">Ne ouer-lyghtly suspecius.</L>
<L>In al hir bidinges scho salbe</L>
<L>Resonabil &amp; also avise,</L>
<L>Wheder it be for gastly thing</L>
<L N="2296">Or worldly &thorn;at scho makes bidyng.</L>
<L>And when scho comaundes oght to do,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="115a">Swilk rewling sal scho hafe &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it be mesured on gude maners,</L>
<L N="2300">Als sant Ion &thorn;e apostil leres:<Q>"Si greges meos faciam &amp;c.;&mdash;</Q></L>
<L>If I ger my bestes," he sais,</L>
<L>"Trauel mor be nyghtes or dais</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;er power perfourn may,</L>
<L N="2304">&THORN;an wil &thorn;ai fall down in &thorn;e way."</L>
<L>&THORN;us bi ensaumpil sal scho take</L>
<L>Materly al thinges to make,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at al thinges in dede &amp; saw</L>
<L N="2308">Be mesured euermor os &thorn;am aw,</L>
<L>And ilka thing in &thorn;er degre,</L>
<L>Bodely or gastly wheder it be.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is ilk rewle &thorn;us if scho rede</L>
<L N="2312">
<PB N="113">And fulfil it in word &amp; dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;en may scho &thorn;er wordes vnderstand,</L>
<L>How crist says of a gud seruand:<Q>"Super omnia bona sua constituet eum."</Q></L>
<L>He &thorn;at in life es funden lele</L>
<L N="2316">In word &amp; wark alway to wele,</L>
<L>Hym wil &thorn;e lord with-outyn lete</L>
<L>Ouer al his gudes assingne<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>assingnes</I>.</NOTE> &amp; sett</L>
<L>And haly put in-til his hand</L>
<L N="2320">Both corn &amp; katel, Hows &amp; land,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="115b">And chanch hym wil he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>, MS. <I>I</I>.</NOTE> for no new</L>
<L>Be reson &thorn;at he findes him trew.</L>
<L>And efterward for his gude dede</L>
<L N="2324">&THORN;e lord wil larchly gif him mede.</L>
<L>So sal al &thorn;o haue wele, we knaw,</L>
<L>&THORN;at trewly dos euer os &thorn;am aw.</L>
</DIV3></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="68">
<HEAD>LXVIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Si inpossibilia iniungentur.</HEAD>
<L>A Priores, als I sayd air,</L>
<L N="2328">Aw to be mesured euermair</L>
<L>To bind non bot als<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>als bot</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;ai may bere,</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;er warkes worthi ere,</L>
<L>And bid non do by nyght &amp; day</L>
<L N="2332">Vn-mesurely mor &thorn;an &thorn;ai may.</L>
<L>And if scho put any vntil</L>
<L>Mor wark &thorn;en &thorn;ai may fulfil,</L>
<L>Til hir bedynges &thorn;ai sal be bayn</L>
<L N="2336">And no&thorn;er gruch ne spek ogayn.</L>
<L>Bot forther, if &thorn;ai se in sight</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e trauel passes &thorn;er myght,</L>
<L>Vn-to hir sal &thorn;ai pray mekely</L>
<L N="2340">Forto relese &thorn;am sum party,</L>
<L>Telland to hir al &thorn;er encheson.</L>
<L>And if scho wil not her &thorn;er reson,</L>
<L>&yogh;it sall &thorn;ai not &thorn;am-self it slake,</L>
<L N="2344"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="116a">Bot suffer it for godes sake,</L>
<L>Thinkand on &thorn;air mikil mede;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal god strengh in &thorn;er dede.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="69">
<PB N="114">
<HEAD>LXIX.</HEAD>
<L>And on al wise &thorn;ai sal take tent,</L>
<L N="2348">&THORN;at no &thorn;ing be don in couent,</L>
<L>In word ne wark ne nokins wise,</L>
<L>Whar-of outward myght sclaunder rise.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="70">
<HEAD>LXX.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vt nulla aliam cedat vel offendat.</HEAD>
<L>Tham<NOTE PLACE="foot">The h in <I>Tham</I> was added subsequently.</NOTE> aw to tent vnto &thorn;is &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="2352">&THORN;at non of &thorn;am sal o&thorn;er dyng,</L>
<L>Ne none herdy oder to greue,</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e Priores gifes leue</L>
<L>And power o&thorn;er to chasty</L>
<L N="2356">&THORN;at funden er in ony foly.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &thorn;at opinly er blamyd,</L>
<L>Al opinly &thorn;ai sal be shamyd,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at o&thorn;er may wernyd be</L>
<L N="2360">Fro al slik folis forto fle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nouece &thorn;at &thorn;is rewle sal lere,</L>
<L>Vntil &thorn;ai be past xv &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Sal be in keping of mastres</L>
<L N="2364">To chasty &thorn;am, when worthi es,</L>
<L>Als it falles &thorn;e trispas to.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="116b">And o&thorn;er-wise if &thorn;at scho do,</L>
<L>Scho sal be punyst for &thorn;at dede;</L>
<L N="2368">For it es writyn, os men may rede:</L>
<L>"Vntil a-no&thorn;er &thorn;ou sal not do</L>
<L>Bot os &thorn;ou wold wor don &thorn;e to."</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sam wise sall ilk souerayn</L>
<L N="2372">Do os &thorn;ai wil take o-gayn.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="67">
<HEAD>LXVII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De exeuntibus et redeuntibus.</HEAD>
<L>Asister, when scho sal oute wende</L>
<L>To fadir or moder or o&thorn;er frend,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal scho tak with gude entent</L>
<L N="2376">Hir leue of all &thorn;e hale couent,</L>
<L>Besekand &thorn;am for hir to pray</L>
<L>&THORN;at god hir wise in all her way.</L>
<L>
<PB N="115">And al &thorn;e couent, small &amp; grete,</L>
<L N="2380">Aw no day forto for-gete,</L>
<L>Bot ilkay day to mak &thorn;er bone,</L>
<L>When seruys of &thorn;e day es done,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er sister &thorn;at er not &thorn;air,</L>
<L N="2384">&THORN;at god enforce &thorn;am in &thorn;er fair.</L>
<L>And when on so hase bene to play,</L>
<L>When scho cummes home, al &thorn;e first day</L>
<L>Prayng sal &thorn;ai put &thorn;am to,</L>
<L N="2388">Besekand oder to pray also</L>
<L>&THORN;at god for-gif with gude entent,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="117a">If &thorn;ai oght wrethid hym, sen &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L>In sight or in hering of eres,</L>
<L N="2392">In word or dede &thorn;at &thorn;e sawle deres,</L>
<L>Or wantunly if &thorn;ai haf wroght</L>
<L>Outher in word, or dede, or thoght.</L>
<L>Of god &thorn;ai sal ask for-gifnes</L>
<L N="2396">And make amendes for mor &amp; lese.</L>
<L>To &thorn;er sisters &thorn;ai sal not tell,</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;ai wer furth how it befell</L>
<L>Of thing &thorn;at myght oght turn to tene;</L>
<L N="2400">For of slik hase harmes bene sene.</L>
<L>Ne outward sal &thorn;ai no thing say</L>
<L>&THORN;at es done with-in &thorn;eir abbay;</L>
<L>Ne oute of close sal &thorn;ai not pas,</L>
<L N="2404">Bot &thorn;ai leue of &thorn;er souerayn ass;</L>
<L>Ne no charge and<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>chargeand</I>.</NOTE> thing sal &thorn;ai do,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ai haue hir lef &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>And who so dose oght here-ogayn</L>
<L N="2408">Efter &thorn;e rewle sal suffer payn.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="66">
<HEAD>LXVI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De officio hostiarij.</HEAD>
<L>Ane old man sal &thorn;e &yogh;ates &yogh;eme</L>
<L>&THORN;at witti es &amp; wele wil seme</L>
<L>For to welcum with wordes fre</L>
<L N="2412">Euyr-ilk man in &thorn;er degre.</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="117b">His dwelling sal be dyght algayte</L>
<L>In a cel be-side &thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>
<PB N="116">So &thorn;at he be redy ay</L>
<L N="2416">Til al &thorn;at cums be nyght or day.</L>
<L>And when so ony knok or call,</L>
<L>Softli answer &thorn;am he sall.</L>
<L>To her &thorn;er wordes sal he be bayn</L>
<L N="2420">And bryng &thorn;am grath answer ogayn.</L>
<L>And baynly sal he bryng &amp; take</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at men sendes for godes sake.</L>
<L>And euer him aw to &yogh;eme &thorn;e &yogh;ate</L>
<L N="2424">For al auenturs arely &amp; layte.</L>
<L>In abbais aw to be al thing</L>
<L>&THORN;at nedeful es to &thorn;eir lifing,</L>
<L>Als watter for to do al &thorn;er dedis,</L>
<L N="2428">Miln, kiln, &amp; ouen, &amp; al &thorn;at nedis,</L>
<L>Gardins, &amp; al o&thorn;er ger</L>
<L>With-in &thorn;am wroght, &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal wer,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal not outward gang</L>
<L N="2432">To say for dred, or wirk, oght wrang.</L>
<L>&THORN;us es &thorn;is rewle ordand to rede</L>
<L>[Als] Oft-sithes als<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Oft sithes als</I>; cf. 1668, 2113.</NOTE> it es nede,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at non sal &thorn;am excuse,</L>
<L N="2436"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="118a">To knaw &thorn;eir rewle &amp; right it vse.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="71">
<HEAD>LXXI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>De obediencia ad inuicem.</HEAD>
<L>Ilk sister sall obedient be</L>
<L>Vnto o&thorn;er in &thorn;air degre,</L>
<L>Witand &thorn;at es &thorn;e sekir way</L>
<L N="2440">Vnto &thorn;e lif &thorn;at lastes ay.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e Priores os prencipall</L>
<L>Sal be honord ouer &thorn;am all;</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er, efter &thorn;ai haue power,</L>
<L N="2444">Salbe honord with seruis ser.</L>
<L>And sithen sal ilkon bainly bow</L>
<L>To honour oder &amp; wil &thorn;er prow.</L>
<L>And who so euer vnbowsum es</L>
<L N="2448">Or rebel to &thorn;er priores,</L>
<L>Or greues hir in ony degre,</L>
<L>Al if &thorn;e trispas litil be,</L>
<L>
<PB N="117">Be-for her fete down sal &thorn;ai fall,</L>
<L N="2452">And so lang &thorn;er lig &thorn;ai sall.</L>
<L>And who so gruches her-ogayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal be gert with greuus payn.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai wil not mend &thorn;erby,</L>
<L N="2456">&THORN;ai sal be chaistid fro company.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="72">
<HEAD>LXXII.</HEAD>
<L>For right os euel luf mor or les,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es fulfilid of bitternes,</L>
<L>Twins fro god, os clerkes tell,</L>
<L N="2460">And ledes a man to pyne of hell,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="118b">Right so gude luf in al degre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es fulfillid of charite,</L>
<L>Twins a man fro<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fro</I>, MS. <I>for</I>.</NOTE> syn &amp; strif</L>
<L N="2464">And ledes him vnto lastand lif.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilk luf suld sisters haue</L>
<L>Emang &thorn;am-self &thorn;er saule to saue,</L>
<L>And ilkon honor o&thorn;er alwais,</L>
<L N="2468">Als &thorn;e appostil playnly sais:<Q>"Honore inuecem preuenientes."</Q></L>
<L>Sekenes sal &thorn;ai gladly bere,</L>
<L>Bodily or gastly wheder &thorn;ai ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;eir awn winyng &thorn;ai sal not wayt,</L>
<L N="2472">&THORN;at o&thorn;er win &thorn;ai sal couayt.</L>
<L>God sal &thorn;ai hertly drede &amp; luf</L>
<L>And &thorn;er souerayn for his be-houe,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai set non erthly &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="2476">Be-for &thorn;e luf of crist, heuyn kyng,</L>
<L>For his lofers ledes he euyn</L>
<L>Vntil his kyngdom hegh on heuyn.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at kingdom he vs lede,</L>
<L N="2480">&THORN;at sufferd dede for our mysdede.</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="73">
<HEAD>LXXIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Conclucio tocius regule.</HEAD>
<L>This<NOTE PLACE="foot">The h in <I>This</I> was added|subsequently.</NOTE> rewle es ordand &thorn;us to rede</L>
<L>To mend our mys &amp; merk vs mede,</L>
<L>
<PB N="118"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="119a">And grath teching til vs at gif,</L>
<L N="2484">In cristes law [how] we<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>law we</I>; cf. 1954.</NOTE> sal lif,</L>
<L>And to draw fro alkin strife</L>
<L>Onto perfeccion of gude life.</L>
<L>For it teches to les &amp; more</L>
<L N="2488">Of haly faders &thorn;at war before.</L>
<L>And if we &thorn;er-in haue delite,</L>
<L>It ledes vs to lif perfite.</L>
<L>For al lessons, als men may luke,</L>
<L N="2492">&THORN;at wretyn er in haly buke,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ai be of moises law</L>
<L>Or of cristes, whilk we suld knaw,</L>
<L>And liues of marters &amp; confessours,</L>
<L N="2496">And teching of godes dere doctours,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Possibly: <I>And|liues &thorn;at</I>; cf. 1952.</NOTE> haly virgins lede,</L>
<L>And rewles, &thorn;at [er] vntil<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at vntil</I>; cf. 1951, 2117.</NOTE> vs rede,</L>
<L>Of basil, Bede, &amp; o&thorn;er mo&mdash;</L>
<L N="2500">Al er &thorn;ai teching vs vnto</L>
<L>And ensaumpil how we sal vse</L>
<L>Gude vertuse, &amp; vices refuse.</L>
<L>To &thorn;am &thorn;at lifes wele, old or &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="2504">Er swilk lessons ful grete likyng.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;am &thorn;at lifes synfully</L>
<L>And refuses to be rewlid &thorn;erby,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="119b">&THORN;an es it gret confucioun</L>
<L N="2508">And hertly schame in ilk sesoun.</L>
<L>For if &thorn;eir lifyng be vnlele,</L>
<L>&THORN;am think dedeyn with it to dele.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfor al &thorn;at &thorn;arto hase hight,</L>
<L N="2512">Saue &thorn;is rewle &amp; &yogh;eme it ryght,</L>
<L>And pray god hertly with gude wil</L>
<L>To gif &thorn;am myght &amp; grace &thorn;ertil.</L>
<L>&THORN;en endles lif sal be &thorn;air mede.</L>
<L N="2516">Vnto &thorn;at lif our lord vs lede!  //amen.//</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>//Explicit.//</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="section">
<PB N="119">
<HEAD>III. THE CAXTON ABSTRACT|OF|The Rule of St. Benet.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(Cambridge University Library, AB. 4. 64.)</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa Ia">&para; Here felowyth a compendious abstracte translate |into englysshe out of the holy rule of saynte Benet for|men and wymmen, of the habyte therof, the whiche|vnderstonde lytyll laten or none / to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton regularly prints <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>e</SUP>.</NOTE> entent &thorn;at they|maye often rede / execute the hole rewll and the better|kepe it than it is / accordyng to the abyte &amp; their streyte|professyon / so that the welle of their sowlys and better|emsample of that holy relygyon maye be the sooner had|and knowen.</P>
<P>He or she &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Through <I>&thorn;at</I> there|arises an anocoluthon.</NOTE> is to be made hede or souereyn in a|monestary / in whom all the hole congregacion|in one acorde after god consentyth / or els that the more|parte therof and sadder wyth god counseyll chesith.</P>
<P>Whan soo euer ony takyth by true eleccyon the|name and dygnytee of an hede or souereyn in|relygyon / they owne to shewe in their dedys to their|disciples two doctrynes / that is to sey, that all suche good|dedys and holy that they teche / &thorn;at they first shewe hem|by their owne dedys rather than by theyr wordys / And|al thynges that they teche their <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa jb">children and disciples |to be contrari to god &amp; their rule / lete her dedes shew|openly suche thinges not to be done, soo &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>so o &thorn;</I><SUP>t</SUP>.</NOTE> theimselfe|be not founde gylty &amp; reprouable in their doctryne &amp;|ensample / &amp; redy to see a lytill mote in their disciples|eyen / but a grete blocke or beme in their owne they|can not espie / but lete it lye styll.  The souereyns also|shulde not dissymyle in punyshment and chastysyng of|theyr subgettes whan they offende / but assone as the
<PB N="120">|synnes begyn to sprynge / forthwyth cut hem vp by the|rote by correccyon accordyng to the rule wythoute acceptynge|of ony persone / Remembryng &thorn;at foles wyll neuer|be corrected with wordis, but rather by chastisment / As|ofte as ony grete maters arn to be doon in the monestary /|all &thorn;e congregacion is to be callyd &amp; to be enformed|of hem by the souereyns / &thorn;e whiche owe to here the|myndys of echone syngulerly / for oft tymes oure lorde|shewyth to the symplest of the relygyon a thynge that|is best therfore.  how be it, what som euer shalbe seide|of the subgettes / see that it be doon wyth al mekenes|and submyssyon of spirite &amp; body / And therevpon the| souereyn ouht to kepe well in mynde <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa ija"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton prints <I>a ij</I> instead of <I>aa ij</I>.</NOTE>the resons or|seyenges of euery of theim / and to doo therafter as can|be founde best and proffitable / For it is a token of an|vnwytty mynde and of a prowde hert of theym that take|their owne way oonly &amp; counseyll.  Also as it is accordynge|to a disciple for to obey his mayster, soo it is|requyred to the souereyn visely &amp; warely and all thynges|of the place to dispose.  To other thynges of lesse charge|the souereyn owe to take counseyle of the senyours of|the relygion &amp; sadder / Soo &thorn;at euery thyng is to be doone|at ony tyme wyth counseyle accordynge to scripture &thorn;at|seyth: "Doo all thynges wyth counseyle / &amp; thou shall|not repente after."  Also bere in thy mynde this synguler|note that the hede or the souereyn wyth all the congregacion|streytly be bounde to folowe the rule in euery|poynte / &amp; that none of theim be soo bolde to declyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>declyue</I>.</NOTE>|or departe therfro; So that none folowe the wyll of theyr|owne mynde oonly / but euer be redy to be reformyd.|The subgettes also owe to be ryght ware &thorn;at they make|no strife wythyn or wythout wyth theyr souereyns / yf|that they doo, anone lete hem haue the streyt reguler| punysshment wyth &thorn;e fere of god and in <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa ijb"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton prints <I>a ij</I> instead of <I>aa ij</I>.</NOTE>kepynge the|rule / remembrynge that the hede withoute ony dowte|shall yeue a full<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>afull</I>.</NOTE> streyte accompte oo day of all their|Iugementes &amp; byhauour to god atte ferefull daye of|rekenynge.  &para; Also be they ware that they trowble not
<PB N="121">|their flocke that ben commytted vnto theim, and that they|dyspose noo thynge of the place vnry&yogh;twysly, as though|they wolde vse theim as their owne / the whyche is|ayens god vterly &amp; &thorn;e reule.  Therfore it is good that|they at all tymes so behaue theim in vertue, that all people|may saye / "loo, suche one is worthy to occupye thys|place and to haue thys dignytee."  Wherfore suche owe|not to be chosen therto by their age / but for their|wertuous lyuyng and wysdom, chastyte and sobre dealyng,|and also for their pyte and mercy the whyche thei muste|vse in all their dedys / that they the rather maye haue|the same of god whan someuer they trespasse / See thenne|that they loue well their chyldren / and hate their synnes /|&amp; in amending of their maners and correccyon of their|synnes wysely to behaue theim / For to moche in ony|thyng is nought, leeste &thorn;at thei breke the <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa iija">vesell / of the |whiche wythoute discrecion and pyte they wolde haue|taken of the rust / Also they must see that they prouffyte|in theyr werkys more than for to loke for worship / and|euer to studye to haue loue rather of the subgettes than|drede / dooynge all thynges wyth discrecion / whiche is|moder of all wertues / consideryng theyr owne freylte,|where-thorough of theyr subgettes the better they may|haue compassion whan someuer they trespase.  Also thei|may not be yrefull, vnrestfull, or obstynate / or to be|Ielouse / or moche suspeccyouse ouer theyr subgettes /|for thenne they shall neuer haue rest to-gyder in the|relygyon / and euer kepe the rule.  Also the souereyn &amp;|the subgettes owe euer to flee Idylnesse, &thorn;e norisshe of|al synnes, &amp; to be ocupyed euer in vertu, louyng god wyth|all their herte of all theyr soule and of all their strength|and theyr neyghbour as theyr selfe / doyng euer vnto|theym as they wolde be done vnto / dyspisyng theyrselfe|and folow crist by the crosse of penaunce.  Also|they must chastyse theyr body and flee the pleasur therof /|and to vse fastynge &amp; refresshe the poore peple wyth|dedes of mercy <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa iijb">goostly and bodely / and medle lytyll |wyth worldly actes, no thyng preferryng aboue the loue|of god / wrath or deceyte neuer to kepe in herte or to|promyse ony false peas / kepynge euer charytee / And
<PB N="122">|vse neuer to swere / leeste<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>neuer / to swere leeste</I>.</NOTE> that by custome ye fall in|periurie / and sey euer the trouth in herte &amp; mouth /|neuer yeldyng euyll for euyll / but rather good for euyll /|doyng no wronge to ony, but for to suffre paciently whan|it is done to you / loue your enmyes / &amp; curse hem not /|&amp; be redy to take persecucion for a ri&yogh;twys mater /|neuer be prowde or dronklew nor moche etyng or slouthfull|/ not grutchynge or bakbytynge / euer puttynge your|trust in our lord god.  Whan &thorn;at ye see ony goodnes in|your-selfe / anone put it to oure lorde &amp; not to your-selfe.|all thinge that is euyll ascryue to your-selfe.  Fere euer|the daye of Iugement &amp; the dungeon of hell / desyrynge|wyth all your mynde &amp; herte &thorn;e euerlastyng lyfe / &amp;|haue euere deth suspecte afore your eyen / &amp; gyde euer|your dedes wysely in euery hour / And be certeyn &thorn;at|god beholdith theim in eueri place / &amp; euery euyl thought|that commyth to your mynde, anone put it awaye by| thynkyng of cristes passyon / &amp; shewe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa iiija">theym by confessyon|to your goostly fader / &amp; kepe euer your tongue|from euyll and shrewde langage / &amp; speke lytyll &amp; well /|&amp; euer auoyde vayn wordes and dissolute laughter &amp;|Iapes, and be glad to here gode lectures and lyues of|sayntes with preyer / dayly waylyng your synnes &amp; the|synnes &amp; Ignoraunce of the peple wyth amendes makyng /|The preceptes of your souereyn in all thynges obey lefull|as to god &amp; fulfyll theym / Loue euer chastyte / &amp; flee|euer enuy / hatrede &amp; stryff / &amp; worship your elders / &amp;|fauour the yong in all loue and drede of god.  Euer pray|for your enmyes / &amp; or the sone goo downe, be in perfyte|peas wyth theym dayly to your power / &amp; neuer dyspeyr of|the grete mercy of god / Loo, thyes ben the Instrumentes|of the spirituell crafte &amp; occupacion, &thorn;e which exercisid|and doon, oure lorde hath promysed to you and vs that|eye neuer sawe / nor ere euer herde, nor cowde euer in-to|mannys herte ascende, &thorn;e whiche to al his louyng seruantes|he hath ordened.  amen.</P>
<P>Obedyence is a grete vertu done without grutchyng|or taryenge.  It is the fyrst steppe vnto mekenes /
<PB N="123">|&amp; it is right specyous<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>specyou<GAP></I>.</NOTE> &amp; nedefull to be had for all peple &amp;|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa iiijb">namely for relygyous persones.  True obediencers, assone |as thei be called or commaundid of theyr souereyn / anone|after &thorn;e worde seyde / they be redy wyth all gladnesse to|doo the dede so commaundid / settyng asyde all other|thynges vndone &amp; their owne wyll in euery poynt / and|&thorn;at wyth all quyknesse of herte &amp; body for drede of our|lorde.  Wherfore he callyth suche a lyfe / a streyt waye|to heuen / and not a comyn waye where synners take her|owne wyll / &amp; be not vndir the yocke of obedyence to an|other / Wythouten doubte trew obedyencers folow surely|oure lorde &amp; his wordes where he seyth / "I come not|in-to thys world to doo myn owne wyll, but the wyll of|my fader<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>myfader</I>.</NOTE> the whiche sent me" / Thenne this obedience is|gretly acceptable to god and swete to al cristen peple, whan|it is done quikly and wythoute grutchynge or frowarde|countenaunce in worde or in herte / Our lorde loueth a|thyng done vnto hym cherefully in soule / and such|obedience done to the souereyn / is done to god &amp; for|god, as he seyth hymselfe.  Yf one obey with grutchyng|either in worde or in their herte, fulfyllyng the commaundement|of theyr souereyn<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa va"> / yet it is not acceptable |to god / the whiche beholdyth the herte euer &amp; the wyll|of the doer therof / &amp; he shal haue noo grace but rather|payne ordeined for grutchers, without he amende him.</P>
<P>As for silence, doo aftir the cheyf prophete of god,|dauid, where he seyth in &thorn;e sauter / "I haue|seyd that<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>seydthat</I>.</NOTE> I shall not offende in my tongue / I haue put a|kepyng to my mowth / &amp; am dompe and therwith made|meke &amp; silent" / In moche speche, as it is writen, synne|cann not be auoyded / also in &thorn;e power of the tongue|is deth &amp; lyfe / As it accordith to a mayster to speke &amp;|teche, so it behoueth the disciple to here &amp; be silent /|wordes of vnclennes / voyde, or meuynge to disolucyon or|to laughter, ben dampned by the rule in ony place to be|had / &amp; it is commaundid streytly by the same / none to|be so bolde to open their mowth in suche maner of
<PB N="124">|talkyng / Also silence is to be kept by the rule at all|tymes &amp; spyrituelly at nyght after complyn, and noo|licence thenne is to be gyuen to ony for to speke but oonly|to officers / or to theim that grete nede causith to speke|with sadnesse &amp; honestee / &amp; silence also is to be kept at| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa vb">all refeccions and meles &amp; in other places / &amp; at other|tymes specyfyed by the rule / Yf theyr be founde ony|gylty in theis premyses, thei ou&yogh;t to be punysshid streytly|and greuously.</P>
<P>Holy scrypture cryeth and seyth / "he that wyll|high hymselfe shal be made lowe, and he that|mekyth hym selfe shall be made high" / In thys is shewid|that exaltacyon is &thorn;e doughter and nygh of kyne to pryde,|whiche is mortall / Yf we wyll atteyne and come to the|heyth of perfyte mekenes, the whiche wyll bringe vs to|the honour of heuen in body and soule, lete vs lyft vp our|herte &amp; mynde vnto heuen by &thorn;e skale and lader of Iacob,|descendyng wyth the angels from ony exaltacyon / and|clymme vp to theym by mekenes &amp; humyliacion.  The|fyrste steppe of thys ladder ascendyng by mekenes to|heuen / is to be euer aferde of god and of your souereyn /|and not to be foryetful / beringe in your mynde surely all|thynges that god hath commaundyd you to be done, and|your rule, and how they &thorn;at contempnyth god &amp; hys preceptes|or the rule shal goo to hell / and to theim that loue|&amp; drede god &amp; kepith his commaundementes is ordeyned| Ioye euerlastyng.  Oure <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa vja">lorde in euery place beholdyth|the dedes &amp; thoughtes of euery creature / and &thorn;e angels|ben redy to shewe to the trynitee dayly the gode dedes of|eche good creature.  &para; The seconde steppe or<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>, Caxton: <I>of</I>.</NOTE> degree of|thys ladder of mekenesse is whan one hath no delyte to|fulfyll theyr owne wyll or desire / but oonli<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>butoonli</I>.</NOTE> to folow crist /|&thorn;at seith: "I come not in-to the worlde to doo myn owne|wyll but the wyll of my fader that sent me."  The iij.|degree is whan one subdewyth &amp; mekyth hymselfe for god|lowly to their souereyn / folowynge crist / of whom the|apostyll seyth / "Ihesus was made obedient vnto deth of|the crosse."  &para; The iiij. degree is whan one can suffre wyth
<PB N="125">|all obedience &amp; pacyence all Iniuries, wronges / wordes of|rebuke, &amp; suche other done or sayd vnto theim / &amp; to take|hem gladly for goddis sake their lyfe enduring / For &thorn;e|gospel seith / "he &thorn;at contynueth to the ende / shall be|sauff."  The v. steppe of this ladder of mekenes is &thorn;at|whan al euyll thoughtes that come vnto their herte or to|their mynde, &amp; their synnes a-fore hid &amp; not confessyd /|&thorn;at they wyll thenne open mekely to theyr souereyn wyth|repentaunce / For it is writen / "shewe <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa vjb">thy wayes of thy |lyuyng to our lord &amp; trust in hym &amp; in his mercy.  for|he is al goodnesse &amp; piteful / &amp; redy is to foryeue thy|trespace &amp; synne, yf thou wyll knowleche it wyth repentaunce|&amp; amende."  &para; The vj. degre of mekenes is whan|one is well content wyth symple araye or habite / &amp; is|glad to be set lytill by &amp; to be take as a drudge or outcast|of the religion / &amp; to be euer redy to doo al thynges that|is boden hym to doo, Iugyng him an Idyll seruaunt and|vnworthy to god and man / &para; The vij. degree is yf he|shew in dede hymself, not oonly with tongue but also|wyth all the inwardes of his herte &amp; by outwarde behauour,|the lothliest &amp; the vilest of all other / seyeng wyth|the prophete / "I am a worme &amp; noo man, the repreef of|peple &amp; abieccion / lord, I thanke the that &thorn;ou hast mekid|me, so that I may the beter lerne thy commaundementes."|&para; The viij: degree is yf that he doo no thynge but as the|commyn rule of the place and holy ensample of his senyours|doo shewe vnto him in our lorde / &para; The ix. degree|is yf one kepe his tongue in al silence to the tyme he be|commaundid to speke / or els that he be askid a questyon.|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa vija">&para; The x. degree is yf one be not lyght and redy to |laughter or to dissolucyon.  It is writen: "a fole wylle|exalte his voyce in laughter."  &para; The enleuenth is for to|speke euer softely wyth sadnes / &amp; mekely &amp; with fewe|wordes groundid vpon reason and godly / It is wryten:|"The wyse man is knowen by hys wordes."  &para; The xij.|degree is whan one, not oonly in his mowthe but aswell in|his body, shewyth meknesse to all that beholde hym / as|in al his dedes / in chaptour / in chirche, in garden /|in felde, sittynge, walkynge, or standynge, &amp; his hede|enclynynge / and his sight to the grounde, shewynge hym
<PB N="126">|selfe euery houre gylty of hys synne, hauynge euer suspect|for to be brought to the ferefull Iugement of god, seyeng|thus wyth the publycan: "Good lorde, I a synner am not|worthy to lyfte vp myn eyen to heuen."  who som euer|hath ascendyd al thise degrees of mekenesse shall anone|haue the charyte of god perfitely, &thorn;e whyche thenne|puttyth awaye all drede in suche thynges / the whyche he|dyde afore with drede / and also dooth thenne al his actes| of accustome, as it were naturalle to <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa vijb">hym, cherefully /|&amp; wythoute labour, &amp; that not for the drede of hell he|dooth it, but for feruent loue &thorn;at he hath to god by a|custome &amp; delyte of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>of</I> (end of line) <I>of vertue</I>.</NOTE> vertue / &thorn;e whyche grace is yeuen of|&thorn;e holy gooste.</P>
<P>How the seruyse of god is to be doone at his|howres acordyng to the tyme / is shewid in the|hole rule distynctly by chaptours, where it is noted in &thorn;e|ende &thorn;at euery weke, begynnynge on the sonday, shal be|songe the hole sawter of dauid wyth anthemes &amp; other|appropryed therfore / &amp; finally it is so of vs to doo in|regarde of holy faders afore tyme, &thorn;at dide deuoutly rendre|&amp; say euery daye of the yer &thorn;e seyde hole sawter, as we|rede.</P>
<P>Sith it is so that our bileue is, that god is presente in|euery place &amp; beholdyth at eche howre both the|gode &amp; the euyll / thenne it is to truste wythoute ony|dowte / &thorn;at moche more whan we be occupied in his|seruyce in &thorn;e chirche or ony other holy place / wherfore|he is to be serued in drede by the counseyle of the prophete|/ &amp; wysely remembring his presence with innumerable| angels / the whyche ben theyr surely at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa viija">dyuyne|seruyce / and lete vs euer soo syng and saye that our|mynde accorde to our voys and the sentence / of the|dyttee.  Amen.</P>
<P>Yf we shulde make ony suggestion to a state|temporall / we wolde not presume to doo it|but with mekenes &amp; reuerence / thenne how moche more|owe we to oure lorde god wyth all mekenes and clennesse
<PB N="127">|deuoutly to make our prayer and supplicacion, &amp; that not|in haste and moche seyenge, but in clennesse of the herte|&amp; compunccion wyth wepyng / &thorn;at we may the rather be|herde in our prayer &amp; petycion.</P>
<P>Of the eleccyon of the deanes &amp; offycers of the|religyon and of theyr good lyfe / &amp; of their|charges / by the whyche the souereyn maye in partie be|discharged, And how they owe to be chosen for theyr|good lyfe / theyr lernynge and wysdom / And how they|shal be correct and blamed / and also depryued, if thei|amende not after theyr defawte / And how that other|better disposyd shall occupye their place, and soo other|offices / and also in what maner they shall slepe in their|clothes gyrde; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="aa viijb">And how offenses and sinnes, grete &amp; |lesse dyuersly, owen to be corrected / And how &thorn;e|souereyn owe to be dilygent aboute suche as a goode leche|or phisicien in all charite &amp; prayer; And also how they|that oft haue ben corrupt &amp; correcte wyll not amende by|noo punysshement reguler, that prayer to god &amp; good|exhortacyon is thenne euer to be had vnto theim; Yf|they wyll not dispose theim so to be reconsiled &amp; to|take grace, how that thenne they shall departe from the|congregacyon, leest that suche a moreyne shepe / empoysen|and enfecte the residue of &thorn;e flocke; And also how those|&thorn;at ones by their owne foly goone out of the religyon ben|receyued ayen; And how childern nouyces arn to be|chastised: al thys afore wryten ben ordeyned afore by|saynte benet in &thorn;e complete rule in seuerall chapitours|full heuenly.</P>
<P>The cellerer of the place is to be chosen of the congregacyon,|suche one that is wyse, quicke, well|condycyoned, &amp; sobre, not prowde, impacient, not trowbelous,|ferefull, nor large / but euer dredynge god / beyng|as a fader or a louyng moder to al &thorn;e congregacion.|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb ja">&para; They must haue grete laboure &amp; thought for all theim / |doyng noo thyng wythout &thorn;e commaundement of the|souereyn / the whiche agreyng to god and the rule is euer|to be kept / soo that they cause not ony of the couent to
<PB N="128">|grutche or be heuy / Yf cace be that ony aske a thynge|vnresonable / yet they owe not to dysdeyne suche one or|dispyse, makyng theim heuy with theyr countenaunce or|answere / but reasonably wyth all mekenes and cheyrfull|countenaunce in softnes of spiritte denie their petycion.|This sayd charge is dredefull and also meritorious; for|the apostle seyth:  "He or she that mynystrith wel / shal|haue grete rewarde &amp; crowned in heuen."  Morouer theyr|charge is to see diligently and well to the seke / and to|Infauntes, to strangers and to power peple / Remembring|that wythout doubte / &thorn;at they shall yeue a streyt rekenyng|and accompte for all theys / and for the leest thyng|in theyr office myskepte or myspendid, atte ferefull daye|of dome / All the vesels of &thorn;e place they owe to kepe|well / in that aswell as though thei were the sacrate| vesels of the awter / Noo thynge they shulde doo neclygently<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb jb">|/ or to be couetous or ouerlarge or prodigous / but|all thynges to doo mesurably wyth discrecyon &amp; after the|commaundement of the souereyn / And specially in thys|offyce thei must haue mekenesse / &amp; whan they haue not|the thyng that is askyd of theym / thenne at leest to yeue|an esy &amp; gentill answer / For it is writen: a soft &amp; esy|answere is a-boue ony yeft.  The refresshynge and fode|that is to be yeuen to the couent or congregacyon is to be|done euer without grutchyng or taryeng, so that thei haue|noo cause to compleyne for<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>compleynefor</I>.</NOTE> the minystracyon / All thynges|is to be askyd in dew houres / soo that none be trowbled|or made pensy in the housholde of our lorde.</P>
<P>For the other stuff of the monestary, and vesture of|the couent wyth other necessaryes / &thorn;e souereyn|owe to prouide suche officers of whos lyf &amp; good maners|he and other may be sure, for the kepyng therof &amp; gaderyng|of the same / and for delyueryng of hem to theym|&thorn;at haue nede / Of the whiche stuff the souereyn shall|haue wrytynge / wherby he maye delyuer the percels to| the offycers as they chaunge / so &thorn;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb ija">it maye be well|knowen what is yeuen and what is receyued / Who so
<PB N="129">|euer neclygently or sluttisshly entretyth ony thyng of the|place / anone be they rebukyd &amp; punysshid /</P>
<P>The grete vice &amp; syn of properte in relygyon is|namely to be cutte awaye by &thorn;e rote / Presume|none in relygyon to yeue ony thyng, or to take, wythout|the wyll &amp; commaundement of the souereyn / nor it is|leefull ony to haue a thyng to theyrself propre / not as|moche as their owne body / or to haue their own wyll in|their power / All thynges to theim necessary is to be had|of the souereyn accordynge to theyr nede, not acceptynge|ony persone more than an other, but accordyng to nede &amp;|in-firmyte / And all thynges must be commyn emonge|theym accordyng to the lyfe of &thorn;e apostles / None presume|to sey: suche a thynge is myne.  Yf ony be founde|gylty in this venemouse offence of properte / lete hem|twyes or thries be correct / yf they doo not amende / see|thenne to<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>to</I> (end of line) <I>to their chatysment</I>.</NOTE> their cha[s]tysment / Yf at ony tyme one nede a|lytyll thyng / thanke he our lorde and say he euer: "Deo|gracias," not beyng sory that another<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb ijb"> that nede hath / |that pite is shewid vppon hym / And he that hath suche|pite shewyd vpon hym shal not therof be proude by contenaunce|or by worde / and thus shall all the congregacyon|be in rest and charitee / and grutchynge layd a syde / the|whiche is perilous to be had eyther by worde or sygne /|Yf ony therin be founde culpable, anone put theim to streyt|disciplyne.</P>
<P>Eche one be besy to serue other, &amp; none is to be|exscusid from &thorn;e dressing bord of &thorn;e kechyn /|wythout they be seke or other wyse occupyed for &thorn;e|commyn well.  In suche meke &amp; low seruice is goten|grete mede / charite and rewarde / and whan they shall|departe wekely from the kechyn by cours / they owe to|make al thynges clene at theyr departyng / and &thorn;e clothes|&thorn;at the couent hath fyled with theyr handes or fete they|shall delyuer clene also wyth all mekenes.  And moreouer|theyr owne fete they shall make clene in theyr departyng,|and delyuer al the naprye and clene clothes to the celerer.
<PB N="130">|Suche seruytoures by &thorn;e rule may take a lytyll refresshing|of mete &amp; drynke afore high dyner / for by-cause of their|attendaunce &amp; seruyse at &thorn;e same.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb iija">Grete attendaunce is to be had aboute seke persones|aboue all other thynges: as though it were to|criste hymselfe / the whiche doutlesse is seruyd in theym|that is seke / as he seyth hymselfe:  "I was seke and ye|visited me, and that ye dide vnto the leest of theym that|were seke, ye dide it vnto me" / Wherfore those that|ben seke shulde considre that suche seruyce is doon to|theym for the loue &amp; honour of god, and therfore they|shulde be righte ware to cause ony heuynese to theyr|seruytoures by ony superfluite or vncurtees demenour.|Not for thy, for theyr sekenes they owe pacyently to be|suffred / for of suche is goten<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>goton</I>.</NOTE> grete rewarde herafter in|heuen.  The souereyn may not be neclygent to the ouersyght|of suche seke persones, serchyng wel that thei lacke|noo helpe or comforte / or ony thing that is necessary for|theim, as is wasshing, bathynge, and medicynes, yeuyng|as oft as nedeth / and to suche is grauntid by the rule for|theyr sooner amendement for to ete flesshe; so &thorn;at after|thei recouer thei absteyn in ony wyse therfro.  Prouyde|alwey &thorn;at fauour be had to Infantes / seke persones &amp;|aged.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb iijb">At all refeccyons and meles / redyng &amp; lecture|must be had / And the reder after the masse on|the sonday shall entre / and humbly desire of all the congregacyon|to pray for hym, makynge a crosse in his forhede /|for the euyll spirite of pryde and other / and after the blessyng|yeuen begyn to rede / and all the tyme of refeccyon|or meles / none to be soo hardy to speke / but to kepe|high silence as speche, noys, or other wyse, preuy or aperte /|how be it, the souereyn maye a lytyll speke of the|processe that is rad or of other for edefieng of his ghestes|or of other that here hym / and not els<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>cls</I>.</NOTE> / Also &thorn;e congregacion|shal be seruyd of al thynges necessary to theym at|that tyme / so that none haue nede to aske ony thynge /
<PB N="131">|Yf cace be &thorn;at suche nede befall / thenne signes must be|vsid and no speche / The reder may afore his lecture take|a lytyll refeccyon that is callyd mixtum / yf nede be for|by-cause of his redyng atte mete / And suche owe to|rede euer / the whiche by theyr redyng may best edyfye|the herers / And the same is to be obseruyd in all syngyng|and redynge in the chirche or in prechyng / and that|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb iva">to be done in mekenes / sadnesse and drede. </P>
<P>It folowyth in the rule of the mesures of mete and|drynke / and what howres after the season and|tyme of the yere / the congregacyon shall take theyr|repast and meles / And also how the souereyn must soo|tempre and dispose all suche thynges wyth other, so that|the soules of his subgettes may be saaf.</P>
<P>To the seruyce of god as sone as is herde ony bell|or token / all thynges set aside, the couent owe to|come in all godely haste and relygyously therto / For|noo thynge owe to be preferryd before the seruyce of|god.  And they that come late therto / shal not goo to|their owne place in &thorn;e quere / but to the place assigned|for suche late commers / to theyr rebuke, penaunce, and|amendement.  How they shall be punysshid that come|late to meles / and of theyr sequestracyon from the|feliship / and of theyr etynge alone in penaunce after|other / the rule with<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>, Caxton: <I>whiche</I>.</NOTE> his expositour dooth specifye /</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb ivb">Tho that fayle in psalmody / respons / anthemes or |lessons, yf they meke not theyr-selfe openly afore|all the congregacion / as puttynge theyr hede downe to|the grounde or other wyse by the rule for a satysfacyon /|els they must haue afterwarde more largelier &amp; greter|penaunce for their offence / And children euer for theyr|trespace must be bette.</P>
<P>Who that euer in his laboures / as in the kechyn,|in celary / in the gardyn, or in ony other|occupacyon, offendyth or brekyth ony thyng / or els
<PB N="132">|lesith, and wyll not knowleche his offence to the hede|and souereyn or to the congregacyon / they owe to|haue grete penaunce, yf it be openly knowen, the offence /|yf it be not knowen but oonly to hym selfe / thenne|lete hym shew it bi confessyon to the souereyn or to his|goostly fader and take his penaunce.</P>
<P>Idilnesse is the enmye of &thorn;e soule / wherfore lyke as|the couent ben occupyed certeyn howres aboute|the seruyce of god / soo certeyn other howres ben thei|occupyed in redyng and studyeng of heuenly thynges /| and in laboures<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb va"> wyth theyr body in thynges that is|good and necessary to theim or &thorn;e place / for thenne thei|ben very religious, whan thei thus folowe holy faders and|doon as the apostles dyden.</P>
<P>In the tyme of lent echon by theyr-selfe haue the|bible / the whiche they owe to rede complete and|hole besyde theyr seruyse / and the seyde bible is to be|delyuerd vnto theym atte begynnynge of lent.  And the|serchers of the relygyon owe to see warely about &thorn;at they|be occupyed in lecture therof sonday and other / &amp; not|aboute fables / Iapes or sluggisshenes.  Yf ony suche be|founde / see that they be spoken vnto sharply ones|or twyes / &amp; yf they amende not theyr-wyth / lete|theym be correct / soo that all other maye beware by|theym.  If theyr be ony so slouthfull or neclygent, that|they maye not or wyll not be occupied in redyng or|holy medytacyon / thenne lete theym be assigned to|other occupacyons to doo / so that they be neuer vnoccupied|in vertu / If they be seke or feble for age /|thenne such an occupacyon is to be put vnto theym|&thorn;at they maye awaye wyth / &amp; not to be ydyll, by &thorn;e|discrecion of the souereyn.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb vb">How be it that a relygious<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>relygions</I>.</NOTE> persone owe euery|tyme to kepe lent / yet for by-cause that fewe|haue thys vertu / therfore we aduise and counseyll, seyth|saynt benet, all of the relygyon spiritually theys xl. dayes|of lent to kepe in all clennesse of lyfe / and to put vtterly
<PB N="133">|awaye all theyr neclygences and olde custome of synne /|and thenne more spiritually to gyue theim to prayer|waylyng and wepinge<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>wepnige</I>.</NOTE> / redinge / and abstinence in|mete and drynke / wythdrawynge somwhat of theyr|takynge in mete and drynke other wyse than they dide|afore, and that wyth good wyll, offerynge it in his mynde|to god and to the poore peple; And to wythdrawe some|what of slepe and speche and wanton behauour.  And as|for abstynence of mete and drynke, it owe to be doon|wyth the consente euer of the souereyn and the helpe of|prayer.  For yf it be otherwyse doon / it is to be taken|of presumpcyon and vayne glory / and thenne it hath noo|mede.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb vja">Noo thynge is to be spoken in the chirche but |prayer / And after that ony seruyce is there|doon / all they owe to departe wyth silence and lowe|reuerence doon to god.  Yf ony after woll praye of deuocyon|/ none shall let hym by theyr noyse or ony other|vncurteys delynge / and thenne suche owe secretly to|praye wyth deuocyon and not on high, but wepynge for|his synnes and the Ignoraunce of the peple and theyr|synnes wyth all meke intencyon of herte and soule.  All|other not soo there occupyed owe to avoyde.</P>
<P>Al strangers or ghestes arn to be receyued for god|&amp; as god.  For here-after they shal here hym|saye to theim / "I was a stranger &amp; ye toke me In / and|gaue me mete &amp; drynke and lodgynge" / and soo of other|dedes of mercy / Euery persone is to be honourid for the|ymage of god / thenne moche more those that ben of|cristen religion and that commen for god / Whan euer it|is shewyd that a stranger is come / anone the souereyn or|his bredern shulde <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb vjb">quykly goo to hym wyth all charyte / |and after theyr prayer togider made and knyt togider in|goddis peas / kissyng togyder and salutyng other / with after|refresshing theim with mete and drynk and other necessaryes|to their power / redynge amonge the lawes of god|to theyr edyfieng of soule / The souereyn may breke his
<PB N="134">|mele for a stranger, wythout it be a spirituell fastynge|daye / and thenne he owe not to breke it / The bredern|may not breke ony faste for strangers.  Also the souereyn|wyth the congregacion shulde with all mekenes|folow oure lorde / and wasshe the fete of the strangers,|sayenge certeyn prayers / for in theim and poore folke is|to be had diligent watche and cure / for crist in theym is|surely receyued / He &thorn;at is asygned for suche gestes or|poore folke, to gyue vnto theim necessaries, shulde drede|god gretly and haue mekenes and pacience / and doo all|thynges with wisdom / and silence, euer fulfillyng the|souereyns commaundement / &amp; whan they ony other mete|or see / they owe to enclyne mekely and salute theim|departyng with silence.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb vija">Noo wyse be it leefull to ony broder to take or|receyue of fader or moder ony letters, tokens,|or yeftes / or els to sende hymself or to yeue ony without|the wyll and comaundement of his hede and souereyn /|the whiche had, he thenne maye receiue theim / not forthy|the souereyn after may yeue suche stuff to suche as it|shall please hym, and he that it was sent vnto shall take|it in worthe &amp; cherefully / in that an other hath it /<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it /</I>, Caxton:<I> / it</I>.</NOTE> leest|that occasion of grutchinge inwarde or outwarde be yeuen|to the by thy goostly enmye.</P>
<P>Clothynge to the couent, and habyte, is to be yeuen|accordyng to the hete of the yere or to the coldenes|of the countre that they dwell in, lasse or more as|nede is / And the souereyn must haue consideracion therof|/ and to bye suche cloth that is made in that countre or|prouynce, of the vilest and lyghtest pryce / And as oft as|they shal take new / thenne to rendre vp the olde for the|vse of pore peple / Of other thynges necessary for theyr|body daye &amp; nyght in wynter and somer, and of theyr|celles and lodgyng, and of their behauour in theim with|other / the hole rule certifieth.  And how the souereyne| shal dyligently serche that thei lacke no <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb vijb">thyng to theym|necessary / soo that all occasion of grutchyng, or for ony
<PB N="135">|thynge werkynge, or for ony thynge kepyng / haue no|place in &thorn;e relygyon / euer remembryng the wordes|wrytyn in the actes of the apostles, where it is seyde /|that it was distribute &amp; delyuerd to echone of theym as|theyr nede required.</P>
<P>The borde or table of the souereyn is to be garnysshid|wyth pilgrymes or ghestes / And whan there|ben few strangers / the soouereyn maye call vnto hym|some of the brederen / so that parte of the senyours be|left wyth the couent for theyr awe and disciplyne.</P>
<P>Whan ony commyth from the worlde to entre|in-to religion / a light or soden entree is not|to be grauntyd; but for to doo after the apostle, preuynge|the spirites / yf they be of god.  Yf cace be that suche|one be abydynge in hys purpose / and founde pacyent for|ony Iniuryes done vnto hym / or for delayeng of his|entree, &amp; suche other, thenne after iiij or v. dayes may|be graunted vnto hym entree / abidyng after by <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb viija">certeyn |space in the ghestys chambre / and after in the cell for|nouices / theyr to be for a tyme in prayer and medytacyon|/ and for to ete and drynke.  And a senyoure of|the relygyon is to be assigned vnto hym / the whyche is|apt to gete sowles to god / the whyche shall see vnto hym|warely and vysely that he be vertuously occupyed / sekynge|our lorde by prayer, and to folow hym by obedyence|and suffryng of repreues / All the hardnesse and sharpnesse|of the ordre is to be tolde hym playnly / by the whiche he|must goo to heuen.  And yf he promyse to contynwe and|to be stable in his purpoos, thenne after two monethes /|the rule shall be red hole by ordre vnto hym / and thus it|shall be seyde vnto hym:  "Beholde here the lawe vndyr|whyche thou must sore laboure and fyght / Yf thou|thynkyst that thou maye kepe it, come in / and yf thou|may not / goo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>/ goo</I>, Caxton: <I>goo /</I>.</NOTE> free ayen where it plesith &thorn;e."  Yf he yet|contynewe by hys promyse, thenne he shall be brought|ayen to the nouyces cell to be preued ayen, and yet ayen
<PB N="136">| after in all pacience; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="bb viijb">&amp; thenne after six monethes the|rule ayen shall be red vnto hym / soo that he may well|know wherfore he entryth in-to relygyon / and yf he contynue|styll iiij. mounthes after / yet not for thy &thorn;e rule|ayen shall be red vnto hym / And yf he promyse thenne|vtterly to kepe all thynges that is so ofte red vnto hym|and to be obedient, thenne atte firste shall he be taken|in-to the congregacyon / knowlechyng thenne that he is|bounde to the law of the rule / and thenne after he may|not departe from<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>from</I>, Caxton: <I>f&omacr;r</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e monestarye / nor exscuse him, but|that he is vnder the yocke of &thorn;e seyd rule to his deth.|&para; Thenne whan he is admyttid and taken in-to the chirche|to be professid afore all the peple / there he shall promytte|of his stabylnesse and amendyng of his maners / &amp;|there-vpon make his obedience afore god and his sayntes /|the whiche is to be done with all his mynde and herte,|leest that he mocke our lorde god to his dampnacyon / Of|his promyse and profession he shall make a peticyon in|writynge to god and to all sayntes / whos relykes ben in|that chirche and to the souereyn assygned therto / the| whiche he shal wryte with <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="cc ja">his owne hande / or els an|other of hym required, yf that he can not write / &amp; marke|it with his owne sygne / the whiche he shall put vpon &thorn;e|awter afterwarde wyth his hande; &amp; seye certayn prayers|ther-wyth / And after this he shal fall downe prostrate at|fete of the couent / prayeng theym to praye for hym / and|after thys he shall be nombrid for euer / and named for|one of the congregacyon / Suche stuff that he hath not|yeuen before to folke &thorn;at ben poore or other wyse, openly|shall he thenne yeue to the monestary / noo thyng reseruyng|vnto hym-selfe; for after that tyme he may haue noo|propirte / not as moche as his owne body / And whan in|&thorn;e chirche he shall doo of his seculer arraye and be cladde|with the habite of the place / those that he puttyth of|shall be kept in the vestuary / leest that the enmye the|fende perswade and cause hym after / the whiche god|defende, for to departe from the religion / and thenne he|must haue his seculer clothes ayen / and put out for euer.|But his petycyon in wrytinge, that he put on the awter in
<PB N="137">|his firste entree / ought euer to remayn and to be kept in|the monestary.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="cc jb">Yf a man of worship offre a yong childe, his sone, |to god and to the religion, thenne shall he or his|frendes make the peticion, as is<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>as it</I>, for <I>as is</I>, or <I>as it is</I>.</NOTE> wryten afore, for him|with writyng / and their offryng wyth the hande of &thorn;e|childe / the whiche shall be rollyd togider in the pall or in|the towell of the awter / How poore children and seculer|prestes / &amp; how mounkes strangers owe to be receyued /|and of the ordynacion of prestes &amp; of dekens wythin &thorn;e|selfe religion, is shewid folowyngly in the complete rule by|large processe / the whiche I passe ouer for the grete|change that is in that religion, and the length.</P>
<P>Whan euer the bredern mete togider / the yonger|shall meke hymselfe / desirynge the blessynge|of hys senyour / And whan ony senyour commyth at ony|tyme before hym / he shal arise and gyue place to sytte;|and the sayd Ionger shall stande tyll he be commande to|sitte.  Yonge children of the religion both in chirche and|at table &amp; elswhere shall kepe theyr place after their age|in relygion / and they shal haue ouerseers, techinge theym|&amp; gyuynge disciplyne / tyll they come to the age of|vnderstondyng.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="cc ija">To the gate of the monestary an aged persone, wise |and well manerd, is to be assigned / the whiche|can take an answere wittely or a message / Whose good|disposicyon woll not suffre hym to wandre aboute or to|be idle / The whiche broder owe to lodge nygh the gate /|soo that strangers that come maye euer fynde hym redy /|of whom they shall take an answere. / And whan someuer|ony knockyth at gate, or els that the poore peple crye,|anone he shall seye:  "Deo gracias" cherefully, and gyue|theym an awnswere comfortably in all mekenes and softnesse|and drede of god / The whiche broder portar shall|haue helpe of an other yonger broder, yf grete nede requyre.|Suche a monestary is to be sette in suche a place where all
<PB N="138">|thynges necessary soone maye be had / so that the couent|nede not to passe the boundes of the clausures therof / the|whiche yf thei dide / shulde be perylle for theyr soules /|Saynt benet woll that the rule be red effectuelly oftymes|in the yere afore the congregacion / for by-cause none of|hem shal pretende Ignorance or ony exscuse.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="cc ijb">Whan ony of the bredern must doo a Iourney|without the clausure of the place, after licence|had, he shall commende hym to the prayer of his souereyn /|and euer at last oryson in the seruyse of god / shal a prayer|be sayd for him and all &thorn;at is absent / And the daye that|they come home ayen / they shal lye prostrate all the|seruyse tyme / &amp; desyre the couent to praye for theym for|theyr excesses done in the iourney / as in syght, heryng|of ony vanytees / or euyll thynges, or ony voyde wordes /|And they shall not tell ony thyng &thorn;at they sawe or herd|in theyr iourney, for it is a grete meane to &thorn;e destruccion|of suche a place of relygion / And he that presumyth to|doo the contrary or to goo oute of the clausure of the|monestary to ony place / thought it be neuer so lytil,|wythout commandement or licence of the souereyn / owe|to be streytly punysshyd.</P>
<P>If ony greuouse or impossible thynges be put vnto|a broder<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>abroder</I>.</NOTE> of his souereyn to doo / he shall wyth all|mekenesse and obedience take the commaundement vpon|hym:  Yf cace be that it passe his power in ony wise to|fulfill it, thenne wyth all lowlynesse he shal tell it to| <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="cc iija">his souereyn / and the cause of impossibilytee.  And yf|cace be the souereyn contynew in his sentence &amp; wyll /|thenne the broder owe to know that it is to hym right|profitable yet to obeye, puttynge his trust in the helpe|of god / whiche woll not forsake all theym that truste|in him.</P>
<P>Eche one shuld beware &thorn;at he exscuse not or|defende an other in ony cause, though al he were|neuer soo nygh to hym of blode / For of it lightly wolde
<PB N="139">|growe grete occasion of sclaundre to the religion / Who|&thorn;at is founde fawty in this trespace owe to be punysshid|greuosly.</P>
<P>It is ordeyned also that it is not lefull to ony of the|couent to punisshe or to bete an other of the|same / but suche one as the souereyn hath yeuen power|vnto / Those that offende openly / must be repreuyd and|punysshid openly / that other maye be the rather aferd to|offende / Children to the xv. yere of age shall stande euer|vndir streyt awe and diligent discipline / &amp; all thynges er|to be doon vnto theym mesurably with discrecyon and|reason / &amp; vndir the commandement euer of the souereyn /|And he that otherwise dooth / shall be correct wyth|<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="cc iijb">reguler disciplyne / for it his writen in the gospell / All |thynges that ye wolde &thorn;at other shuld doo vnto you / doo|ye it to theym / and that ye wolde not haue done to you /|doo it not to theim.</P>
<P>Obedience is not oonly to be yeuen of al the couent|to the souereyn / but also echon to other must|obeye / knowyng that by &thorn;e way of obedience thei shall|come vnto heuen.  Whan the commaundement of the|souereyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Caxton: <I>soueuereyn</I>.</NOTE> is doon by the subgette / saynt Benet woll|that besyde that / &thorn;at euer the yonger in religion obeye|theyr senyours in all charite / dilygence, &amp; mekenesse;|who &thorn;at woll not must be correct / Yf ony brother be|blamed of his souereyn for ony cause / though it be right|small / as soone as that he knowyth that his souereyn or|his senyour is greued wyth hym or trowbled, though it be|right lityll / anone he owe to fall downe prosstrate at his|fete / so longe to the tyme he that is greued be satisfied &amp;|plesid for his humyliacyon.  Yf ony disdeyn to doo thys /|lete hym be punysshid on the nakyd body / and yf he be|obstynate / put hym out of the monestary.</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="cc iva">As there is an euyll &yogh;ele / loue, or affeccyon / the |whiche departyth one from god and bringith|hym to hell / soo there is a &yogh;ele or affeccion the whiche
<PB N="140">|departyth one from synne and bryngith hym to god to|euerlastyng lyfe, the whiche is to be had in religion in all|feruent desire / for by it echone gladly woll reuerence|other, and echone suffre other for ony infirmytee or condycions|/ and that wyth all pacience / and moreouer|echone be glad who can best meke hymselfe and to be|obedient / neuer folowyng that thyng the whiche he|demeth to be profitable oonly to hymselfe / but moche|more that thyng that is profitable for other.  Echone|shewe charitee to other as brethern in all clene &amp; chaste|loue / dredyng euer god / and louynge theyr souereyn in|charyte vnfeyned, preferryng euer goddis cause and mater|afore all other / the whiche woll brynge hem all to-gider to|reygne in the lyfe / the whiche is eternalle.  AMEN.</P>
<TRAILER>Explicit.</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>&para; Of your charite praye for the translatour of thys|sayd treatyse.</TRAILER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="text">
<PB N="141">
<HEAD>IV. THE NORTHERN LANSDOWNE RITUAL|FOR THE|Ordination of Nuns.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(Lansdowne MS. 378, British Museum.)</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="43a">This is &thorn;e furme how A Nouice sall be made &amp; |resaiuid to religiun.</P>
<P>In &thorn;e first begining, when sho hase made hir peticiun,|And askid &thorn;e howse, &amp; priores and &thorn;e Couent hase|graunt hir it, &thorn;an sall sho cume to &thorn;e priores and knele|downe be-fore hir on hir kneis.  And &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>e</SUP>.</NOTE> priores schall|take hyr hende in hirs and kisse hir, and sho sall be|resauid.</P>
<P>Efterwarde, when &thorn;ai likis to bringe hir to &thorn;e|chaypitur for to be examend, &thorn;ai sall aray hir in|&thorn;at wede &thorn;at sho sall vse &thorn;e first &yogh;ere to sho be profest.|And &thorn;an, when chaipitur is done, sho &thorn;at sall be hir|maistres sall say to &thorn;e priores: "&thorn;are is a Nouice for to|be examend."</P>
<P>And &thorn;an [&thorn;e] priores<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;an priores</I>.</NOTE> sall byd bring hir in.  And hir|maistres sall bring hir in.  And when sho comes whare &thorn;e|cuuent takis &thorn;are venyse, &thorn;an sall sho prostrate downe.|And &thorn;an &thorn;e priores sall aske hir: "dere doughtir, what is|&thorn;i asking?"  And ligand still, sho sall say:  "&thorn;e mercy of|god and &yogh;oures."  And &thorn;e priores sall garre hir rise, and|say tyll hir on &thorn;is wyse: "What is &thorn;at mercy &thorn;at &thorn;u<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>u</SUP>; similarly p. 142, l. 12.</NOTE>|askes?" and sho sall say: "for to dwelle in &thorn;is <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="43b">place |in &thorn;e abet of religiun to serue godde, &amp; for to punysce|my sinnis, &amp; for amendment of my life, &amp; finally for|saluacion<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>finally of saluacion</I>.</NOTE> of my saule."  And &thorn;an &thorn;e priores sall say|a-gayn: "Dere doghtir, &thorn;is thing &thorn;at &thorn;u askis is a harde|thing &amp; a strate.  Neuir-&thorn;eles, to &thorn;am &thorn;at [god] inspires<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at inspires</I>.</NOTE> &amp;
<PB N="142">|giffis grace, will, and power to fulfil it, &amp; standis stabill|in-to &thorn;e purpose &thorn;at &thorn;a be-gane, it is bott light, meritory,|&amp; medefull, &amp; spedand to &thorn;e lif &thorn;at euir sall last.  Bott|at &thorn;e begining of &thorn;is spiritual life, thre thyngis &thorn;ar ar &thorn;at|&thorn;e behuvis: to forsake &thorn;ine awne propir will, &amp; liffe vndir|obedience, &amp; be obediant principally to &thorn;i priores &amp; to &thorn;i|elders in &thorn;e ordir In all lefull &thorn;ingis &amp; honeste.  The|secunde is, &thorn;at &thorn;e behouis liue in wilfull power[te],<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>power</I>.</NOTE> na thing|awand with-owtyn wittyng of &thorn;i priores, na nathing take|of nane of &thorn;i frendis, golde ne siluir, no na other gifte, bot|at &thorn;i priores se it, And &thorn;at it fully be disposid at hir will,|&thorn;at &thorn;u be noght propirtarij and falle in owre-hegh daunger|enence &thorn;i religiun.  For wha sa euir hase ani thing, golde,| siluir, iuel, or ony propirte, with-outen <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="44a">&thorn;e witting &amp;|sufferans of hir priores, sho standis curste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>siluir or ony iuel with|outen &thorn;e witting &amp; sufferans of hir priores propirte sho standis|curste</I>.  In a prior copy of the ritual, the word <I>propirte</I> was|probably written in the margin.  The scribe entered it in the|wrong place, also putting <I>or ony</I> before <I>iuel</I> (jewel).</NOTE>  The thirde is,|&thorn;at &thorn;e behouis to liue chaiste, and take god to &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>i</SUP>.</NOTE> spouse,|and forsake all &thorn;i lust, &amp; &thorn;i liking of &thorn;i flesche; &thorn;e behouis|to giue &thorn;e to abstinens &amp; faste, when o&thorn;ir men etis;|&thorn;e behouis to rise to &thorn;e seruise of godde, when o&thorn;ir men|slepis; &thorn;e be-houis gife &thorn;e to praier &amp; deuocion for to|purches grace, and stifly stande<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>stifly and stande</I>.</NOTE> in &thorn;e purpose &thorn;at &thorn;u takis|&thorn;e to.  And dohtir, giue &thorn;u seis &thorn;at &thorn;u mai fulfill with|&thorn;e grace of god all &thorn;eis poyntes &thorn;at I haue reherced, Sais|now her be-fore &thorn;e cuuent: what is &thorn;i wille?"  And &thorn;an|&thorn;e nouyce, if sho will abide in hir purpose, sall say on &thorn;is|wise: "The gude purpose &thorn;at I haue tane, I sall fulfill it|to my liuis ende thrugh &thorn;e grace of god and &yogh;ure gude|informaciun."  And &thorn;an &thorn;e priores sal say tyl hir: "Dere|doghtir, godd of his grete grace, he giue &thorn;e gude perseuerans.|Ga with &thorn;i maistres in &thorn;e name of crist."  And hir|mastres sall haue hir to &thorn;e Nouycery, &amp; infurme as religiun|will.  And when twa monethes er passid, hir maistres| salle <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="44b">expone hir &thorn;e rewle and all &thorn;e poyntis and stratenes|of religiun, na thing lanande fra hir.  And when hir|maistres hase exponed hir &thorn;e rewle, sho sall be examned
<PB N="143">|a-gain in &thorn;e chaipitur on &thorn;e same wise os es be-fore saide.|And giffe sho standis in hir purpose eftir &thorn;e space of sex|monethes, &thorn;e rewle eftir sone sall be exponed til hir of hir|maistres.  And &thorn;an sall sho be examend in &thorn;e chaipitur in|&thorn;e maner be-fore saide.  And giffe sho &yogh;itte abide fully in|hir purpose to hir &yogh;ere ende, &thorn;an on &thorn;e day &thorn;at sho sall be|profest, sho sall be broght in-to &thorn;e chaipitur, &amp; &thorn;e fourte|tyme be examend, as be-fore es rehercede.  And &thorn;an if|sho fully agre hir to &thorn;e beheste &thorn;at sho made before,|Efter &thorn;e gospell on &thorn;e day &thorn;at sho sall be profeste, hir|maistres sall cum til hir &amp; lede hir til &thorn;e gree.  And &thorn;are|sho sall rede hir professiun, The preste &thorn;at singis &thorn;e messe|standand at &thorn;e right corner of &thorn;e auter.  And when sho|hase redde hir profession, hir maistres sall gyffe hir a penne|with ynke, &amp; &thorn;e nouyce sal make a crosse on &thorn;e buke of|hir profession, and sa wende vp to &thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="45a">hee auter, and hir |maistres with hir, &amp; lay it on &thorn;e right ende of &thorn;e auter,|and kys &thorn;e auter, and encline deuotelie, and gange againe|to &thorn;e gree, &amp; singe &thorn;are thrise: "Suscipe me, domine" &amp;c.;|&thorn;e couent, all-way standant in &thorn;are stallis, sall reherce &thorn;e|same again thrise, and "Gloria patri."  &THORN;an &thorn;e nouice|sall prostrate downe be-fore &thorn;e gree, when "Kirieleison,|Christeleison, Kirieleison."  And &thorn;an &thorn;e preste sall say or|sing: "Et ne nos."  "Sed libera nos," sall &thorn;e qwere|answer.  And &thorn;an &thorn;e chantur sall be-gine &thorn;is salme:|"Miserere mei, deus," &thorn;e ta side a verse, &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;ir a-noder,|And "gloria patri," "Sicut."  And when &thorn;is salme es|endit, &thorn;an &thorn;e preste sall cume fra &thorn;e hee awter to|&thorn;e gree, and on hir: "Saluam<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Saluum</I>; cf. p. 144, l. 20, and p. 148, l. 2.</NOTE> fac ancillam tuam."|And &thorn;e qwere sall answer: "Deus meus, sperantem in|te."  And efter sune &thorn;e preste sall singe: "Mitte ei,|domine, auxilium de sancto."  The qwere sall answer:|"Et de sion tuere eam."  &THORN;e preste: "Esto ei, domine,|turris fortitudinis."  &THORN;e qwere: "A facie inimici."  And|&thorn;an &thorn;e preste: "Nichil <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="45b">proficiet inimicus in ea."  And |&thorn;an &thorn;e quere: "Et filius iniquitatis non apponet nocere|ei."  &THORN;e preste: "Domine, deus virtutum, co[n]uerte<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>couerte</I>.</NOTE> nos."|&THORN;e quere: "Et ostende faciem."  &THORN;e preste: "Dominus
<PB N="144">|vobiscum."  &THORN;e quere: "Et cum."  &THORN;e preste: "Oremus."|And &thorn;an he sall say fore colettis oure hir,<NOTE PLACE="foot">After <I>hir</I> nearly half a line is left blank.</NOTE> The nouice|ligand prostrate be &thorn;e gree, And &thorn;e priores and &thorn;e couent|standand in &thorn;er stallis, and &thorn;ar facis turned to &thorn;e autir.|And when &thorn;e collettis are all endid, &thorn;an &thorn;e nouice sall|stand qwil &thorn;e vaile es in halowyng.  And when &thorn;e preste|hase halowid it, thre or fowre of hir sistirs with hir|mastres sall cum oute of &thorn;e qwere &amp; stand a-bowte hir,|qwil hir vales ar in doyng on, All &thorn;e o&thorn;ir remanant of &thorn;e|couent standand in &thorn;are stallis.  &THORN;an, when sho is arayid|vp in hir valis, &thorn;e chantir sall be-ginne solemply &thorn;is hym:|"Veni, creator," &thorn;e quere a verse, &thorn;e to&thorn;ir a-no&thorn;ir.  And in|&thorn;e mene time sall &thorn;e Nouice make hir profession to &thorn;e|priores, kneland on hir kneis, saiand on &thorn;is maner:|"Promitto tibi obedienciam secundum regulam sancti| benedicti."  <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="46a">And &thorn;e priores sais &thorn;an: "Det tibi Deus|uitam eternam."  And on &thorn;e same wise sall sho ga downe|&thorn;e priores side, and syne &thorn;e to&thorn;ir syde.  And when sho sall|cume again, &thorn;are [sall] sho<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;are sho</I>.</NOTE> prostrate and ligge hir downe.|And &thorn;an &thorn;e preste at makis hir sal sai or sing: "Saluam<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Saluum</I>.</NOTE>|fac," "Nichil proficiet," As be-fore es saide, and &thorn;ir|colettis: "Deus, qui caritatis," "Acciones nostras," "Fidelium|deus."  Qwen &thorn;ir thre colettis ar said, &thorn;e priores sall|cume &amp; lede hir til &thorn;e stall, whare sho sal stande, and &thorn;e|preste sall ga to &thorn;e awter and be-gynne &thorn;e crede.  And at|&thorn;is [ah] hir<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;is hir</I>.</NOTE> to be howslid.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="text">
<PB N="145">
<HEAD>V. THE VESPASIAN RITUAL|FOR THE|Ordination of Nuns.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(Cotton MS. Vespasian A. 25, British Museum.)</HEAD>
<HEAD><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="120a">The Method of makeing a Nunn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The heading is in a later hand.  The English text (with some|short Latin expressions) is underlined in red ink.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Here bygyns &thorn;e manere forto make a nun.  At &thorn;e|first be-gynnyng &thorn;e mese salbe of our lady.  &thorn;e|offece of &thorn;e mese sall be "Salue, sancta parens."  &thorn;e|Epistil &amp; &thorn;e godspel &amp; all &thorn;e tother salbe als &thorn;e tyme of|&thorn;e &yogh;er askes.  Att &thorn;e bygynnyng of &thorn;e mese &thorn;e madyn|&thorn;at salbe mayde nun sal sit in &thorn;e quere a-pon a stole be-for|&thorn;e priores stayle with hir prouese in hir hand.  And at &thorn;e|offerand tyme &thorn;e Priores sal lede &thorn;e madyn til &thorn;e toumbe|in-mydes &thorn;e quer, &amp; &thorn;er sal scho betech hir vntil hir next|frendes.  And &thorn;ai sal lede hir vp vnto &thorn;e hegh auter.|And &thorn;e Priores &amp; &thorn;e conuent sal folow vp vnto &thorn;e auter.|And &thorn;en hir frendes sal offer hir vp tyl &thorn;e auter, &amp; &thorn;an|byken hir to &thorn;e priores ogayn.  And &thorn;e same tyme al &thorn;at|wil may offir.  And &thorn;en &thorn;ai al sal sit down &amp; here &thorn;e|preching, And scho with hir professe-boke in hir hand.|And when &thorn;e preching es done, &thorn;e Priores sal hafe hir befor|&thorn;e auter &amp; vncleth hir of hir seculer clething.  And in|&thorn;e same tyme &thorn;e prelet sall halow hir habete with-outyn|note, &thorn;er sayand: "Dominus vob[iscum]!</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="120b">Deus, qui vestimentum salutare et indumentum eterne |iocunditatis tuis fidelibus promisisti, clemenciam|tuam suppliciter exoramus, vt hec indumenta, humilitatem|cordis et contemptum mundi significancia, quibus famula|(-e) tua (-e) N. sancto visibiliter est (sunt) informanda (-e)<NOTE PLACE="foot">25 ff. The|letters and words here placed within parentheses are, in the MS.,|written above (the endings of) the corresponding words.</NOTE>
<PB N="146">|propocito, propicius benedicas, et beate castitatis habitum,|quem te inspirante susceperit (-perint), te protegente|custodiat (-ant).  Per christum dominum nostrum.</P>
<P>Deus, bonarum virtutum dator et omnium benediccionum|largus infusor, exaudi preces nostras, et|hanc (-as) vestem (-es), quam (-as) famula (-e) tua (-e) N.|pro conseruande castitatis signo se ad-operiendam (-das)|exposcit (-cunt), benedicere et sanctificare digneris.  Per|christum.</P>
<P>&THORN;e blissing our &thorn;e vayle: "Dominus vobiscum!</P>
<P>Caput omnium fidelium, deus, et tocius corporis saluator,|hoc (-ec) operimentum (-ta) velaminis (-num),|quod (que) famula (-e) tua (-e) propter tuam tueque genitricis|beatissime sancte semper virginis marie amorem suo|capiti est (sunt) impositura (-re), tua dextera et hoc, quod|per illud (-a) mistice datur intelligi, tua semper custodia|corpore pariter et animo incontaminato custodiat (-ant),|vt quum ad perpetuam sanctorum remuneracionem uenerit|(-int), cum prudentibus virginibus et ipsa (-e) preparata (-e)| te perducente ad <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="121a">perpetue felicitatis nupcias intrare meriatur|(-an-).  Per dominum."</P>
<P>Efter &thorn;eir orisons kast haly watter o-pon &thorn;e clethyng,|and &thorn;an &thorn;e prelete sal gyf &thorn;e madyn hir clethyng: first hir|cote, sayand with-outen note:</P>
<P>"Accipe uestem! indue sanctitatis decorem! ornare|habitu sancte religionis cum timore &amp; reuerencia,|quem interueniente beata dei genitrice Maria cum bonorum|obseruancia operum ignita castitatis lampade suffulta immaculatum|[ante] tribunal<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>maculatum tribunal</I>; cf. p. 147, l. 2.</NOTE> christi perferas.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>perfer/ras</I>;|cf. p. 2, ll. 3, 7, footnotes.</NOTE> Qui viuit et|regnat cum deo patre."</P>
<P>And sythen sal &thorn;e prelete gif hir &thorn;e mantill, sayand:|"Accipe uestem," vt supra.</P>
<P>Efter &thorn;is, &thorn;en sal &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>e</SUP>.</NOTE> prelete with a payr of schers be-gyn|forto kut hir hair befor at &thorn;e toppyng, sayand: "In nomine|patris" &mdash; "et filii,"  behind &mdash; &amp; "spiritus sancti" &mdash;|"Amen," on a&thorn;er side.  And &thorn;en sal &thorn;e priores kut o-way|&thorn;e remnaunt of &thorn;e hair.  And &thorn;en sal &thorn;e prelete gif hir hir|wimpil, sayand:</P>
<P>
<PB N="147">"Accipe peplum sacrum, puella, quod perferas sine|macula ante tribunal domini nostri iesu christi,|cui flectitur omne genu celestium, terrestrium, &amp; infernorum,|in secula seculorum."</P>
<P>And &thorn;an &thorn;e prelete <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="121b">sal lay &thorn;e vayle apon hir hede, |sayand:</P>
<P>"Accipe velum sacrum, puella, quod perferas sine|macula," vt supra.</P>
<P>And &thorn;an sal he gif hir &thorn;e girdyl, sayand: "Accipe|&yogh;onam," &amp;c.;  &THORN;is orison "Accipe" salbe sayd at iij|thynges, &thorn;at es to wit: at &thorn;e gyfyng of &thorn;e wimpil, &amp; of|&thorn;e vayle, &amp; of &thorn;e girdyl, als it es sayd be-for.</P>
<P>Efter &thorn;is sal &thorn;at nun nouece stand stil befor &thorn;e auter &amp;|rede hir prouesse with note, sayand:</P>
<P>"Ego soror N., deo data, promitto stabilitatem meam|et conuersionem morum meorum et obidienciam|secundum regulam sancti Benedicti coram deo &amp; omnibus|sanctis eius in hoc monasterio, quod constructum est in|honorem sancti N., in presencia domne N. priorisse."&mdash;&THORN;e|profession on english: "I sister N., giffyn to god, I|hete my stabilnes &amp; turnyng of my maners &amp; buxsumnes|efter &thorn;e rewle of sant Benett, befor god &amp; all his halows|in &thorn;is mynster, &thorn;at es set in &thorn;e wirchep of sant N., in &thorn;e|presence of daym N. priores."</P>
<P>When scho hase red <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="122a">hir professe, scho sal wend vp to |&thorn;e auter, And lay hir profession-boke a-pon &thorn;e auter, &amp; &thorn;e|ryng with-al.  And &thorn;an &thorn;e priores sal wind or lap &thorn;e|maydyn handes in &thorn;e halowd towel of &thorn;e auter, &amp; &thorn;an sal|&thorn;at nun nouece gay down be-nethen &thorn;e grece of &thorn;e auter,|turnand hir vp vnto &thorn;e auter, standand, &amp; sayand &thorn;is vers|with note: "Suscipe me, domine, secundum eloquium tuum,|et viuam."  And in &thorn;as wordes sayng, sal scho fall down to|&thorn;e erth, And &thorn;an rise vp &amp; turn hir to &thorn;e pepil, sayand:|"Et non confundas me ab exspectacione mea;"  And|lowte; &amp; &thorn;is vers sal scho say iij tymes on &thorn;is maner.|And &thorn;is same vers al &thorn;e congregacion, &thorn;at es to wit, al|&thorn;e conuent, sal answer thris, sayand with-outyn note:|"Suscipe me, domine" &amp;c.; with "Gloria patri;" And &thorn;an|"kyrieleison, christeleison, kyrieleison," "Pater noster."|And &thorn;an sal &thorn;e nun be layd down grofelyng on lenghe befor
<PB N="148">|&thorn;e ryght end of &thorn;e auter.  And &thorn;an &thorn;e prelet sal say|oue[r]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>oue</I>; cf. Notes.</NOTE> hir with note: "Et ne nos," "Saluam (-as) [fac] ancillam<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Saluam (-as) ancillam</I>; cf. p. 143,|l. 29.</NOTE>|(-as) tuam (-as)!  Mitte ei (-is), domine, auxilium de| sancto.  Nichil <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="122b">perficiat inimicus in ea (-is).  Esto ei (-is),|domine, turris fortitudinis.  Domine, exaudi oracionem|meam.  Presta, quesumus, domine, huic (-iis) ancille (-is)|tue (-is) renuncianti (-bus) secularibus pompis gracie tue|ianuas aperire, que despectis mundi illecebris confugit|(-unt) sub titulo christi, uenientem (-es) ad te sereno vultu|suscipere, ne de ea (-is) valeat inimicus triumphare; tribue|ei (-is), quesumus, infatigabile brachium auxilii tui; mentem|eius (-arum) fidei lorica circumda, vt felici muro uallata|(-e) mundum se gaudeat (-ant) euasisse.  Per eundem|dominum nostrum" &amp;c.;&mdash;And &thorn;en sal &thorn;e prelete, kneland|be-for &thorn;e auter, begyn with note &thorn;e yme: "Veni, creator|spiritus."  And &thorn;e quere sal syng &thorn;e same vers to end.|And &thorn;e prelete sal be-gyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>salbe gyn</I>.</NOTE> ilka vers of &thorn;e yme kneland,|&amp; when he hase sayd al &thorn;at vers til end, he sal stand vp|to &thorn;e tyme he begyn a-no&thorn;er vers; &amp; on &thorn;is maner sal he|do til &thorn;e yme<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;e tyme</I>.</NOTE> all be endydde, &amp; &thorn;e quer sal syng &thorn;e|remnant.</P>
<P>"VEni, creator spiritus, mentes tuorum visita, imple|superna gracia que tu creasti pectora, Qui paraclitus|diceris, donum dei."</P>
<P><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="123a">when "veni, creator" es endyd, &thorn;e prelete sal say|ouer hir with note &thorn;er orysons:</P>
<P>"Sancte spiritus, qui te deum ac dominum reuelare|mortalibus dignatus es, immensam tue bonitatis|graciam postulamus, vt sicut ubi-uis spiras, sic &amp; huic|ancille tue affectum deuocionis indulgeas, &amp; que tua sapiencia|est condita, tua quoque prouidencia gubernetur, quam|iuxta consuetam graciam unccio tua de omnibus doceat, et|per intercessionem beatissime dei genitricis Marie eam a|vanitate seculi ueraciter conuerte, &amp; sicut es omnium peccatorum|remissio, deprimentes impietatis obligaciones in ea|dissolue ad obseruanciam sancte castitatis vel virginitatis;|fac eam certatim feruere in tribulacionibus &amp; angustiis;|tua difficiente consolacione valeat respirare, vt sobrie, iuste,
<PB N="149">|&amp; pie, per veram humilitatem atque deuocionem in christi|caritate fundata, quod te donante desiderat felici perseuerancia|compleat in te; cui est honor et gloria cum patre &amp;|filio per omnia secula seculorum.  amen.</P>
<P>Respice, domine propicius, super hanc famulam tuam|N., vt virginitatis sancte propocitum, quod te inspirante|suscepit, te gubernante custodiat.  Per christum|dominum.</P>
<P>Da, qu&aelig;sumus, Omnipotens deus, vt hec famula tua,|que pro spe retribucionis eterne tibi domino desiderat|consecrari, plena fide animoque in <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="123b">sancto propocito |permaneat; tu eam, omnipotens pater, sanctificare et benedicere|et imperpetuum conseruare digneris; tribue ei|humilitatem, castitatem, obedienciam, caritatem, &amp; omnium|bonorum quantitatem.  Da ei, domine, pro operibus gloriam,|pro pudore reuerenciam, pro pudicicia sanctitatem, vt|ad meritum possit glorie peruenire; per christum.</P>
<P>Benedicat te conditor celi et terre, deus, pater omnipotens,|qui te elegere dignatur ad sancte marie|matris domini nostri iesu christi consorcium, vt integram|et inmaculatam virginitatem, quam professa es coram|domino et angelis eius, conserues, propocitum teneas, castitatem|diligas, pacienciam serues, &amp; coronam virginitatis|accipere meriaris; per eundem christum.</P>
<P>Benedicat te deus pater &amp; filius &amp; spiritus sanctus in|omni benediccione spirituali, vt maneas sine macula|sub vestimento marie, matris domini nostri iesu christi.|Per dominum.</P>
<P>Benedicat te &amp; custodiat semper diuina maiestas patris|et filii &amp; spiritus sancti.  Amen."</P>
<P>And &thorn;an cast hali water a-pon hir &amp; encens hir.  And|&thorn;e priores &amp; &thorn;e couent sal &thorn;en go down into &thorn;e qwer in-to|&thorn;er stalles, &amp; &thorn;an sal &thorn;e sub-priores lede &thorn;e &yogh;ong nun to &thorn;e|priores, &amp; scho sal hald vp <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="124a">both hir handes, &amp; &thorn;e priores |sal tak hir handes be-twene hir handes &amp; kis hir, &amp; swa|sal scho mak hir obedience, &amp; swa forth til al &thorn;e couent, &amp;|&thorn;an sall scho be set in &thorn;e vttermest stale in &thorn;e quer, vnto|&thorn;e "Agnus dei" of &thorn;e mese be down, &amp; &thorn;en sal &thorn;e subpriores|lede hir vp to &thorn;e auter; &amp; qwen &thorn;e prelete hase|vsede &amp; rineside, &thorn;an sal scho be howseld of hym, &amp; &thorn;an
<PB N="150">|sal &thorn;e quer sing &thorn;e comune of &thorn;e mese, &amp; &thorn;en sal &thorn;e subpriores|lede hir be-for &thorn;e lady auter, &amp; &thorn;air sal scho sit in hir|prayers vnto &thorn;e mete-tym.  &amp; &thorn;es iij days sal scho not|spek vnto &thorn;e iiij day, &thorn;at scho hafe leue of &thorn;e priores.|And at euyn, when scho es in hir bede, &thorn;e priores &amp; &thorn;e|couent sal cum vp in-to &thorn;e dortour, &amp; &thorn;e prest &amp; &thorn;e clerk|with torch-lyght forto halow hir bed; &amp; he sal say|withoutyn note: "Ecce, non dormitabit neque dormitet|Dominus vobiscum.</P>
<P>Benedic, domine, hoc famularum tuarum dormitorium,|qui non dormis neque dormitas, qui custodis israel;|famulam tuam in hac domo quiescentem post laborem custodi|ab illusionibus, fantasmatis sathane, vt vigilans in|preceptis tuis meditetur, dormiens te per saporem senciat,| &amp; hic &amp; vbique defensionis<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="124b"> tue auxilio muniatur, Per|dominum nostrum."</P>
<P>And efter &thorn;is orison sal he say "In principio"; &amp; when|&thorn;at es sayd, &thorn;en sal he kest haly water, &amp; encence hir &amp; &thorn;e|bede, &amp; &thorn;e ij nyghtes efter &thorn;e conuent sal do &thorn;e same.</P><TRAILER>//Amen.//<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Here follows, in a later hand, a Latin prayer</I>, Benediccio|Annule.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="notes">
<PB N="151">
<HEAD>NOTES.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version notes">
<HEAD>NORTHERN PROSE VERSION.</HEAD>
<LIST>
<LABEL>1/14-16.</LABEL><ITEM>THE negations, being double, have got out of gear.  Lat. <I>ut|non solum ut iratus pater suos non aliquando filios exheredet, sed nec ut|metuendus dominus .. tradat</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2/13.</LABEL><ITEM><I>&thorn;aim</I>, probably referring to <I>lippis</I>: "that thy life may follow|thy lips."  Cf. <I>sey euer the trouth in herte &amp; mouth</I>, 122/2.  But the Lat.|has: <I>inquire pacem et sequere eam</I>; the Common Version: <I>sec sibbe and|hyre &yogh;efol&yogh;a</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>3/31-4/1.</LABEL><ITEM>The passage is poetical (Introd. &sect; 3) and deviates from the|original text.  Perhaps <I>&thorn;are may help &thorn;e here to</I> is a corruption of <I>&thorn;at|&thorn;are may help &thorn;e, here do!</I> = Lat. <I>agendum est modo quod in perpetuum|nobis expediat</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>4/4.</LABEL><ITEM><I>stresce</I>; thus I read the MS.  It is well known that <I>st</I> and <I>sc</I> are|easily confused (as <I>storid</I> for <I>scorid</I>, p. 153, l. 10).  Is not Halliwell's|<I>streste</I> due to a mistake?</ITEM>
<LABEL>4/24.</LABEL><ITEM>"So must be said of them as of the gold that thou mayst see,|which .."</ITEM>
<LABEL>4/29.</LABEL><ITEM>"who neither want to be resident&mdash;but to go from place to|place do they want&mdash;nor stay long (at each temporary abode)."</ITEM>
<LABEL>6/1.</LABEL><ITEM>"For need's sake he may place one before another as to reverence|(due to them), if he does not wish to have (or keep) each one in his|order, as he takes it."</ITEM>
<LABEL>7/3.</LABEL><ITEM><I>of litil oresun</I>, "unable to pray much (and eloquently)."  But|the Lat. has: <I>ne causetur de minori forte substantia</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>7/8.</LABEL><ITEM><I>Nichil de-esse</I>; the Lat. text: <I>Nihil deest timentibus eum</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>7/23.</LABEL><ITEM>"let her keep to the one which is best."</ITEM>
<LABEL>7/30.</LABEL><ITEM>Lat. <I>omnes magistram sequantur regulam</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>7/32.</LABEL><ITEM><I>Yef any sal take discipline, gruching sal sho make nane</I>.  But|the Lat. has: <I>quod si presumpserit quisquam, disciplinae regulari subjaceat</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>10/26.</LABEL><ITEM>An addition like "yea, it beseems you" would be quite in the|style of the rule; see Introd. &sect; 138.  Another possibility: <I>for &thorn;i sal tu|quite &thorn;e wid scrift, ye[f] it bi-timis yu</I>; cf. 17/6.</ITEM>
<LABEL>13/13-15.</LABEL><ITEM>Lat. <I>Probasti nos, inquit, deus, igne nos examinasti, sicut|examinatur argentum; induxisti nos in laqueum, posuisti tribulationes in|dorso nostro</I>.  Thus <I>laqueum</I> is the Lat. word apparently corresponding|to <I>lay</I>, and the latter may be a corruption of <I>las</I>, "snare." Cf. Introd. &sect; 45.</ITEM>
<LABEL>13/21.</LABEL><ITEM><I>weris taim</I>, "wears them" (i. e. the mantles).  The whole|passage is quite different from the original text: <I>auferenti tunicam dimittunt|et pallium</I>, etc. (cf. Luke vi. 29).</ITEM>
<LABEL>14/32.</LABEL><ITEM><I>and helpis noht</I>, "and is no use."</ITEM>
<LABEL>15/29 ff.</LABEL><ITEM>The Lat. rule speaks of vigils (2 a.m.), a short interval,|matins (at day-break).  Here: night-service, a short interval, work at|day-break.</ITEM>
<LABEL>16/30.</LABEL><ITEM>"in that same above-mentioned order."
<PB N="152"></ITEM>
<LABEL>17/10.</LABEL><ITEM><I>feste-dais .. sexe salmis</I>.  But the Lat. has: <I>dominico die ..|sexagesimus sextus psalmus.</I></ITEM>
<LABEL>18/6.</LABEL><ITEM>And (MS. <I>At</I>) <I>o niht ryse</I>, Lat. <I>et nocte surgamus</I>.  Seven <I>at</I>'s|before in those two lines!</ITEM>
<LABEL>18/10 ff.</LABEL><ITEM>Thus: 1. the verse "Deus," 2. the hymn, 3. three psalms, 4.|a lesson, etc.&mdash;For <I>te salme</I> the Lat. has: <I>psalmi</I> (pl.).</ITEM>
<LABEL>18/30-33.</LABEL><ITEM>Not in the original.  Cf. Luther's "Winkelmesse."</ITEM>
<LABEL>19/31.</LABEL><ITEM>Where the Lat. rule makes an exception for <I>affectu inspirationis</I>,|this version puts <I>mis-trouz</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>24/31.</LABEL><ITEM>"and for utensils and other things she shall provide such of|whose life and deed she is sure."  Cf. 128/29 ff.</ITEM>
<LABEL>25/27.</LABEL><ITEM>"To the needy shall she (i. e. the sound sister who gives)|humble herself in their illness, and she (i. e. the sick sister) shall not.."</ITEM>
<LABEL>30/9.</LABEL><ITEM><I>&thorn;e gloria patri of &thorn;e Venite</I>, the "Glory be to the Father," etc.,|which is sung after the 94th psalm.</ITEM>
<LABEL>35/6.</LABEL><ITEM><I>Alle .. And</I>; Lat. <I>omnibus congruus honor exibeatur, maxime|domesticis fidei et peregrinis</I>.  Cf. p. 102, l. 1929.</ITEM>
<LABEL>35/13.</LABEL><ITEM><I>alure</I> is a suspicious form.  Murray, under the verb <I>allure</I>,|quotes: <I>God's love alure</I> (1616), <I>alluring the mercy of God</I> (1622).  Thus,|certainly, it does not seem altogether impossible that the idea of|worship, expressed by <I>anure</I> (Lat. <I>honorare</I>) and <I>aure</I> (Lat. <I>adorare</I>)|was, at an early period, associated with the verb <I>alure</I>.  But the|expression <I>ou&thorn;ir wid &thorn;e heuidis ou&thorn;ir wid al &thorn;e bodi</I> would go better|with an <I>alute</I>, "bow down in deference or worship"; the Lat. has:|<I>inclinato capite vel prostrato toto corpore in terram</I>; and, as is well|known, the letters t and r were easily confused (cf. 2/27).  A third|possibility is the assumption of a simple blunder for <I>anure</I> or <I>aure</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>36/20.</LABEL><ITEM><I>In caald cuntre es nede of warmer hend</I> makes the impression|of being a proverbial saying.  The Lat. has: <I>in frigidis regionibus|amplius indigetur</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>38/39.</LABEL><ITEM><I>&thorn;at sho</I>, etc.  The Lat. conveys quite a different thought: <I>ut|si aliquando suadente diabolo consenserit, ut egrediatur de monasterio,|quod absit, tunc exuta rebus monasterii proitiatur</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>39/18.</LABEL><ITEM><I>Sain Benet hauis te sperance of &thorn;o&thorn;ir</I> means essentially the|same as the Lat. <I>quod absit</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>39/21.</LABEL><ITEM><I>&thorn;at we</I>, etc., i. e. that we may act up to our high calling, our|relatives having offered us to God.</ITEM>
<LABEL>39/34.</LABEL><ITEM><I>Yef &thorn;ar</I>, etc.  Here our version, or its pattern, deals rather|freely with the original text.</ITEM>
<LABEL>40/6.</LABEL><ITEM><I>hym-selfe, He</I>, erroneous masculine forms (Introd. &sect; 6).</ITEM>
<LABEL>40/18.</LABEL><ITEM>Possibly an original <I>swilk</I> was misread as <I>hvilk</I> and changed|into <I>whilk</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>42/16.</LABEL><ITEM>"that she may refer, for testimony, both to the New and to|the Old Testament."</ITEM>
<LABEL>42/25.</LABEL><ITEM><I>beli pipe</I> answers to the Lat. <I>calamum quassatum</I> (Common|Version: <I>tocwysede hreod</I>), but it is hard to account for the form.  A|participle like <I>berid</I>, beaten, bruised, would seem acceptable.  Or has|<I>beli-pipe</I>, "bag-pipe" (not in N.E.D.), been introduced through some|misunderstanding?</ITEM>
<LABEL>43/6.</LABEL><ITEM><I>&thorn;at gafe</I>, etc., Lat. <I>qui erogavit triticum conservis suis in|tempore suo</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>43/18.</LABEL><ITEM>Lat. <I>materia ei datur superbiendi</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>47/19.</LABEL><ITEM>"For holy men, who lead a good life . . , such things may|support (be a help to keep) this life."</ITEM></LIST>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version notes">
<PB N="153">
<HEAD>NORTHERN METRICAL VERSION.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(B. = B&ouml;ddeker; H. = Holthausen; K. = K&ouml;lbing; cf. Introd. &sect; 1, F.)</HEAD>
<P>I commence by giving a list of erroneous readings left uncorrected by|K.: sely 1, here 116 ('123'), hafs 150 ('159,' in the note), amendes 204|('215'), Commers in &thorn;e kingdom 250 ('262'), lighth 301 ('314'), folc 406|('424'), &thorn;e 509 ('529'), ne 569 ('591'), honour 673 ('698'), bocksum 682|('707'), te 883 ('918'), asaide 954 ('991'), haly 991 ('1028'), deuocion|1191 ('1235'), nunces 1209 ('1253'), chastyng 1244 ('1289'), That 1262|('1306'), fast 1265 ('1309'), chastisyng 1356 ('1401'), omission of: id <I>est</I>|1360b ('1406'), celararii 1420b ('1467'), storid 1536 ('1589'), witsununday|1703 ('1764'), seruise 1896 ('1959'), wer 1997 ('2063'), hir mayne 2141|('2210'), chaisted 2456 ('2533').</P>
<P>Some of these errors, and others not mentioned here, are of a more or|less harmless nature.  But sense and construction, and statements in|grammars, essays, and dictionaries, are concerned when a text offers <I>sely</I>|for <I>lely</I>, <I>commers</I> for <I>comuners</I>, <I>lighth</I> for <I>lightli</I>, <I>ne</I> for <I>not</I>, <I>bocksum</I> (!) for|<I>bowsum</I>, <I>nunces</I> for <I>nouices</I>, <I>That</I> for <I>what</I>, <I>fast</I> for <I>tast</I>, <I>storid</I> for <I>scorid</I>,|<I>wer</I> for <I>whor</I>, etc.</P>
<P>Fresh errors introduced by the collator: Thurch 34 ('35'; B. is right;|the 't' is distinct enough both here, in l. 39, and other places), fulfillyd 78|('82'), gudenes 160 ('169'; see below), Ne 570 ('592'), awm 712|('737'; for B.'s 'awn'; both are wrong), it ho 890 ('925'; certainly|'who,' as B. prints it, although not unlike 'it ho'), fonne 1078 ('1117';|for B.'s fone; both are wrong), mihi 1098b, 1312b ('1138b, 1357b'),|Subpriores 1553 ('1607'), III 1576 ('1631'; see below), &amp; &yogh;apli 1674|('1733'; it is B.'s '&amp; apli,' not his 'apli,' that is to be corrected into '&yogh;apli'),|loquantur 1728b ('1790'; see below), &thorn;am 1736 ('1798'; B. is right),|modo 1802b ('1865b'), Sicut (the first letter is n o t totally red; it is black|with a perpendicular red stroke through it), 2154 ('2224').</P>
<P>Part of the inaccuracies and errors mentioned in these lists are due to|inadvertency.  Others&mdash;the majority &mdash; were deliberately accepted or|advanced.</P>
<P>I may add that K. corrects B.'s &thorn;erfourn into parfourn 224 ('236'),|but parfection into perfeccion 2486 ('2564').</P>
<LIST>
<LABEL>30 ('31').</LABEL><ITEM>'<I>&thorn;i</I>, ms. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>i</SUP> (= <I>&thorn;ai</I>).'  B.  Of course <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>i</SUP> means <I>&thorn;i</I>, and|nothing else; cf. p. 48, footnote.</ITEM>
<LABEL>55 ('56').</LABEL><ITEM>B. punctuates: <I>&THORN;e whylk yf &thorn;ay dyde, wele myght wend</I>,|and adds the explanation: '<I>dyde</I>, i. e. be worthy.'  Similar specimens of|B.'s punctuation are to be found in 267 ('280'), 373 ('390'), 422-424|('440-442'), 452 ('471') 1159 ('1202'), 1531 ('1584') ff., 1586 ('1641')|ff., etc.  Some others have been corrected by H.</ITEM>
<LABEL>97 ('103').</LABEL><ITEM>'<I>Als so say</I>, der sage es.' B.  I render the line: "I am|desirous, also, to speak of him."</ITEM>
<LABEL>129 ('136').</LABEL><ITEM>B. substitutes <I>we</I> for <I>he</I>.  In either case the pron. must|refer to the man who wishes to be saved.</ITEM>
<LABEL>145-146 ('154-155').</LABEL><ITEM>B. puts the comma after <I>noy</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>159-160.</LABEL><ITEM><P>The lines may, as also H. suggests, have run something like|this: <I>For th&uacute;rth oure m&iacute;ghtes m&oacute;r no m&yacute;n M&aacute;y we n&oacute;nekyns g&uacute;de beg&yacute;n</I>.|K. declares that the MS. has <I>gudenes</I> and that H.'s emendation thus 'sich|erledigt.'  But there is not even the slightest trace of another syllable after|<I>gude</I>; and as B. saw the MS. in 1872, K. in 1896, the whole thing appears|somewhat mysterious.  Nor could I accept K.'s reading even as an emendation;|it is not supported by the evidence of the text itself.  For <I>gudenes</I>|is not used anywhere else in the whole version, whereas <I>gude</I> occurs substantively
<PB N="154">|twice on the same leaf (of my print): ll. 109 and 168, the latter|passage answering very closely to the line in question.  And the words|<I>alkin(e)s, alkin (-kyn), nokins, whatkyn</I>, in all the nine instances in which|they occur, are accentuated &mdash;&breve;, followed as they are by a monosyllabic|word (usually a rhyme-word).</P><P>The collocations <I>mor no min, mor or les</I>, etc., gradually wore down|into mere expletives, or nearly so.  Partly on this account, it is sometimes|hard to decide whether the words should be looked on as pure adjectives,|as adjectives used substantively, or as adverbs.</P></ITEM>
<LABEL>275 ('288').</LABEL><ITEM>'<I>mekli</I> . ., lies <I>mekil</I>.' H.  See Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>331 ('345').</LABEL><ITEM>[<I>in</I>] <I>werld</I>. B.  But see Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>334b.</LABEL><ITEM>Properly <I>spiritum adopcionis</I> (Rom. viii. 15); but to judge from|<I>gaste of mede</I>, the corruption must have been already in the copy used|by the author.</ITEM>
<LABEL>340 ('355').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>&thorn;er</I> . . st. <I>&yogh;er</I>.' H.  But see Introd. &sect; 58, 1 (&sect; 59, 1).</ITEM>
<LABEL>372 ('389').</LABEL><ITEM>'das verbum <I>be</I> fehlt vor oder hinter <I>dampned</I>.' H.|True in a sense.  But see Introd. &sect; 128.</ITEM>
<LABEL>459 ('478').</LABEL><ITEM>B. substitutes <I>let</I> for <I>set</I>.  But see Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>588 ('610').</LABEL><ITEM>Lat. <I>nihil amori Christi preponere</I>; Common Version:|<I>nan &thorn;ing beforan Cristes lufe settan</I>.  B. supplies: [god].</ITEM>
<LABEL>592.</LABEL><ITEM><I>for to sake</I>, possibly for original <I>to forsake</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>627.</LABEL><ITEM><I>praers</I> can hardly be explained as the direct object of <I>schriue</I>,|the pronoun <I>vs</I> in such a case being the indirect object: "and prayers to|God we should prescribe for ourselves as penance."  Such a construction|of the verb is not recorded elsewhere (as far as my knowledge goes).|In all probability the original had <I>In</I>.  As <I>in</I> was also a worn-down form|of the conj. <I>and</I> (2007, 2260), and the whole passage (607 ff.) is full of|<I>and</I>'s, the substitution of <I>And</I> for <I>In</I> seems easily accounted for.  Thus|properly: "In prayers to God we should confess (and take penance)."|B. makes the same emendation.</ITEM>
<LABEL>677 ('702').</LABEL><ITEM>'Der text ist wahrscheinlich zum theil corrumpirt.'|B.  'Die verderbniss des textes ist leicht zu beseitigen, wenn wir . . <I>And</I>|streichen.' H.  <I>And</I>, however, can be satisfactorily explained (whether|used by the poet, or added by a scribe).  In Northern languages, the|corresponding <I>och</I> (&aring;', etc.) is freely used after an adj. or a quality-noun|to introduce the expression for that in which the quality consists, or what|it concerns: <I>han hade den v&auml;nligheten &aring;' komma</I> (he had the kindness to|come); <I>jag var f&auml;rdig &aring;' gr&aring;ta</I> (I was on the point of crying).  And in|our texts, p. 44, ll. 20-21, we actually find: <I>&thorn;at &thorn;ai . . alle timis finde|hir redi and speke with &thorn;aim</I>.  This sentence might, with a different word-order,|easily have turned into: <I>redi and with &thorn;aim (for) to speke</I>.  Thus, in|677, <I>And . . to</I> is practically the same as "to," and from our point of view|we may term it pleonastic.  But that, I believe, is all.</ITEM>
<LABEL>699.</LABEL><ITEM>I am not certain of this <I>bown</I>.  Cf. however 317-318.</ITEM>
<LABEL>796.</LABEL><ITEM><I>mekenes</I> is the subject (misunderstood by B. in Engl. Stud. ii,|p. 364).</ITEM>
<LABEL>801.</LABEL><ITEM>Even if <I>crakes</I> might have been tolerably understood as "talks,"|"tales" (?), there is not the smallest doubt but it is a corruption of <I>clerkes</I>.|<I>Als clerkes tels</I> is, like <I>who likes to loke</I>, etc., one of those favourite phrases|which, with various modifications (cf. 2459, 773, 461, 858, 836), were used|in medi&aelig;val poetry both to give a stamp of authority to the exposition and|to supply a convenient rhyme.  The latter object is served by phrases like|<I>in feld and town, arely and late, be day and night, loud and still</I>, which also|meet us so often here and elsewhere.  Cf. J. Ullmann's treatise on Richard|Rolle de Hampole in Engl. Stud. vii, pp. 415 ff. (specially pp. 428-454).
<PB N="155"></ITEM>
<LABEL>867.</LABEL><ITEM><I>in &yogh;arning</I> (MS.) would certainly give some sense: even before|it has become a thought or deed.  Yet the alteration, made also by B., is|probably right.</ITEM>
<LABEL>897.</LABEL><ITEM>I might have mentioned that the two words <I>&thorn;at hase</I> in 896|were thoughtlessly repeated after <I>fader</I>, but immediately crossed out|again.</ITEM>
<LABEL>915.</LABEL><ITEM>To supply the missing line is out of the question.  It may have|conveyed a thought like: <I>For &thorn;i he shewed swilk bowsumnes</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>924 ('959').</LABEL><ITEM>'wir haben ohne zweifel f&uuml;r &thorn;ai einzuf&uuml;hren &thorn;am.' B.|(Eng. Stud. ii, p. 360).  But see Introd. &sect;&sect; 37, 114.</ITEM>
<LABEL>929 ('964').</LABEL><ITEM>On account of the preceding <I>&thorn;ai, &thorn;er, &thorn;am</I>, 'ist auch hier|<I>&thorn;er</I> statt <I>our</I> einzusetzen.'  H.  But see Introd. &sect; 138.</ITEM>
<LABEL>938, 940 ('974, 976').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>sofferand</I> st. <I>souerand</I>.' H.  But cf. Introd.|&sect;&sect; 55, 89, 90, and <I>vnsouerable</I>, Wallace, ed. Jamieson, l. 267, etc.</ITEM>
<LABEL>942.</LABEL><ITEM>The line has fared badly:<I> r &thorn;i sake for</I> is written on an erasure,|<I>r sa e fo</I> being much blurred; <I>to</I> is squeezed in afterwards between <I>for</I> and|<I>be</I>; traces of the old letters are left.  In its present shape, it is cumbrously|long.  <I>Al (&thorn;e) d&aacute;y for &thorn;&iacute; sake t&oacute; be sl&aacute;yn</I> would run smoothly.</ITEM>
<LABEL>965 ('1002').</LABEL><ITEM>'<I>o bouen</I> [<I>vs</I>].' B.</ITEM>
<LABEL>972 ('1008').</LABEL><ITEM>'Vor <I>o&thorn;er</I> fehlt offenbar <I>&thorn;at</I> oder <I>&thorn;et</I>.' H.  But cf.|Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1045 ('1084').</LABEL><ITEM>'nach dem beispiele, das zu ersehen ist an denjenigen.'|B.  Misconstruction.  See Introd. &sect; 135.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1070 ('1109').</LABEL><ITEM>B., misunderstanding the function of <I>laghter</I>, transposes|<I>at</I> and <I>be</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1126 ('1167').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>be</I> st. <I>bi</I>.' H.  But cf. Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1131 ('1172').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>&thorn;e</I> statt des ersten <I>al</I>.' H.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1172 ff.</LABEL><ITEM>The lines give fairly good sense without an alteration: "since|we may see (from Scripture), that everything we do," etc.  Nevertheless|it is not unlikely that the first <I>we</I>, as H. suggests, stands in the place of|an original <I>&thorn;ai</I>: "since they can see all that we do."</ITEM>
<LABEL>1221 ('1265').</LABEL><ITEM>'erg&auml;nze <I>&thorn;ai</I> vor <I>vse</I>.' H.  This does not improve the|metre (cf. 1829).  Yet it may be right.  In both the lines (605 and 1221)|where I wish to explain <I>no</I> as "none" (like <I>a</I> = "an"), something may be|omitted.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1198b ('1242b').</LABEL><ITEM>What I expand as <I>Quomodo sanctimonialles</I>, K.|explains as <I>Quod singillatim</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1253-54.</LABEL><ITEM>The omitted line may as well have been the first in the|pair, <I>for</I> being wrong for <I>fro</I>, like in 1259, etc.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1266 ('1310').</LABEL><ITEM>'<I>fullyng</I> zu mlat. <I>fullare</I>, neuengl. <I>to full</I>.' B.  But see|Glossary, and Introd. &sect; 99.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1269 ff.</LABEL><ITEM>Although <I>comyn</I> might be, and might have been, taken for|an adj. ("familiar," "communicating") and <I>cum</I> for a participle, I believe,|like B., that <I>If</I> is omitted: "If a nun .. communes .. or comes."  Lat.|<I>Si qua soror presumpserit</I>; Winteney Version: <I>Gyf hwilc swuster ..|&yogh;edyrstl&aelig;c&eth;</I>.  In a prior copy, a blank had probably been left for the|word; cf. 2179 and the footnotes on 923, 2151, 2481.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1306 ('1351').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>arest</I> (=<I>arested</I>) st. <I>warest</I>.' H.  But see Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1317 ('1362').</LABEL><ITEM>K. corrects B.'s <I>found</I>, but puts a (!) after <I>faund</I>, thus|appearing to misunderstand the word.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1403.</LABEL><ITEM><I>Or els</I> regularly means "or else;" thus: "or else rebellious|rise against her."  But it is tempting to compare the line with 440: "or|as a rebel rise against her."  Then <I>els</I> would be a corruption, or possibly|a weakened form, of <I>als</I>; cf. <I>es</I> (8/3) = <I>as</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1434 ('1481').</LABEL><ITEM>The end of the line, where all the letters stand rather
<PB N="156">|far apart, may be transcribed <I>her to</I>, as I have done, or <I>herto</I>, as B. did.|But the sense is "to her," not "hereto."</ITEM>
<LABEL>1457 ('1506').</LABEL><ITEM>B. substitutes <I>serue</I> for <I>saue</I>.  Uncalled for.&mdash;B. prints|<I>selu</I>, K. says the MS. has <I>seln</I>.  It is quite true that the last character|looks like an n.  However, if K. had compared it e.g. with the fourth letter|in <I>wayue</I> 444, he would have found that the last-mentioned letter has the|same claims on being rendered by an n.  But the word being a rhyme-word,|K. silently put u.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1468.</LABEL><ITEM>In M.V. <I>what so</I> means "whatever;" in P.V. the same words|would have meant "what she."  The latter signification suits the context|much better and probably belonged to the original metrical text.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1476 ('1526').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>&thorn;e enournmentes</I>.' H.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1490 ('1540').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>er</I> st. <I>es</I>.' H.  But see Glossaries.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1517 ('1568').</LABEL><ITEM>For B.'s erroneous <I>falted</I> H. substitutes <I>failed</I>.  K.|states that the MS. has <I>falled</I> and accepts H.'s emendation.  Cf. however|Introd. &sect;&sect; 78, 99.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1576 ('1631').</LABEL><ITEM>B. correctly prints <I>in like</I>.  K. declares the MS. has|<I>III like</I>, and refers to the Lat. <I>addatur et tercium</I>!  Cf. ll. 408, 1635.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1633 ('1691').</LABEL><ITEM>B. expands <I>leuerty</I>, which is impossible.  The omission|of a syllable (cf. 142/8) need not be supposed either.  The meaning is, that|they should not possess anything, but rather receive what is|necessary to each one.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1728b ('1790').</LABEL><ITEM>B.'s reading, loquatur, is wrong, K.'s is impossible.|But I wavered between loq<I>ua</I>nt<I>ur</I> and loqu<I>an</I>t<I>ur</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1756 ('1818').</LABEL><ITEM>K. thinks <I>day</I> was altered into <I>&thorn;ay</I>.  I admit that this|would appear more natural.  But the d-part of the hybrid character is|written with specially black, bold strokes, as if intended to predominate.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1780 ('1843').</LABEL><ITEM>'erg&auml;nze <I>be</I> vor <I>ianglyng</I>.' H.  See my note on 372.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1868-70.</LABEL><ITEM>The Lat. text mentions no other hour than <I>terciam</I> and|<I>decimam</I>.  Line 1780 seems as weak as <I>in Descember</I> 1121.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1878 ('1941').</LABEL><ITEM>'erg&auml;nze <I>be</I> vor <I>writ</I>.' H.  I would rather insert it|before the participle.  Cf. Introd. &sect; 128, end.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1890 ('1953').</LABEL><ITEM>'<I>&thorn;ai s</I> ist wol zu streichen.' H.  This would be a metrical|disimprovement.  And cf. passages mentioned in Introd. &sect; 138.</ITEM>
<LABEL>1929.</LABEL><ITEM>"who are known to be pilgrims."</ITEM>
<LABEL>1968.</LABEL><ITEM>The line corresponds to <I>in medio templi tui</I> 1966b,<I> I-middis ti|tempil</I> 35/24.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2008 ('2074').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>Less</I> st. <I>Sich</I>, vgl. das original: <I>in calidis uero|minus</I>.'  H.  Cf. Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2027 ('2093').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>wend</I>.' H.  Cf. Introd. &sect; 60, 2.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2076. ('2145')</LABEL><ITEM>'erg&auml;nze <I>men</I>, man, vor <I>hir</I>.' H.  I have substituted|<I>&thorn;ai</I> for <I>&thorn;at</I>.  My supposition is that the original had the shorter conjunctional|phrase <I>Or tyme</I>, followed by the pron. <I>&thorn;ai</I>.  Equivalent to <I>or tyme</I>,|and just as common, was the fuller <I>or tyme &thorn;at</I> (2286), analogously to|<I>fro time</I> (2201) and <I>fro time &thorn;at</I> (1719), <I>do wilis</I> (2/7) and <I>to whilis &thorn;at</I>|(40/29, 33).  Thus the slip was easily made.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2190 ('2262').</LABEL><ITEM>'lies <I>lay</I> st. <I>law</I>.' H.  Cf. Introd. &sect; 41, and Glossary.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2354 ('2430').</LABEL><ITEM>B. incorrectly substitutes <I>as</I> for <I>at</I>.</ITEM>
<LABEL>2346 ('2421').</LABEL><ITEM>'B. &auml;ndert <I>strengh in</I> zu <I>strengthen</I>, was aber gar|keinen sinn giebt.  Es is einfach <I>&thorn;am</I> vor <I>in</I> einzuschieben.' H.  <I>&thorn;am</I> is|very acceptable, but does not seem quite necessary: "then God shall|grant strength in their deed."</ITEM>
<LABEL>2385 ('2462').</LABEL><ITEM>'<I>to play</I> giebt in diesem zusammenhange keinen rechten|sinn.  Ich vermute, dass <I>to play</I> f&uuml;r urspr&uuml;ngliches <I>o-way</I> geschrieben|ist.' H.  But cf. the opening lines of the chapter, and the statement in
<PB N="157">|W. Dugdale's Monasticon Anglicanum, vol. ii, p. 474a (London 1846),|that a lady superior was allowed 'to go out of the monastery to one of|her manors, to take the air and divert herself.'</ITEM>
<LABEL>2432.</LABEL><ITEM>Cf. Introd. &sect; 136.</ITEM></LIST>
</DIV2>
